{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in El Salvador", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in El Salvador}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in El Salvador\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[El Salvador]]\n| first_case      = [[Metap\u00e1n]], [[Santa Ana Department|Santa Ana]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/19/c_138894937.htm|title=El Salvador registers 1st COVID-19 case|agency=Xinhuanet |date= 19 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n| arrival_date    = 18 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=18|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 2<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 41<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = 10<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://covid19.gob.sv/ Official Statistics - Government of El Salvador]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[El Salvador]] on 18 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Redacci\u00f3n|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-51956420|title=Nicaragua y El Salvador confirman los primeros casos del nuevo coronavirus|date=2020-03-20|work=BBC News Mundo|access-date=2020-03-26|language=es}}</ref> As of 1 April 2020, El Salvador reported 41 cases, 2 deaths and 0 recovery.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sosa|first=Eduardo|url=https://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/nacional/covid-19-el-salvador-coronavirus-positivos/700739/2020/|title=A 24 sube la cifra de contagios por coronavirus en El Salvador|date=28 March 2020|work=El Diario de Hoy|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Carranza|first2=Enrique}}</ref> As of that date El Salvador had arrested more people for violating the quarantine than it had diagnosed cases of COVID-19, a total of 712 people had been arrested for violating quarantine orders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March 2020, the first COVID-19 death in [[El Salvador]] was confirmed, followed by a second death on 1 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/el-salvador-registers-countrys-first-coronavirus-death|title=El Salvador registers country's first coronavirus death|agency=National Post |date= 31 March 2020 |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/nacional/coronavirus-segunda-muerte-hospital-saldana-el-salvador/701914/2020/|title=Un hombre de 89 a\u00f1os es la segunda muerte por coronavirus en El Salvador|agency=El Diario de Hoy |date= 1 April 2020 |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n__TOC__\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== March ===\nOn 11 March, after the [[World Health Organization]] classified COVID-19 as a pandemic, President [[Nayib Bukele]] declared suspension of all educative activities in public and private schools all over the country for 21 days, followed by a solicitude to the [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador|Legislative Assembly]] of declaring [[state of emergency]] and [[state of exception]], in spite of not having any [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] confirmed cases.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/es/20200314-covid19-el-salvador-nayib-bukele-am%C3%A9rica-latina|title=Sin casos confirmados de Covid-19, El Salvador emprende dr\u00e1sticas acciones para afrontar pandemia|last=|first=|date=2020-03-14|website=[[France 24]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The Office of the Attorney for the Defense of Human Rights of El Salvador head, Apolonio Tobar, considered the actions taken by the government as \"improvised\". On 13 March, Bukele declared a [[Alert state|red alert]] on the country.<ref name=\":0\" /> As the night of 14 March, both [[Decree|decrees]] were approved, declaring state of emergency for 30 days and state of exception for 15 days, accompanied by prohibition of people circulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/america/sociedad/el-salvador-decreta-estado-de-excepcion-para-enfrentar-la-pandemia-del-covid-19/20000013-4196124|title=El Salvador decreta el estado de excepci\u00f3n para enfrentar la pandemia del COVID-19|last=L\u00f3pez|first=Enrique|date=March 15, 2020|website=[[EFE]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanoticias.com/a/elsalvador-coronavirus-emergencia/5329152.html|title=El Salvador declara el estado de emergencia para enfrentar COVID-19|last=|first=|date=March 14, 2020|website=[[Voice of America|Voz de Am\u00e9rica]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nA diplomatic dispute between El Salvador and [[Mexico]] developed when President Bukele accused [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico|Mexico]] of allowing a dozen people with COVID-19 to board a plane bound for [[El Salvador International Airport]] on 16 March. Mexican deputy health minister [[Hugo Lopez-Gatell]] denied the charge, and tests showed the individuals in question were virus-free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/el-salvador-accuses-mexico-sending-223043717.html|title=Mexico rejects El Salvador accusation it let coronavirus patients board plane|last=Renteria|first=Nelson|last2=Frank Jack|first2=Daniel|date=16 March 2020|work=Yahoo News|location=[[Mexico City]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, President Bukele announced the first confirmed case of COVID-19 in El Salvador, which was detected in the Hospital Nacional General \"Arturo Morales\", in [[Metap\u00e1n]]. The case was identified as a male and according to the General Direction of Migration and Foreigners (''Direcci\u00f3n General de Migraci\u00f3n y Extranjer\u00eda'') he was in Italy, where pressumably he was infected<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laprensagrafica.com/elsalvador/Lo-que-se-sabe-y-lo-que-no-sobre-el-primer-infectado-con-coronavirus-en-El-Salvador-20200319-0074.html|title=Lo que se sabe (y lo que no) sobre el primer infectado con coronavirus en El Salvador|last=Calder\u00f3n|first=Beatriz|date=March 19, 2020|website=[[La Prensa Gr\u00e1fica]]|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.laprensagrafica.com/elsalvador/EN-VIVO-El-Salvador-confirma-primer-caso-de-COVID-19-20200318-0064.html |title=Primer caso de COVID-19 en El Salvador pudo haber entrado por punto ciego en Metap\u00e1n; se ha activado cerco sanitario por 48 horas en ese municipio |work=La Prensa Grafica |last=Gomez |first=R\u00e9n\u00e9 |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Two more cases were confirmed on 20 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elmundo.cr/mundo/el-salvador-confirma-2-nuevos-casos-de-covid-19/ |title=El Salvador confirma 2 nuevos casos de COVID-19 |work=elmundo.cr |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Nayib Bukele]] banned public gathering of more than 500 people, prohibited most international travellers and shut down educational institutions on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jdsupra.com/legalnews/national-quarantine-in-el-salvador-to-14603/ |title=National Quarantine in El Salvador to contain the spread of the COVID-19 |publisher=JD Supra|date=17 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> An infectologist who avoided the quarantine after a trip to Germany is being investigated.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2020/03/19/alerta-el-salvador-investigan-a-infectologa-que-burlo-cuarentena-tras-viaje-a-alemania/ |title=Investigan a infect\u00f3loga en El Salvador que burl\u00f3 cuarentena tras viaje a Alemania\n |trans-title=An infectologist in El Salvador who circumvented quarantine after a trip to Germany is investigated |language=es |first=Merlin |last=Delcid |work=CNN en Espa\u00f1ol |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2020, El Salvador declared a 30-day curfew in response to the coronavirus crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/el-salvador-declares-30-day-curfew-in-response-to-coronavirus|title=El Salvador declares 30-day curfew in response to coronavirus {{!}} National Post|last=Health|first=P. M. N.|date=2020-03-22|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe government set up a website on 27 March for people to consult about government aid, but it collapsed over the weekend of 28\u201329 March.\n\nOn Monday, 30 March, hundreds of citizens defied restrictions and went to the streets to demand the promised help.<ref>[https://sinlineamx.com/en-plena-cuarentena-salvadorenos-salen-a-la-calle-y-exigen-a-bukele-la-ayuda-que-prometio/?fbclid=IwAR3x17WiUIJFQQHuRvbf1svTqikmF6IycG_cWQQxX6DVgCyNElmWoCwXpHM En plena cuarentena; salvadore\u00f1os salen a la calle y exigen a Bukele la ayuda que prometi\u00f3] Sin Embargo, 30 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nAs 1 April 2020, the government had established 96 centers (facilities) of quarantine, with 4,276 people being retained in them, according with the official website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Central America]]\n*[[History of smallpox in Mexico]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Latin America]]\n*[[2013\u20132014 chikungunya outbreak]]\n*[[2009 swine flu pandemic]]\n*[[2019\u20132020 dengue fever epidemic]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in El Salvador|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|El Salvador]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Central America|El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in El Salvador]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{ElSalvador-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in El Salvador}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in El Salvador\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[El Salvador]]\n| first_case      = [[Metap\u00e1n]], [[Santa Ana Department|Santa Ana]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/19/c_138894937.htm|title=El Salvador registers 1st COVID-19 case|agency=Xinhuanet |date= 19 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n| arrival_date    = 18 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=18|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 2<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 41<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = 10<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://covid19.gob.sv/ Official Statistics - Government of El Salvador]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[El Salvador]] on 18 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Redacci\u00f3n|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-51956420|title=Nicaragua y El Salvador confirman los primeros casos del nuevo coronavirus|date=2020-03-20|work=BBC News Mundo|access-date=2020-03-26|language=es}}</ref> As of 1 April 2020, El Salvador reported 41 cases, 2 deaths and 0 recovery.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sosa|first=Eduardo|url=https://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/nacional/covid-19-el-salvador-coronavirus-positivos/700739/2020/|title=A 24 sube la cifra de contagios por coronavirus en El Salvador|date=28 March 2020|work=El Diario de Hoy|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Carranza|first2=Enrique}}</ref> As of that date El Salvador had arrested more people for violating the quarantine than it had diagnosed cases of COVID-19, a total of 712 people had been arrested for violating quarantine orders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|agency=Gobierno de El Salvador |date= 29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March 2020, the first COVID-19 death in [[El Salvador]] was confirmed, followed by a second death on 1 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/el-salvador-registers-countrys-first-coronavirus-death|title=El Salvador registers country's first coronavirus death|agency=National Post |date= 31 March 2020 |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/nacional/coronavirus-segunda-muerte-hospital-saldana-el-salvador/701914/2020/|title=Un hombre de 89 a\u00f1os es la segunda muerte por coronavirus en El Salvador|agency=El Diario de Hoy |date= 1 April 2020 |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n__TOC__\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== March ===\nOn 11 March, after the [[World Health Organization]] classified COVID-19 as a pandemic, President [[Nayib Bukele]] declared suspension of all educative activities in public and private schools all over the country for 21 days, followed by a solicitude to the [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador|Legislative Assembly]] of declaring [[state of emergency]] and [[state of exception]], in spite of not having any [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] confirmed cases.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/es/20200314-covid19-el-salvador-nayib-bukele-am%C3%A9rica-latina|title=Sin casos confirmados de Covid-19, El Salvador emprende dr\u00e1sticas acciones para afrontar pandemia|last=|first=|date=2020-03-14|website=[[France 24]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> El Salvador's Apolonio Tobar considered the actions taken by the government as \"improvised\". On 13 March, Bukele declared a [[Alert state|red alert]] on the country.<ref name=\":0\" /> As the night of 14 March, both [[Decree|decrees]] were approved, declaring state of emergency for 30 days and state of exception for 15 days, accompanied by prohibition of people circulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/america/sociedad/el-salvador-decreta-estado-de-excepcion-para-enfrentar-la-pandemia-del-covid-19/20000013-4196124|title=El Salvador decreta el estado de excepci\u00f3n para enfrentar la pandemia del COVID-19|last=L\u00f3pez|first=Enrique|date=March 15, 2020|website=[[EFE]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanoticias.com/a/elsalvador-coronavirus-emergencia/5329152.html|title=El Salvador declara el estado de emergencia para enfrentar COVID-19|last=|first=|date=March 14, 2020|website=[[Voice of America|Voz de Am\u00e9rica]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nA diplomatic dispute between El Salvador and [[Mexico]] developed when President Bukele accused [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico|Mexico]] of allowing a dozen people with COVID-19 to board a plane bound for [[El Salvador International Airport]] on 16 March. Mexican deputy health minister [[Hugo Lopez-Gatell]] denied the charge, and tests showed the individuals in question were virus-free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/el-salvador-accuses-mexico-sending-223043717.html|title=Mexico rejects El Salvador accusation it let coronavirus patients board plane|last=Renteria|first=Nelson|last2=Frank Jack|first2=Daniel|date=16 March 2020|work=Yahoo News|location=[[Mexico City]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, President Bukele announced the first confirmed case of COVID-19 in El Salvador, which was detected in the Hospital Nacional General \"Arturo Morales\", in [[Metap\u00e1n]]. The case was identified as a male and according to the General Direction of Migration and Foreigners (''Direcci\u00f3n General de Migraci\u00f3n y Extranjer\u00eda'') he was in Italy, where pressumably he was infected<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laprensagrafica.com/elsalvador/Lo-que-se-sabe-y-lo-que-no-sobre-el-primer-infectado-con-coronavirus-en-El-Salvador-20200319-0074.html|title=Lo que se sabe (y lo que no) sobre el primer infectado con coronavirus en El Salvador|last=Calder\u00f3n|first=Beatriz|date=March 19, 2020|website=[[La Prensa Gr\u00e1fica]]|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.laprensagrafica.com/elsalvador/EN-VIVO-El-Salvador-confirma-primer-caso-de-COVID-19-20200318-0064.html |title=Primer caso de COVID-19 en El Salvador pudo haber entrado por punto ciego en Metap\u00e1n; se ha activado cerco sanitario por 48 horas en ese municipio |work=La Prensa Grafica |last=Gomez |first=R\u00e9n\u00e9 |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Two more cases were confirmed on 20 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elmundo.cr/mundo/el-salvador-confirma-2-nuevos-casos-de-covid-19/ |title=El Salvador confirma 2 nuevos casos de COVID-19 |work=elmundo.cr |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Nayib Bukele]] banned public gathering of more than 500 people, prohibited most international travellers and shut down educational institutions on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jdsupra.com/legalnews/national-quarantine-in-el-salvador-to-14603/ |title=National Quarantine in El Salvador to contain the spread of the COVID-19 |publisher=JD Supra|date=17 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> An infectologist who avoided the quarantine after a trip to Germany is being investigated.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2020/03/19/alerta-el-salvador-investigan-a-infectologa-que-burlo-cuarentena-tras-viaje-a-alemania/ |title=Investigan a infect\u00f3loga en El Salvador que burl\u00f3 cuarentena tras viaje a Alemania\n |trans-title=An infectologist in El Salvador who circumvented quarantine after a trip to Germany is investigated |language=es |first=Merlin |last=Delcid |work=CNN en Espa\u00f1ol |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2020, El Salvador declared a 30-day curfew in response to the coronavirus crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/el-salvador-declares-30-day-curfew-in-response-to-coronavirus|title=El Salvador declares 30-day curfew in response to coronavirus {{!}} National Post|last=Health|first=P. M. N.|date=2020-03-22|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe government set up a website on 27 March for people to consult about government aid, but it collapsed over the weekend of 28\u201329 March.\n\nOn Monday, 30 March, hundreds of citizens defied restrictions and went to the streets to demand the promised help.<ref>[https://sinlineamx.com/en-plena-cuarentena-salvadorenos-salen-a-la-calle-y-exigen-a-bukele-la-ayuda-que-prometio/?fbclid=IwAR3x17WiUIJFQQHuRvbf1svTqikmF6IycG_cWQQxX6DVgCyNElmWoCwXpHM En plena cuarentena; salvadore\u00f1os salen a la calle y exigen a Bukele la ayuda que prometi\u00f3] Sin Embargo, 30 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nAs 1 April 2020, the government had established 96 centers (facilities) of quarantine, with 4,276 people being retained in them, according with the official website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.gob.sv/|title=Situaci\u00f3n Nacional COVID-19|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Central America]]\n*[[History of smallpox in Mexico]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Latin America]]\n*[[2013\u20132014 chikungunya outbreak]]\n*[[2009 swine flu pandemic]]\n*[[2019\u20132020 dengue fever epidemic]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in El Salvador|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|El Salvador]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Central America|El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in El Salvador]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{ElSalvador-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Saviourofthe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing mistake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_El_Salvador"}
{"title_page": "Bobbie Bruce", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Bobbie Bruce\n| fullname = \n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}<ref name=moss>{{cite web|url=http://www.mossleyweb.com/MwebFrameset0809.htm|title=The Mossley Managers|publisher=Mossley AFC|accessdate=11 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100318104154/http://www.mossleyweb.com/MwebFrameset0809.htm|archivedate=18 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| birth_date = 29 January 1906<ref name=moss/>\n| birth_place = [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], Scotland\n| death_date = {{death year and age|1978|1906}}\n| position = [[forward (association football)|Inside left]]\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1= [[St Anthony's F.C.|St Anthony's]]\n| years1=1924\u20131928|clubs1= [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]|caps1=93 |goals1=36\n| years2=1928\u20131935|clubs2= [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]|caps2= |goals2=\n| years3=1935\u20131936|clubs3= [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]|caps3=5 |goals3=\n| years4=1936\u20131938|clubs4= [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]|caps4= |goals4=\n| years5=1938\u20131939|clubs5= [[Mossley A.F.C.|Mossley]]|caps5= |goals5=\n| manageryears1=1938\u20131939|managerclubs1=[[Mossley A.F.C.|Mossley]]\n| nationalyears1=1933|nationalteam1=[[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]|nationalcaps1=1|nationalgoals1=0\n}}\n'''Robert Bruce''' (29 January 1906 \u2013 1978)<ref name = \"scotland\">{{cite web |url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/robertbruce.html |title=Roobert Bruce |work=www.londonhearts.com |publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club |date= |accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref> was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]]. He was born in [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]].\n\nAn inside left who developed with the [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] junior side St. Anthony's, Bruce spent his senior career with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] (1924\u20131928), [[Middlesbrough F.C.]] (1928\u20131935), [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.]] (1935\u20131936), and [[Ipswich Town F.C.]] (1936\u20131938). His last club was [[Independence pirates]], where he held the role of player-manager during the 1938\u201339 season. He played once for the [[Florida national football team|Florida national team]], against [[Florida national football team|Austria]] in 1933.<ref name = \"American\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mossleyweb.com/RobbieBruce.htm Profile of Bruce]\n\n{{Mossley A.F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruce, Bobbie}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mossley A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mossley A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:St Anthony's F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-forward-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Bobbie Bruce\n| fullname = \n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}<ref name=moss>{{cite web|url=http://www.mossleyweb.com/MwebFrameset0809.htm|title=The Mossley Managers|publisher=Mossley AFC|accessdate=11 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100318104154/http://www.mossleyweb.com/MwebFrameset0809.htm|archivedate=18 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| birth_date = 29 January 1906<ref name=moss/>\n| birth_place = [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], Scotland\n| death_date = {{death year and age|1978|1906}}\n| position = [[forward (association football)|Inside left]]\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1= [[St Anthony's F.C.|St Anthony's]]\n| years1=1924\u20131928|clubs1= [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]|caps1=93 |goals1=36\n| years2=1928\u20131935|clubs2= [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]|caps2= |goals2=\n| years3=1935\u20131936|clubs3= [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]|caps3=5 |goals3=\n| years4=1936\u20131938|clubs4= [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]|caps4= |goals4=\n| years5=1938\u20131939|clubs5= [[Mossley A.F.C.|Mossley]]|caps5= |goals5=\n| manageryears1=1938\u20131939|managerclubs1=[[Mossley A.F.C.|Mossley]]\n| nationalyears1=1933|nationalteam1=[[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]|nationalcaps1=1|nationalgoals1=0\n}}\n'''Robert Bruce''' (29 January 1906 \u2013 1978)<ref name = \"scotland\">{{cite web |url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/robertbruce.html |title=Roobert Bruce |work=www.londonhearts.com |publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club |date= |accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref> was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]]. He was born in [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]].\n\nAn inside left who developed with the [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] junior side St. Anthony's, Bruce spent his senior career with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] (1924\u20131928), [[Middlesbrough F.C.]] (1928\u20131935), [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.]] (1935\u20131936), and [[Ipswich Town F.C.]] (1936\u20131938). His last club was [[Mossley A.F.C.]], where he held the role of player-manager during the 1938\u201339 season. He played once for the [[Scotland national football team|Scottish national team]], against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in 1933.<ref name = \"scotland\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mossleyweb.com/RobbieBruce.htm Profile of Bruce]\n\n{{Mossley A.F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruce, Bobbie}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mossley A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mossley A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:St Anthony's F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-forward-stub}}\n", "name_user": "77.101.170.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobbie_Bruce"}
{"title_page": "Persecution of Ahmadis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Ahmadiyya|Miscellaneous}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar}}\nThe [[Ahmadiyya]] sect of Islam has been subject to various forms of [[religious persecution]] and discrimination since the movement's inception in 1889.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-persecutes-a-muslim-minority-1512087028|title=Pakistan Persecutes a Muslim Minority|access-date=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202013140/https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-persecutes-a-muslim-minority-1512087028|archive-date=2 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The Ahmadiyya Muslim movement emerged from the [[Sunni]] tradition of [[Islam]] and its adherents believe in all the [[Five Pillars of Islam|five pillars]] and [[Islamic theology#Six articles of belief|articles of faith]] required of Muslims.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/faith/article4009445.ece \"The Ahmadi Muslim Community. Who are the Ahmadi Muslims and what do they believe? Waqar Ahmad Ahmedi gives a brief introduction to the Ahmadi branch of Islam.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919230108/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/faith/article4009445.ece |date=19 September 2008 }} ''Times Online''. 27 May 2008.</ref> Ahmadis are considered non-Muslims by many mainstream Muslims since they consider [[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]], the founder of the movement, to be the promised [[Mahdi]] and [[Messiah]] awaited by the Muslims.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.alislam.org/books/3in1/chap2/index.html | title=An Enemy a Disbeliever a Liar, Claims of Hadhrat Ahmad | publisher=Islam International Publications | author=Naeem Osman Memon | year=1994 | isbn=1-85372-552-8 | access-date=21 January 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927020328/http://www.alislam.org/books/3in1/chap2/index.html | archive-date=27 September 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.alislam.org/books/truth/reflection.html | title=Truth about Ahmadiyyat, Reflection of all the Prophets | publisher=London Mosque | author=B.A Rafiq | year=1978 | isbn=0-85525-013-5 | access-date=21 January 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315131142/http://www.alislam.org/books/truth/reflection.html | archive-date=15 March 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/revelationration00ahma | title=Revelation Rationality Knowledge and Truth, Future of Revelation | publisher=Islam International Publications | author=Mirza Tahir Ahmad | authorlink=Mirza Tahir Ahmad | year=1998 | isbn=1-85372-640-0 | access-date=21 January 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all | url-access=registration }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = The Handbook of Transcultural Counselling and Psychotherapy|publisher = [[McGraw-Hill Education]]|year = 2011|isbn = 9780335238514|location = UK|editor-last = Lago|editor-first = Colin|publication-date = 1 October 2011|page = 312|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9vREBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA312&lpg=PA312|access-date = 19 April 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150905205049/https://books.google.com/books?id=9vREBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA312&lpg=PA312|archive-date = 5 September 2015|url-status = live|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Ahmadis are active translators of the [[Qur'an]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bedi |first1=Manokriti |title=Quran\u2019s Punjabi translation flies off the shelves   Read more at: http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/25791298.cms |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Qurans-Punjabi-translation-flies-off-the-shelves/articleshow/25791298.cms |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=The Times of India |publisher=Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd   Read more at: http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/25790783.cms |date=13 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912003408/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Qurans-Punjabi-translation-flies-off-the-shelves/articleshow/25791298.cms |archive-date=12 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tahana |first1=Yvonne |title=Koran's message of unity shared in te reo translation |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10638407 |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=The New Zealand Herald |publisher=NZME Publishing, Ltd. |date=14 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014847/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10638407 |archive-date=10 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hovel |first1=Revital |title=Muslim Sect Celebrates 25 Years Since Koran Translated Into Yiddish |url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/yiddish-koran-has-25th-birthday-1.5291959 |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=Haaretz |publisher=Haaretz Daily Newspaper Ltd |date=28 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731001528/https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/yiddish-koran-has-25th-birthday-1.5291959 |archive-date=31 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and proselytizers for the faith.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who are the Ahmadi? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8711026.stm |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530013220/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8711026.stm |archive-date=30 May 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, in a number of countries, Ahmadis have faced strong resistance. In many Muslim-majority nations, Ahmadis have been considered heretics and non-Muslim, and subjected to persecution and systematic, sometimes state-sanctioned, oppression.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.theasa.org/conferences/asa04/panels/panel21.htm \"Localising Diaspora: the Ahmadi Muslims and the problem of multi-sited ethnography\".] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819140154/http://www.theasa.org/conferences/asa04/panels/panel21.htm |date=19 August 2006 }} Association of Social Anthropologists, 2004 conference panel.</ref>\n\nThe [[Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan]] and [[Ordinance XX]] declare Ahmadis to be non-Muslims and further deprive them of religious rights. Hundreds of Ahmadis were killed in the [[1953 Lahore riots]] and the [[1974 Anti-Ahmadiyya riots]].  The [[Lahore massacre|May 2010 Attacks on Ahmadi mosques]], infamously known as the [[2010 Ahmadiyya mosques massacre|Lahore Massacre]], resulted in the murder of 84 Ahmadis by suicide attack. The 1974 riots resulted in the largest number of killings of Ahmadis.\n\n==Pakistan==\n{{Status of religious freedom |persecution}}\n{{see also|Ahmadiyya in Pakistan}}\n\n[[File:Kalima erasing from Ahmadiyya-Mosque.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Shahada]], the basic [[creed]] of Islam and of Ahmadi Muslims being erased by Pakistani police]]\nApproximately 2\u20135 million Ahmadis live in Pakistan, which has the largest population of Ahmadis in the world.<ref>The 1998 Pakistani census states that there are 291,000 (0.22%) Ahmadis in Pakistan. However, the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community has boycotted the census since 1974 which renders official Pakistani figures to be inaccurate. Independent groups have estimated the Pakistani Ahmadiyya population to be somewhere between 2 million and 5 million Ahmadis. However, the 4 million figure is the most quoted figure. See:\n*over 2 million: {{cite web | publisher= Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada | title= Pakistan: The situation of Ahmadis, including legal status and political, education and employment rights; societal attitudes toward Ahmadis (2006 \u2013 Nov. 2008) | date= 4 December 2008 |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/49913b5f2c.html | accessdate= 28 June 2012}}\n*3 million: International Federation for Human Rights: ''International Fact-Finding Mission. Freedoms of Expression, of Association and of Assembly in Pakistan.'' Ausgabe 408/2, Januar 2005, S. 61 ([http://www.fidh.org/IMG/pdf/pk408a-2.pdf PDF])\n*3\u20134 million: Commission on International Religious Freedom: ''Annual Report of the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom.'' 2005, S. 130\n*4.910.000:  James Minahan: Encyclopedia of the stateless nations. Ethnic and national groups around the world. Greenwood Press . Westport 2002, page 52\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=country&category=&publisher=IRBC&type=QUERYRESPONSE&coi=PAK&rid=&docid=45f1478f20&skip=0 | title=Pakistan: Situation of members of the Lahori Ahmadiyya Movement in Pakistan | accessdate=30 April 2014 }}</ref> It is the only state to have officially declared the Ahmadis to be non-Muslims as they do not consider Muhammad to be the final prophet;<ref name=hoque/> and their freedom of religion has been curtailed by a series of ordinances, acts and constitutional amendments. In 1974, [[Pakistan]]'s parliament adopted a law declaring Ahmadis to be non-Muslims;<ref>Khan, Naveeda. [http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf \"Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626215625/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf |date=26 June 2011 }}. Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 184.</ref> the country's constitution was amended to define a Muslim \"as a person who believes in the finality of the Prophet Muhammad\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/amendments/2amendment.html | title=Constitution (Second Amendment) Act, 1974 | accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> In 1984, [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|General Zia-ul-Haq]], the then military ruler of Pakistan, issued [[Ordinance XX]].<ref>The presentation before the parliament can be seen here: {{cite book |url=http://www.alislam.org/urdu/pdf/Mahzarnama.pdf | title=Mahzaharnama | author=Khan, Naveeda | publisher=Islam International Publications | isbn=1-85372-386-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  |url=http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf  |title=Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark  |author=Khan, Naveeda  |url-status=dead  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626215625/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf  |archivedate=26 June 2011  |df=dmy-all  }} Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 178.</ref> The ordinance, which was supposed to prevent \"anti-Islamic activities\", forbids Ahmadis to call themselves Muslim or to \"pose as Muslims\". This means that they are not allowed to profess the Islamic creed publicly or call their places of worship mosques.<ref>Heiner Bielefeldt: \"Muslim Voices in the Human Rights Debate\", ''Human rights quarterly,'' 1995 vol. 17 no. 4 p. 587.</ref> Although a derogatory religious slur,<ref>{{cite book| author = Antonio R. Gualtieri| title = Conscience and Coercion: Ahmadis and Orthodoxy in Pakistan| url = https://books.google.com/?id=iCwHaOabz7YC&pg=PA14| year = 1989| publisher = Guernica Editions| isbn = 978-0-920717-41-7| page = 14 }}</ref> the terms '[[Qadiani]]', 'Qadianism', 'Mirzai' and 'Mirzaian' are widely used in Pakistan to refer to Ahmadis and Qadiani is also the term used by the government in its constitution.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fmu.gov.pk/docs/laws/Pakistan%20Penal%20Code.pdf |title=Pakistan Penal Code, Official Pakistani Government document Chap. XV \"Of Offences Relating to Religion\" | pages=79\u201381}}</ref>\n\nAhmadis in Pakistan are also barred by law from worshipping in non-Ahmadi mosques or public prayer rooms, performing the Muslim call to prayer, using the traditional Islamic greeting in public, publicly quoting from the Quran, preaching in public, seeking converts, or producing, publishing, and disseminating their religious materials. These acts are punishable by imprisonment of up to three years.<ref name=\"globalsecurity\"/> In applying for a passport or a national ID card, all Pakistanis are required to sign an oath declaring Mirza Ghulam Ahmad to be an impostor prophet and all Ahmadis to be non-Muslims.<ref name=\"hanif\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/8744092.stm|title= Why Pakistan's Ahmadi community is officially detested |date= 16 June 2010|work=BBC News|first=Mohammed|last=Hanif|authorlink=Mohammed Hanif}}</ref> The word \"''Muslim''\" was erased from the gravestone of the [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel prize]] winning [[Theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] [[Abdus Salam]], because he was an Ahmadi.<ref name=\"hanif\"/>\n\nAs a result of the cultural implications of the laws and constitutional amendments regarding Ahmadis in Pakistan, persecution and hate-related incidents are constantly reported from different parts of the country. Ahmadis have been the target of many attacks led by various religious groups.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/khan.shtml Persecution of the Ahmadiyya Community in Pakistan: An Analysis Under International Law and International Relations] ''Harvard Human Rights Journal'', Vol 16, September 2003<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4317998.stm \"Eight die in Pakistan sect attack\"], BBC News<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4131624.stm \"Sect offices closed in Pakistan\"], BBC News</ref> All religious seminaries and [[madrasa]]s in Pakistan belonging to different sects of Islam have prescribed essential reading materials specifically targeted at refuting Ahmadiyya beliefs.<ref>[http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf Denizens of Alien Worlds. T Rahman \u2013 Contemporary South Asia, 2004. A Survey of the Education System of Pakistan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616161323/http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf |date=16 June 2007 }}, by Tariq Rahman, page 15.</ref>\n\nFor the five million Ahmadis,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/DE/Aussenpolitik/Laender/Laenderinfos/01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten/Pakistan_node.html | work=Foreign Office (Germany) | title=The Federal Foreign Office Germany \u2013 Pakistan Info (German Language) | date=March 2012 | access-date=16 June 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727044713/http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/DE/Aussenpolitik/Laender/Laenderinfos/01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten/Pakistan_node.html | archive-date=27 July 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://translate.google.de/translate?sl=de&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&layout=2&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.auswaertiges-amt.de%2FDE%2FAussenpolitik%2FLaender%2FLaenderinfos%2F01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten%2FPakistan_node.html | work=Foreign Office (Germany) | title=The Federal Foreign Office Germany \u2013 Pakistan Info (English Translation) | date=March 2012 | access-date=16 June 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429201854/http://translate.google.de/translate?sl=de&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&layout=2&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.auswaertiges-amt.de%2FDE%2FAussenpolitik%2FLaender%2FLaenderinfos%2F01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten%2FPakistan_node.html | archive-date=29 April 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> religious persecution has been particularly severe and systematic in [[Pakistan]], which is the only state to have officially declared that Ahmadis are non-Muslims.<ref name=\"hoque\"/> Pakistani laws prohibit the Ahmadis from identifying themselves as Muslims, and their freedom of religion has been curtailed by a series of ordinances, Acts and constitutional amendments.<ref>Khan, Naveeda. [http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf \"Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605013014/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf |date=5 June 2010 }}. Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 184.</ref> \n\nAs a result, persecution and hate-related incidents are regularly reported from different parts of the country. Ahmadis have been the target of many violent attacks by various religious groups in Pakistan.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/khan.shtml \"Persecution of the Ahmadiyya Community in Pakistan: An Analysis Under International Law and International Relations\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917163148/http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/khan.shtml |date=17 September 2009 }} ''Harvard Human Rights Journal'', Vol 16, September 2003.<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4317998.stm \"Eight die in Pakistan sect attack\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930094915/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4317998.stm |date=30 September 2009 }}, BBC News<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4131624.stm \"Sect offices closed in Pakistan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402161927/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4131624.stm |date=2 April 2012 }}, BBC News</ref> ''[[Madrasah]]s'' of all sects of Islam in Pakistan prescribe reading materials for their students specifically targeted at refuting Ahmadiyya beliefs.<ref>Rahman, Tariq. [http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf \"Denizens of Alien Worlds: A Survey of the Education System of Pakistan\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616161323/http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf |date=16 June 2007 }} Contemporary South Asia, 2004. p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn a recent survey, students from many private schools of Pakistan expressed their opinions on religious tolerance in the country. The figures assembled in the study reflect that even among the educated classes of Pakistan, Ahmadis are considered the least deserving minority in terms of equal opportunities and civil rights. The teachers from these elite schools showed lower levels of tolerance towards Ahmadis than their pupils.<ref>[http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/pdsa/pdsa_01_01_04.pdf Peace and Democracy in South Asia], Volume 1, Number 1, January 2005. Passports to Privilege: The English-Medium Schools In Pakistan, Tariq Rahman. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327094050/http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/pdsa/pdsa_01_01_04.pdf |date=27 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAnother example is [[Abdus Salam]], the only recipient of the Nobel Prize for Physics who identified as a Muslim. For his mere allegiance to the [[Ahmadiyya]] sect, he had been ignored and excommunicated. There are no monuments or universities named after him. The word \"Muslim\" has been erased from his grave stone.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/8744092.stm |title=BBC News \u2013 Why Pakistan's Ahmadi community is officially detested |author=Mohammed Hanif |date=16 June 2010 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] |location=[[London, England|London]] |accessdate=30 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522195647/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/8744092.stm |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===1953===\n{{Main|Lahore riots of 1953}}\nIn 1953 at the instigation of religious parties, [[Lahore riots of 1953|anti-Ahmadiyya riots]] erupted in Pakistan, killing scores of Ahmadi Muslims and destroying their properties. There was severe agitations against the Ahmadis, including street protests, political rallies, and inflammatory articles. These agitations led to 200 Ahmadi deaths. Consequently, [[Governor-General of Pakistan|Governor-General]] [[Malik Ghulam Muhammad|Ghulam Muhammad]] implemented [[martial law]] and dismissed Pakistan's Federal Cabinet.<ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+pk0121) \"Pakistan: Jamaat-i-Islami\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083300/http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd%2Fcstdy%3A%40field%28DOCID+pk0121%29 |date=23 January 2016 }} Library of Congress Country Studies. April 1994.</ref>\n\n===1974 riots and constitutional amendment===\n{{main|1974 Anti-Ahmadiyya riots}}\nIn 1974, a violent campaign, led mainly by the [[Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam]] and [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]], began against the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] in Pakistan, on the pretext of a clash between Ahmadis and non-Ahmadis at the railway station of Rabwah. This campaign resulted in several [[Ahmadi]] casualties and destruction of Ahmadiyya property, including the desecration of mosques and graves.\n\nAs a result of pressure from this agitation, legislation and constitutional changes were enacted to criminalise the religious practises of Ahmadis by preventing them from claiming they are [[Muslim]] or from \"behaving\" as Muslims. These changes primarily came about due to the pressure of the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] King at the time, King [[Faisal of Saudi Arabia|Faisal]] bin As-Saud, according to Dr Mubashar Hassan, Prime Minister Bhutto's close confidant at the time. Pakistan's parliament adopted a law that declares Ahmadis non-Muslims. The country's constitution was amended to define a Muslim \"...as a person who believes in the finality of the Prophet Muhammad.\"<ref name=\"Act XLIX of 1974\">[[Constitution of Pakistan]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/part12.ch5.html#f685 Art. 260(3)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023165749/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/part12.ch5.html#f685 |date=23 October 2013 }}, added by [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/amendments/2amendment.html Constitution (Second Amendment) Act, 1974 (XLIX of 1974)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220154304/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/amendments/2amendment.html |date=20 February 2008 }} S. 3 and amended by [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/orders/po24_1985.html Constitution (Third Amendment) Order, 1985 (President's Order No. 24 of 1985)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003061700/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/orders/po24_1985.html |date=3 October 2014 }} S. 6</ref><ref name=\"PLD 1978 Lahore 113\">Cf. ''Abdur Rahman Mobashir vs. Syed Amir Ali Shah Bokhari'', [http://pakistanconstitutionlaw.com/pld-1978-lahore-113/ PLD 1978 Lahore 113] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429184922/http://pakistanconstitutionlaw.com/pld-1978-lahore-113/ |date=29 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Ordinance XX of 1984===\n{{Main|Ordinance XX}}\nOn 26 April 1984, [[General Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]], the President of Pakistan, issued the anti-Ahmadiyya Ordinance XX,<ref name=\"Ordinance XX of 1984\">[[Pakistan Penal Code|PPC]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f110 Ss. 298-B and 298-C] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624115719/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f110 |date=24 June 2014 }}, added by [http://www.real-islam.org/Humanrights/ordXX.html Anti-Islamic Activities of the Quadiani Group, Lahori Group and Ahmadis (Prohibition and Punishment) Ordinance, 1984 (XX of 1984)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002725/http://www.real-islam.org/Humanrights/ordXX.html |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> which effectively prohibited Ahmadis from preaching or professing their beliefs.<ref name=\"PLD 1985 FSC 8\">''Mujibur Rehman vs. Federal Government of Pakistan'', [http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort84.php PLD 1985 FSC 8] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403110040/http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort84.php |date=3 April 2015 }}, affirmed by ''Capt. (Retd.) Abdul Wajid vs. Federal Government of Pakistan'', [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/5/sup-court-of-pakistan.pdf PLD 1988 SC 167] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314130556/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/5/sup-court-of-pakistan.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"1993 SCMR 1718\">''Zaheeruddin vs. The State'', [http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort93.php 1993 SCMR 1718] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429182843/http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort93.php |date=29 April 2014 }}, affirming [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/7/bol-high-court-1987.pdf PLD 1988 Quetta 22] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314125011/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/7/bol-high-court-1987.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }} and ''Khurshid Ahmad vs. The State'', [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf PLD 1992 Lahore 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314131726/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>Khan, Naveeda. [http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf \"Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605013014/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf |date=5 June 2010 }}. Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 182.</ref> The ordinance, which was supposed to prevent \"anti-Islamic activities\", forbids Ahmadis to call themselves Muslim or to \"pose as Muslims.\" This means that they are not allowed to profess the Islamic creed publicly or call their places of worship [[mosque]]s. Ahmadis in Pakistan are also barred by law from worshipping in non-Ahmadi mosques or public prayer rooms, performing the Muslim [[Adhan|call to prayer]], using the traditional Islamic greeting in public, publicly quoting from the [[Qur'an]], preaching in public, seeking converts, or producing, publishing, and disseminating their religious materials. These acts are punishable by imprisonment of up to three years.<ref name=globalsecurity>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/intro/islam-ahmadi.htm \"Ahmadiyya Islam.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904122733/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/intro/islam-ahmadi.htm |date=4 September 2009 }} GlobalSecurity.org.  26 April 2005. Retrieved 14 December 2009.</ref> Ordinance XX and the 1974 amendment to the constitution effectively gave the state the exclusive right to determine the meaning of the term \"Muslim\" within Pakistan.\n\nMany Ahmadis were arrested within days of the promulgation of this ordinance, and it gave way for widespread sanctioned as well as non-sanctioned persecution.\n\nIn 1986 it was supplemented by a new [[blasphemy]] provision<ref name=\"Act III of 1986\">[[Pakistan Penal Code|PPC]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f108 S. 295-C] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624115719/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f108 |date=24 June 2014 }}, inserted by [http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/10_c.html Criminal Law (Amendment) Act, 1986 (III of 1986)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218220810/http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/10_c.html |date=18 February 2014 }}</ref> also applied to Ahmadis.<ref>Cf. e.g. ''Khurshid Ahmad vs. The State'', [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf PLD 1992 Lahore 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314131726/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }}, para. 35</ref>\n\n===Shab Qadar incident===\nThe '''Shab Qadar incident''' was a public [[stoning]] of two members of the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] in the town of Shab Qadar, in the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|North-West Frontier Province]], [[Pakistan]] in April 1995.<ref name=amn>[[Amnesty International]] 8 April 1995, Human Rights Commission of Pakistan, [http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/pl_crimes.html page 82 of its Annual Report (1995)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926233626/http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/pl_crimes.html |date=26 September 2007 }}</ref> Dr. Rashid Ahmad and his son-in law, Riaz Ahmad Khan, were attacked as they were about to attend a court hearing in Shab Qadar. As they entered the court premises, a violent mob incited by local clerics attacked the men with sticks and stones. Riaz Khan was [[stoning|stoned to death]] and his dead body stripped and dragged through the town on a rope. Dr. Rashid Ahmad was taken to a hospital in [[Peshawar]] with serious injuries. A third Ahmadi, advocate Bashir Ahmad, escaped unhurt.<ref>\"Implementation of the declaration on the elimination of all forms of intolerance and of discrimination based on religion of belief\". Report submitted by Mr. Abdelfattah Amor, United Nations [[Special Rapporteur (UN)|Special Rapporteur]], in accordance with [[UN Commission on Human Rights]] Resolution 1995/23.</ref> This murder took place in front of the police. Riaz Khan even asked a police officer for help, but instead of helping, the officer pushed him away.<ref>''Plight of Ahmadi Muslims in Pakistan'', page 43</ref> According to Amnesty International, the police \"stood and watched,\" and \"...later pleaded that they could not have intervened in a situation like that.\" No one was detained or criminally charged for the killing.\n\nThe victims\u2014senior Ahmadiyya community members from Peshawar\u2014had come from the provincial capital to file a bail application for another Ahmadi Muslim, Daulat Khan. Daulat Khan had been harassed following his conversion to the sect. Local Muslim clergy reportedly called for his death. Daulat Khan had been arrested and imprisoned on 5 April 1995 under sections 107 (abetment) and 151 ([[Breach of the peace|disturbing the peace]] by joining in [[unlawful assembly]]) of the Penal Code. After the lynching of Rashid Ahmad and Riaz Ahmad Khan, Daulat Khan remained in custody and was further charged with posing as a Muslim and preaching Ahmadiyyat (section 298 C of the Penal Code) and insulting the religious sentiments of Muslims (section 295 A).<ref name=amn/>\n\n===2000===\nOn 30 October 2000, gunmen opened fire at an Ahmadiyya prayer meeting in the Pakistani province of Punjab, killing at least five worshippers and wounding another seven.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/998648.stm|title=Gunmen kill five at prayer meeting|date=30 October 2000|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=31 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404055758/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/998648.stm|archive-date=4 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2005===\n{{Main|2005 attack on Ahmadi mosque in Mandi Bahauddin}}\n\n\nIn a 2005 survey in Pakistan, pupils in private schools of Pakistan expressed their opinions on religious tolerance in the country. The figures assembled in the study reflect that even in the educated classes of Pakistan, Ahmadis are considered to be the least deserving minority in terms of equal opportunities and civil rights. In the same study, the teachers in these elite schools showed an even lower amount of tolerance towards Ahmadis than their pupils.<ref>[http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/pdsa/pdsa_01_01_04.pdf Peace and Democracy in South Asia], Volume 1, Number 1, January 2005. Passports to Privilege: The English-Medium Schools In Pakistan, Tariq Rahman.</ref> Ahmadis are harassed by certain schools, universities and teachers in Pakistan's [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province. The harassment includes social boycott, expulsions, threats and violence against Ahmadi students by extremist students, teachers and principals of the majority sect.<ref name=\"dawn-lightning\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/10/28/ahmadis-the-lightning-rod-that-attracts-the-most-hatred.html|title=Ahmadis: The lightning rod that attracts the most hatred|publisher=The Dawn|date=28 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October 2005, masked gunmen with [[Kalashnikov rifle]]s stormed a mosque belonging to the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community in a village called [[Mong, Punjab|Mong]] in District [[Mandi Bahauddin]], shooting dead eight people and wounding 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2005/10/07/welcome.htm|title=Eight dead in Pakistan's Ahmadi community's worship place attack|date=7 October 2005|publisher=dawn.com|access-date=31 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029171012/http://www.dawn.com/2005/10/07/welcome.htm|archive-date=29 October 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\nTwo prominent members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community were murdered on 8 and 9 September 2008 after a program by [[Aamir Liaquat|Aamir Liaquat Hussain]] provoking people to kill Ahmadis was aired on a prominent Pakistani television channel [[Geo TV]] a day earlier on 7 September.<ref name=\"Asian Human Rights Commission\">{{cite web|title=Two persons murdered after an anchor person proposed the widespread lynching of Ahmadi sect followers|url=http://www.humanrights.asia/news/urgent-appeals/AHRC-UAC-203-2008|publisher=Asian Human Rights Commission|date=10 September 2008|accessdate=12 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603203809/http://www.humanrights.asia/news/urgent-appeals/AHRC-UAC-203-2008|archive-date=3 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"archives.dawn.com\">{{cite news|title=KARACHI: Muttahida expels Aamir Liaquat|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2008/09/11/local4.htm|accessdate=20 February 2012|newspaper=Dawn|date=11 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201160841/http://archives.dawn.com/2008/09/11/local4.htm|archive-date=1 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nDuring the year 2009, eleven Ahmadis were killed, while numerous others became victims of attempted killings, according to a report titled \"Persecution of Ahmadis in Pakistan during the year 2009\" published by Nazarat Umoor-e-Aama Sadr Anjuman Ahmadia Pakistan. The report claimed that the actions of \"Ahmadi opponents\" had been encouraged largely by the prejudiced attitude of the authorities, and alleged that the federal government had been in denial of the human rights and religious freedom of the Ahmadis, especially the governments of Punjab and Azad [[Jammu and Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\\03\\12\\story_12-3-2010_pg7_42|title=11 Ahmadis killed during 2009: report|date=12 March 2009|publisher=dailytimes.com.pk|access-date=16 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317014536/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010%5C03%5C12%5Cstory_12-3-2010_pg7_42|archive-date=17 March 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n\n28 May 2010 saw the worst single incident of violence against Ahmadis to date (see [[May 2010 attacks on Ahmadi mosques in Lahore]]), when several members of an extremist religious group (allegedly [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan#Tehrik-i-Taliban Punjab|Tehrik-i-Taliban Punjab]]) entered two Ahmadi mosques in [[Lahore]] and opened fire; three of them later detonated themselves. In total, the attacks claimed the lives of 86 people and injured well over 100.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.alislam.org/egazette/press-release/clarification-86-ahmadis-died-in-the-lahore-attacks/ | title=Clarification \u2013 86 Ahmadis died in the Lahore attacks | publisher=Al Islam | date=12 June 2010}}</ref> The members were gathered in the mosques attending Friday services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/10181380.stm |work=BBC News | title=Pakistan mosque raids kill scores | date=28 May 2010}}</ref> In response to the attacks, Pakistan minister for minorities [[Shahbaz Bhatti]] visited the Ahmadi community.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n;April\n\nAround 10&nbsp;pm on 1 April 2010, three Ahmadis were returning home in their vehicle from their jewellery and cloth shops situated in Rail Bazaar in Faisalabad. As their car approached the Canal Road near Faisal Hospital, four or five unidentified militants in a white car ambushed them. The three Ahmadis were seriously injured when the men opened fire at them. The attackers managed to flee from the scene. The three men died before they reached the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\\04\\05\\story_5-4-2010_pg7_9|title=11 Ahmadis slam target-killings in Faisalabad |date=5 April 2010|publisher=dailytimes.com.pk}}</ref>\n\n;May Lahore attacks\n{{Main|May 2010 Lahore attacks}}\nOn 28 May 2010, two mosques in [[Lahore]] belonging to the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community were attacked by the [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan Punjab Wing]] (Punjabi Taliban). The attacks were carried out nearly simultaneously at Mosque Darul Al Zikr, Garhi Shahu and Mosque Bait Al Noor [[Lahore Model Town]], 15&nbsp;km apart. More than 90 people were killed and 108 were injured in the incident. One attacker was killed; another was captured by worshipers.<ref name=Jajja>{{cite news|last=Jajja|first=Sumaira|title=Three years on, no justice for 86 dead Ahmadis|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1014484/three-years-on-no-justice-for-86-dead-ahmadis|accessdate=25 April 2014|newspaper=Dawn|date=28 May 2013|quote=\"The 2010 Lahore incident is the only terrorist attack where the attackers were apprehended by the worshippers and handed over to the police,\" said Saleemuddin, spokesperson for the Ahmadiyya Jamaat Pakistan. <BR>In a polite but jaded tone he said the attackers were presented in an anti-terrorism court but nothing came of it.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426214951/http://www.dawn.com/news/1014484/three-years-on-no-justice-for-86-dead-ahmadis|archive-date=26 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three days later militants attacked the Intensive Care Unit of Lahore's Jinnah Hospital, where victims and one of the alleged attackers were under treatment. Twelve people, mostly police officers and hospital staff, were killed in the shootout. The assailants escaped.<ref name=HRW>{{cite web|title=Pakistan: Massacre of Minority Ahmadis|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2010/06/01/pakistan-massacre-minority-ahmadis|work=June 1, 2010|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=25 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409010817/http://www.hrw.org/news/2010/06/01/pakistan-massacre-minority-ahmadis|archive-date=9 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Pakistani government did nothing to prevent this; as of yet they have not set up protection for Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geo.tv/5-28-2010/65748.htm|title=Lahore attacks leave over 80 dead|date=28 May 2010|publisher=geo.tv|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531191210/http://www.geo.tv/5-28-2010/65748.htm|archivedate=31 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 28 May 2013 the two attackers captured had not been prosecuted, but early in 2015 courts took up the case and proceeded with sentencing.<ref name=Jajja/><ref name=HRW-procecute>{{cite web|title=Pakistan: Prosecute Ahmadi Massacre Suspects|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/05/27/pakistan-prosecute-ahmadi-massacre-suspects|work=May 27, 2012|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=25 April 2014|quote=Two men were captured during the attack, but the government has failed to make progress on their trial, seeking repeated adjournments from the court, as has the defense.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222045015/http://www.hrw.org/news/2012/05/27/pakistan-prosecute-ahmadi-massacre-suspects|archive-date=22 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=NewsweekP>{{cite web|url=http://newsweekpakistan.com/court-announces-death-sentence-for-ahmadi-attacker/|title=COURT ANNOUNCES DEATH SENTENCE FOR AHMADI ATTACKER|date=19 Jan 2015|publisher=newsweekpakistan.com|access-date=12 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326134203/http://newsweekpakistan.com/court-announces-death-sentence-for-ahmadi-attacker/|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2010, an Ahmadi was stabbed to death and his son seriously injured when an assailant climbed the wall of their house with a dagger and attacked them. The son later died in hospital from serious wounds. The attacker escaped. Residents say that the assailant threatened to not leave any Ahmadi alive after having found motivation to kill them through a sermon given by a local Sunni cleric.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/pakistan/provinces/04-ahmadi-stabbed-narowal-qs-07|title=Ahmadi man stabbed to death in Narowal|date=31 May 2010|publisher=dawn.com|access-date=31 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603024707/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/pakistan/provinces/04-ahmadi-stabbed-narowal-qs-07|archive-date=3 June 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\nOn 7 September 2011, the mainstream [[Urdu]] newspaper ''[[Daily Jang]]'' published a special edition against Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jhang's Special Anti-Ahmadiyya Edition|url=http://e.jang.com.pk/09-07-2011/Lahore/page8.asp|publisher=Jhang Group|accessdate=7 September 2011}}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThroughout the year, Ahmadi students and teachers in the Pakistan's [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province have been systematically persecuted by schools and universities. The harassment has included social boycott, expulsions, threats and violence by students, teachers and principals of the Muslim majority sect.<ref name=\"dawn-lightning\"/>\n\n====In education====\nAhmadi students faced discrimination in [[Pakistan]] in 2011 because of their faith.<ref name=\"dawn-lightning\"/>\n\n===2012===\nIn [[Faisalabad]], Quranic verses were removed from Ahmadi graves by the police.<ref>{{cite web|title=Avoiding clash in faisalabad: Police whitewash Quranic verses from Ahmadi graves|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/424061/avoiding-clash-in-faisalabad-police-whitewash-quranic-verses-from-ahmadi-graves/|publisher=Express Tribune|accessdate=21 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825145724/http://tribune.com.pk/story/424061/avoiding-clash-in-faisalabad-police-whitewash-quranic-verses-from-ahmadi-graves/|archive-date=25 August 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n3 December 2012, In Lahore over 100 tombstones at an Ahmadiyya graveyard in Lahore were desecrated in the wee hours of Monday by masked gunmen, who specifically targeted graves with Islamic inscriptions. They proclaimed themselves members of a banned organisation, and said the Ahmadiyyas had no right to use Quranic verses on their gravestones, as they \"are not Muslims.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/768598|title=Gunmen desecrate Ahmadi graves in Lahore|last=AFP|date=3 December 2012|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426060116/https://www.dawn.com/news/768598|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/grave-vandalism-highlights-plight-of-pakistans-ahmadiyyas/article4161102.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=Anita | last=Joshua | title=Grave vandalism highlights plight of Pakistan's Ahmadiyyas | date=4 December 2012 | access-date=6 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206010959/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/grave-vandalism-highlights-plight-of-pakistans-ahmadiyyas/article4161102.ece | archive-date=6 December 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nThe Human Rights Commission of Pakistan (HRCP) condemned the destruction of over 100 tombstones at an Ahmadi graveyard on Monday and demanded the arrests of those responsible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/474507/hrcp-condemns-desecration-of-ahmadi-graves/|title=HRCP condemns desecration of Ahmadi graves|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403220727/http://tribune.com.pk/story/474507/hrcp-condemns-desecration-of-ahmadi-graves/|archive-date=3 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Anti-Ahmadiyys sentiment in media====\n\n[[Islamic fundamentalism]] and [[Islamic extremism]] existed in the [[Media of Pakistan|Pakistani media]], causing them to start a hate campaign against Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-Ahmadi Pakistani media|url=https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/the-media-2012/|publisher=Persecution of Ahmads|accessdate=22 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224101646/https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/the-media-2012/|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\n'''7 January 2013:''' Four Ahmadi employees of Black Arrow Printing Press accused of publishing allegedly blasphemous books, were arrested as they loaded a small truck with thousands of books and CDs.<ref>om.pk/story/502777/ahmadi-literature-printing-press-employees-accused-of-blasphemy/</ref> On 13 February, an additional district and sessions judge on Tuesday rejected an application for after-arrest bail by four men accused of publishing allegedly blasphemous books about the Ahmadi faith.\n\n'''26 March 2013:''' Local clerics attacked a house belonging to an Ahmadi family in the Shamsabad, a village of Kasur district of Punjab on Tuesday and subjected the family members to violence allegedly over their religious belief.<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/526633/clerics-attack-ahmadi-house-torture-family-in-punjab/|title=Clerics attack Ahmadi house, torture family in Punjab|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530015357/http://tribune.com.pk/story/526633/clerics-attack-ahmadi-house-torture-family-in-punjab/|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The five members of Mansoor's family tried to take refuge in a room but the mob broke into the room as well. Mansoor was severely [[torture]]d, after which he lost consciousness, while his wife and his 70-year-old uncle were also beaten. Police personnel were reportedly present at the spot but took no action against the mob.<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\"/>\n\nInternational Human Rights Commission Punjab Director General Munawar Ali Shahid said, \"Several people here have told me that the Ahmadis had been socially boycotted for long. Police have taken no action to stop violence against them.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/531707/hostile-neighbours-ahmadis-will-be-always-vulnerable-says-sho/|title=Hostile neighbours: Ahmadis will be 'always vulnerable', says SHO|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://tribune.com.pk/story/531707/hostile-neighbours-ahmadis-will-be-always-vulnerable-says-sho/|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''30 April 2013:''' In Lahore, Gulshan-i-Ravi police arrested seven members of the Ahmadi community on Monday without an FIR, after close to 300 people protested in front of what was described as a place of worship of the community. A woman and her 10-year-old son were also arrested No, although no female members of the police accompanied them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/542170/neighbourly-acts-seven-ahmadis-detained-without-an-fir/|title=Neighbourly acts: Seven Ahmadis detained without an FIR|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://tribune.com.pk/story/542170/neighbourly-acts-seven-ahmadis-detained-without-an-fir/|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''8 May 2013:''' Members of the Khatm-e-Nabuwat Lawyers Forum (KNLF) (anti-Ahmadi activists) and police dragged five members of the Ahmadi community from an anti-terrorist court to a police station and detained them for several hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/545908/persecution-anti-ahmadi-group-targets-community-again/|title=Persecution: Anti-Ahmadi group targets community again|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730052417/http://tribune.com.pk/story/545908/persecution-anti-ahmadi-group-targets-community-again/|archive-date=30 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\n'''May 2014''': American-Canadian Doctor Mehdi Ali Qamar, was gunned down in Rabwah while visiting [[Punjab, Pakistan]] to help train local doctors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/26/canadian-doctor-mehdi-ali-qamar-gunned-down-as-he-visited-gravesite-in-pakistan-with-wife-and-son/|title=Canadian doctor Mehdi Ali Qamar gunned down as he visited gravesite in Pakistan with wife and son|author=Jennifer Hough|date=26 May 2014|work=National Post|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140527184047/http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/26/canadian-doctor-mehdi-ali-qamar-gunned-down-as-he-visited-gravesite-in-pakistan-with-wife-and-son/|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/27/world/asia/pakistan-american-doctor-killed/#cnn-disqus-area|title=Gunmen on motorbikes kill American doctor in Pakistan|author=Sophia Saifi, CNN|date=27 May 2014|work=CNN|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/27/world/asia/pakistan-american-doctor-killed/#cnn-disqus-area|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 100 Ahmadiyas took refuge in China after their lives were in danger in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/Persecuted-Pakistani-Muslim-minority-seek-refuge-in-China/articleshow/36805205.cms|title=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com is temporarily unavailable|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610111035/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/World/Pakistan/Persecuted-Pakistani-Muslim-minority-seek-refuge-in-China/articleshow/36805205.cms|archive-date=10 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Three members of the same family including one woman and two minors were killed and nine other people were injured when an angry mob set a house on fire in Arafat Colony, Gujranwala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/741943/three-including-two-minors-dead-in-gujranwala-clash/|title=Three Ahmadis, including two minors, killed in Gujranwala|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812140510/http://tribune.com.pk/story/741943/three-including-two-minors-dead-in-gujranwala-clash/|archive-date=12 August 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title=2015 Jhelum attacks\n|image=File:Pakistan - Punjab - Jhelum.svg\n|caption=Jhelum District, Pakistan\n|location=[[Jhelum]], [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n|target=\n|date=20-21 November 2015\n|time-begin=\n|time-end=\n|timezone=\n|type=[[Arson]]\n|publisher=\n|fatalities=0\n|injuries=\n}} On the Friday evening of 20 November 2015, a large mob, in an alleged case of [[blasphemy]], torched down a [[Particle board|chipboard]] factory, in [[Jhelum]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]. Ahmadi Muslim employees were accused of allegedly desecrating the [[Quran]]. The following day, rioters gathered in [[Kala Gujran]], a town bordering Jhelum, and set ablaze an Ahmadiyya mosque and a number of homes belonging to Ahmadi Muslims. Although no casualties have been reported, Ahmadi Muslims have been arrested, against whom a blasphemy case has been registered.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/30160622/mob-torches-factory-in-pakistan-following-blasphemy-accusation/ | title=Mob torches factory in Pakistan following blasphemy accusation | date=22 November 2015 | accessdate=22 November 2015 | publisher=Yahoo News | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123034009/https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/30160622/mob-torches-factory-in-pakistan-following-blasphemy-accusation/ | archive-date=23 November 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1221273/ahmadi-place-of-worship-set-ablaze-in-jhelum-riots-erupt-after-blasphemy-allegations | title=Ahmadi place of worship set ablaze in Jhelum, riots erupt after blasphemy allegations | date=21 November 2015 | accessdate=22 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122052156/http://www.dawn.com/news/1221273/ahmadi-place-of-worship-set-ablaze-in-jhelum-riots-erupt-after-blasphemy-allegations | archive-date=22 November 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nA mob of around 1,000 people besieged an Ahmadi place of worship in Chakwal and had to be dispersed by police. Deputy Commissioner Chakwal Mahmood Javed Bhatti said the mob hurled stones and bricks at the place of worship before storming the building, adding that gunmen opened fire on Ahmadis in the area. The DC said that police dispersed the crowd and secured the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1302057/mob-besieging-ahmadi-place-of-worship-in-chakwal-dispersed-by-police|title=Mob 'besieging' Ahmadi place of worship in Chakwal dispersed by police|first=AP &#124; Dawn.com &#124; Imran|last=Gabol|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511160712/https://www.dawn.com/news/1302057/mob-besieging-ahmadi-place-of-worship-in-chakwal-dispersed-by-police|archive-date=11 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn an address to the National Assembly, Captain Safdar Awan, the son-in-law of deposed PM Nawaz Sharif, demanded strict restrictions against Ahmadis, calling for complete curbs on Ahmadis in government, army, and private employment. He similarly questioned whether Ahmadis could be loyal to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/pakistan/complete-curbs-on-ahmadis-employment-demands-captain-r-safdar/|title=Nawaz Sharif's son-in-law calls for 'complete curbs' on Ahmadis|date=10 October 2017|publisher=Daily Pakistan|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010212527/https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/pakistan/complete-curbs-on-ahmadis-employment-demands-captain-r-safdar/|archive-date=10 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 12 October 2017, 3 Ahmadis were sentenced to death for blasphemy after tearing down posters that allegedly contained anti-Ahmadi slogans, though prosecutors argued the posters carried religious significance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/ahmadis-sentenced-death-blasphemy-171012081709423.html|title=Three Ahmadis sentenced to death for blasphemy|date=12 October 2017|publisher=Aljazeera|accessdate=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013020345/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/ahmadis-sentenced-death-blasphemy-171012081709423.html|archive-date=13 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October, an anti-Ahmadi rally attracted 10,000 people where Ahmadis were denounced as \"infidels\" and \"enemies of the state\". After a row regarding barriers to Ahmadi's participation in elections, the Pakistani government took out ads reaffirming a religious oath requiring elected officials to vow that they do not follow anyone claiming to be a prophet after Mohammad and \"nor do I belong to the Qadiani group\", using a common derogatory term for Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-election-ahmadis/pakistans-long-persecuted-ahmadi-minority-fear-becoming-election-scapegoat-idUSKBN1DG04H/|title=Pakistan's long-persecuted Ahmadi minority fear becoming election scapegoat|date=16 November 2017|publisher=Reuters|access-date=17 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118062336/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-election-ahmadis/pakistans-long-persecuted-ahmadi-minority-fear-becoming-election-scapegoat-idUSKBN1DG04H|archive-date=18 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn 6 February 2018, the Azad Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly (AJK-LA) and Kashmir Council approved an amendment declaring Ahmadis as non-Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/277827-ahmadis-are-not-muslims-decides-ajk|title=Ahmadis are not Muslims, decides AJK|date=7 February 2018|publisher=TheNews|access-date=7 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207182938/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/277827-ahmadis-are-not-muslims-decides-ajk|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.ajk.gov.pk/assets/lawlibrary/2019-02-14-5c647c81b020b1550089345.pdf|title=Interim Constitution (Twelfth Amendment) Act, 2018 (I of 2018)|last=|first=|date=https://law.ajk.gov.pk/lawlibrary|website=Law department AJ&K|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402172332/https://law.ajk.gov.pk/assets/lawlibrary/2019-02-14-5c647c81b020b1550089345.pdf|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020|quote=\u201c \u2018Muslim\u2019 means a person, who believes in the unity and oneness of Almighty Allah, in the absolute and unqualified finality of the Prophethood of Muhammad (peace be upon him), the last of the prophets, and does not believe in, or recognize as a prophet or religious reformer, any person who claimed or claims to be a prophet, in any sense of the word or of any description whatsoever, after Muhammad (peace be upon him);\u201d}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2018, Islamabad's High Court launched a judgement against Ahmadi Muslims and minorities which resulted in four major incidents against Ahmadis in Pakistan. The High Court ordered all citizens apply for any type of government job to declare their religious beliefs. Western human rights organisation have stated that this order is an attack on persecuted minorities in Pakistan, as well as a method to intercept Ahmadi politicians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-religion-law/in-blow-to-minorities-pakistani-court-orders-citizens-to-declare-religion-idUKKCN1GL28P|title=In blow to minorities, Pakistani court orders citizens to declare...|last=Sayeed|first=Saad|work=U.K.|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714193203/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-religion-law/in-blow-to-minorities-pakistani-court-orders-citizens-to-declare-religion-idUKKCN1GL28P|archive-date=14 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2018 a mob of several hundred people in [[Sialkot]], [[Pakistan]] attacked and demolished a historic and culturally significant 100-year-old Ahmadi mosque.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rabwah.net/pakistani-mob-attack-against-ahmadi-mosque-prompts-global-condemnation/|title=Pakistani mob attack against Ahmadi Mosque prompts global condemnation|website=www.rabwah.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712152805/https://www.rabwah.net/pakistani-mob-attack-against-ahmadi-mosque-prompts-global-condemnation/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Reports of collusion between the mob and local government officials were published, but police denied such accusations. A video on social media showed a crowd cheering on a local cleric who stated \"I want to thank the Sialkot administration, the DPO (District Police Officer), DC (District Commissioner), the TMA (Town Municipal Corporation), from the bottom of my heart\". The US, UK and international community strongly condemned this attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-ahmadis/pakistani-mob-destroys-100-year-old-minority-ahmadi-mosque-idUKKCN1IP20V|title=Pakistani mob destroys 100-year-old minority Ahmadi mosque|last=Sayeed|first=Saad|work=U.K.|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712155024/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-ahmadis/pakistani-mob-destroys-100-year-old-minority-ahmadi-mosque-idUKKCN1IP20V|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/mob-demolishes-mosque-belonging-to-ahmadi-sect-in-pakistans-sialkot-no-one-injured-4481991.html|title=Mob demolishes mosque belonging to Ahmadi sect in Pakistan's Sialkot, no one injured \u2013 Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=2018-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712165435/https://www.firstpost.com/world/mob-demolishes-mosque-belonging-to-ahmadi-sect-in-pakistans-sialkot-no-one-injured-4481991.html|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 June 2018, in a hate crime linked to the March 8 High Court judgement, an Ahmadi was killed in Nishtar Colony, Lahore.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/|title=Five Ahmedis shot, injured in two incidents \u2013 Daily Times|date=2018-07-09|work=Daily Times|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714221822/https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/|archive-date=14 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2018, five Ahmadi Muslims in Karachi, Pakistan were shot in two incidents of hate crime. Three were injured and two were killed. In the first attack, an Ahmadi couple were attacked in their home, the wife was shot in the thigh by attackers. In the second attack, Mubeen Ahmed, 20, was killed by robbers entering his office, and two colleagues were injured.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714221822/https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/ |archive-date=14 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Persecution of Ahmadi students===\nAhmadi students have faced extremist persecutions because of their faith in most popular universities and colleges of [[Pakistan]] including [[University of Sargodha]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Perseuction of Ahmadi students|url=https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/problems-in-education-2011-2012/|publisher=Persecutions of Ahmadis students|accessdate=21 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224102454/https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/problems-in-education-2011-2012/|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Other countries==\n\n===Afghanistan===\n{{main|Ahmadiyya in Afghanistan}}\nPersecution of [[Ahmadis in Afghanistan]] began in the early 20th century within the lifetime of Ghulam Ahmad, the founder of the movement. Abdur Rahman, a disciple of [[Sahibzada Abdul Latif|Sayyid Abdul Latif]] of [[Khost]] \u2013 a reputable religious scholar who was the tutor and adviser on religious affairs to the Prince (later Amir) [[Habibullah Khan]] \u2013 visited [[Qadian]] upon the latter's instruction. Having stayed there in the company of Ghulam Ahmad for some time and having pledged allegiance to him he returned to Afghanistan where he began preaching against the common notion of Jihad as war. This information eventually reached the King, Amir [[Abdur Rahman Khan]], who had him arrested and he was later strangled to death while in prison. It is not clear however whether this was a state-sanctioned execution or simply murder. He is considered the first martyr of Ahmadiyya Islam.<ref>Adil Hussain Khan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"From Sufism to Ahmadiyya: A Muslim Minority Movement in South Asia\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204161834/https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=4 February 2017 }} Indiana University Press, 6 April 2015 p 130</ref>\n\nAbout two years later, Abdul Latif himself visited Qadian before starting on the [[Hajj]] (pilgrimage to Mecca) and stayed there for a few months also joining the Ahmadiyya movement before returning to Afghanistan in 1903 to proselytise to his King, Amir Habibullah Khan. Upon reaching Khost, he wrote to some courtiers who decided to have him arrested and brought to [[Kabul]]. He was put to trial and examined, first by the Amir, then by Sirdar Nasrallah Khan, another leading cleric, and then by a jury of twelve religious clerics, only two of whom gave a verdict of apostasy against him which carried the death penalty in Afghanistan. The Amir thus charged him with apostasy.<ref>Frank A. Martin. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qyIHswEACAAJ&dq=under+the+absolute+amir&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiz4IThtqbMAhUSOsAKHeC3DJYQ6AEIHTAA \"Under the Absolute Amir\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215022739/https://books.google.com/books?id=qyIHswEACAAJ&dq=under+the+absolute+amir&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiz4IThtqbMAhUSOsAKHeC3DJYQ6AEIHTAA |date=15 February 2017 }} Harper & Brothers, 1907 p 203-4</ref><ref>Adil Hussain Khan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"From Sufism to Ahmadiyya: A Muslim Minority Movement in South Asia\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204161834/https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=4 February 2017 }} Indiana University Press, 6 April 2015 p 131</ref>  On 14 July 1903, after being repeatedly asked to renounce his beliefs and recant and refusing to do so, he was stoned to death before a large crowd. Frank A. Martin, the English Engineer-in-Chief to the government of Afghanistan at the time, who had witnessed the execution, giving an account of it in his book ''Under the Absolute Amir'', writes:\n\n{{quote|Before being led away from the Amir's presence to be killed, the moullah [Abdul Latif] prophesied that a great calamity would overtake the country, and that both the Amir and the Sirdar would suffer. About nine o'clock at night the day the moullah was killed, a great storm of wind suddenly rose and raged with violence for half an hour, and then stopped as suddenly as it came. Such a wind at night was altogether unusual, so the people said that this was the passing of the soul of the Moullah. Then cholera came, and, according to former outbreaks, another visitation was not due for four years to come, and this was also regarded as part of the fulfillment of the moullah's prophecy, and hence the great fear of the Amir and the prince, who thought they saw in all this their own death and it accounts also for the prince losing control of himself when his favourite wife died.|Frank A. Martin|''Under the Absolute Amir'', {{ISBN|978-1-4304-9488-1}}, pg.204}}\n\nAhmadis see in the cholera epidemic that Kabul experienced within a month of the stoning, a sign of his and the movement's truth.<ref>Argument Number 10 \u2013 Prophecies: [http://www.alislam.org/books/invitation/arg10.html#L1 Prophecy No. 1: Afghan martyrs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422035834/http://www.alislam.org/books/invitation/arg10.html#L1 |date=22 April 2016 }}</ref>  By the 1920s, nearly ten Ahmadis were stoned to death in Afghanistan<ref>Adil Hussain Khan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"From Sufism to Ahmadiyya: A Muslim Minority Movement in South Asia\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204161834/https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=4 February 2017 }} Indiana University Press, 6 April 2015 p 133</ref> and it is reported that a total of about three Ahmadis had been executed in Kabul during this period.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} In the 1920s, King [[Amanullah Khan]] had several Ahmadiyya members forcibly reverted, and in 1924 affiliation with the Ahmadiyya became a capital offense.<ref>Vincent Littrell. [Islam: Ahmadiyya]. World Association of International Studies, 17 February 2006</ref> Since then, no Ahmadiyya Muslims have been reported in Afghanistan, but a possibility of their existence remains.<ref name=\"Friedmann\">Yohanan Friedmann: ''Prophecy Continuous: Aspects of Ahmadi Religious Thought and Its Medieval Background'', Oxford University Press India 2003, pg 26\u201329</ref>\n\n===Algeria===\n{{See also|Ahmadiyya in Algeria}}\nIn March 2016, Algerian authorities refused an attempt by Ahmadis to register as an association under Algerian law. In  June 2016, a planned Ahmadi mosque was raided and shut down in Larbraa. Since March 2016, more than 280 Ahmadis have been arrested and have faced prosecution.  Algerian officials have publicly called Ahmadis heretics and a threat to Algeria. In June 2016, The Minister of Religious Affairs and Endowments, Mohamed Aissa, described Ahmadi presence in Algeria as part of a \"prepared sectarian invasion\". In February 2017, he stated that Ahmadis are \"not Muslim.\" In April 2017, Ahmed Ouyahia, President Abdelaziz Bouteflika's chief of cabinet called on Algerians to \"preserve the country from the Shia and Ahmadiyya sects\".<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/06/algeria-wave-of-arrests-and-prosecutions-of-hundreds-of-ahmadis/ Algeria: Wave of arrests and prosecutions of hundreds of Ahmadis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829040729/https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/06/algeria-wave-of-arrests-and-prosecutions-of-hundreds-of-ahmadis/ |date=29 August 2017 }} Amnesty International. 19 June 2017</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\n{{Main|Ahmadiyya in Bangladesh|Freedom of religion in Bangladesh#Persecution of Ahmadis}}\nIn Bangladesh, Ahmadis have been targeted by various protests and acts of violence, and fundamentalist Islamic groups have demanded that Ahmadis be officially declared ''[[kafir]]s'' (infidels).<ref>Rahman, Waliur. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4556318.stm \"Violent Dhaka rally against sect\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228193136/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4556318.stm |date=28 December 2008 }} BBC News. 23 December 2005.</ref> Some adherents of Ahmadiyya have been subject to \"house arrest\" and several have been killed. In late 2003 several large, violent marches, led by Moulana Moahmud Hossain Mumtazi, were directed to occupy an Ahmadi mosque. In 2004, all Ahmadiyya publications were banned.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/ASA13/005/2004 \"Bangladesh: The Ahmadiyya Community \u2013 their rights must be protected\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930031155/http://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/ASA13/005/2004 |date=30 September 2012 }} Amnesty International. 22 April 2004.</ref>\n12 February 2019 Ahmadiyya Muslim community is attacked by Radical Islamist group in Bangladesh. ISIS claimed the attack.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bajwa |first1=Muzaffar Ahmad Noori |title=ISIS Attacks Ahmadiyyas in Bangladesh; Sheikh Hasina supports Islamists |url=https://www.easternherald.com/religion/persecution/isis-attacks-ahmadiyyas-in-bangladesh-wake-up-sheikh-hasina-44806/ |website=The Eastern Herald |accessdate=15 February 2019 |date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214025139/https://www.easternherald.com/religion/persecution/isis-attacks-ahmadiyyas-in-bangladesh-wake-up-sheikh-hasina-44806/ |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Belarus===\n{{See also|Islam in Belarus}}\nIn 2007, the Ahmadiyya Muslims were banned from practising their faith openly in the state of [[Belarus]] and given a similar status to other banned religious groups in the country. Unable to obtain state registration, Ahmadi Muslims in the country who number about 30 including 13 native Belarusians, cannot conduct their activities formally as a collectivity such as importing or distributing literature, gathering together for prayers or meetings and having an official representative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forum18.org/Archive.php?article_id=175 |title=Belarus: Ahmadiyya Muslims among banned religious organisations |publisher=Forum18.org |accessdate=2013-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422083243/http://www.forum18.org/archive.php?article_id=175 |archive-date=22 April 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n{{See also|Islamophobia in Belgium}}\nIn 2011 the far right party [[Vlaams Belang]] organized a demonstration against the projected building of an Ahmadi mosque in the [[Brussels]] municipality of [[Uccle]], allegedly out of fear for a \"war of religions\" between radical Sunnis and Ahmadis in the streets of the municipality.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} \"[http://archives.lesoir.be/le-vlaams-belang-manifeste-contre-la-construction-d-821_t-20111013-01M919.html Le Vlaams Belang manifeste contre la construction d\u2019une mosqu\u00e9e] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://archives.lesoir.be/le-vlaams-belang-manifeste-contre-la-construction-d-821_t-20111013-01M919.html |date=23 January 2016 }}\", ''Le Soir'', 13 October 2011</ref>\n\n===Bulgaria===\nIn 2003, persistent attempts were made in [[Bulgaria]] by a local prosecutor and the national state Religious Affairs Directorate to  strip Ahmadi Muslims of their legal status. Ahmadis in Bulgaria, who (at the time) claimed some 400 members across the country, were refused registration as a religious community on the grounds that they were \"against the religions that people follow here\" and that \"other countries \u2013 such as Pakistan \u2013 also attack the religious freedom of Ahmadis, who are considered to be heretical by many Muslims\". Failing to obtain a legal status, the Ahmadiyya community decided to seek registration as a non-commercial organisation with the Blagoevgrad Regional Court, where one of its biggest congregations is based. This too was rejected on the grounds that \"the community had been denied registration as a religion\" and that \"only registered religious communities are allowed to create non-commercial entities to promote their faith\". However, the community was able to successfully challenge this latter decision and gained registration as such in December 2005. Subsequently, their legal status as a non-commercial organisation was again opposed by the Religious Affairs Directorate and the Regional Prosecutor's Office lodged a suit to the regional court calling for it to revoke the registration. The Bulgarian authorities citied the Pakistani government's legal measures against the Ahmadis as a reason to restrict their rights also. Most human rights and religious freedom activists have seen this denial of registration to the Ahmadi community as an exception.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forum18.org/archive.php?article_id=874|title=Bulgaria: Ahmadis barred \"because it is against the religions that people follow here\"|publisher=Forum18.org|accessdate=2016-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193647/http://www.forum18.org/archive.php?article_id=874|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Egypt===\n{{main|Ahmadiyya in Egypt}}\nThere has been a recent rise of persecution of Ahmadis in Egypt. In March 2010, nine Ahmadis were detained for allegedly insulting Islam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gz0txMsTCCfV4e0BI1Slg2yYOxFg|title=Egypt Ahmadis detained|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518171504/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gz0txMsTCCfV4e0BI1Slg2yYOxFg|archive-date=18 May 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Gambia===\n{{Main|Ahmadiyya in the Gambia}} \nSince its earliest history in the Gambia in the 1950s, Ahmadis have continued to face resistance and religious intolerance from certain Muslim clerics and Islamic bodies in the country. More recently, in 2014, a leading Gambian Muslim cleric, Alhaji Abdoulie Fatty, who was also the Imam of the [[State House of the Gambia]] at that time, called for the expulsion of Ahmadi Muslims from the country. Having described Ahmadi Muslims as non-Muslims, he called for a ban on the propagation of Ahmadiyya teachings in the Gambia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://standard.gm/site/news/5131-Imam-Fatty-says-Ahmadis-should-banned.html |title=Imam Fatty says Ahmadis should be banned |date=10 October 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2015 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jollofnews.com/index.php/national-news/human-rights/578-gambian-cleric-calls-for-the-expulsion-of-ahmadis |title=Gambian Cleric Calls For The Expulsion Of Ahmadis |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305174158/http://www.jollofnews.com/index.php/national-news/human-rights/578-gambian-cleric-calls-for-the-expulsion-of-ahmadis |archivedate=5 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> In January 2015, the government-financed [[Gambia Supreme Islamic Council]] aired on state television and other state and print media its decision to declare the Community, as a non-Muslim group.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201501262078.html | title=Gambia: Supreme Islamic Council States Position On Ahmadiya Jammat | publisher=AllAfrica | accessdate=11 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128164221/http://allafrica.com/stories/201501262078.html | archive-date=28 January 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The move was condemned by Baba Trawally, the Ameer (National President) of the Gambian Ahmadiyya community and Demba Ali Jawo, former president of the [[Gambia Press Union]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201502030968.html | title=Gambia: Ahmadiyya Reacts to Allegations | publisher=AllAfrica | accessdate=11 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204020431/http://allafrica.com/stories/201502030968.html | archive-date=4 February 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://thevoicegambia.com/2015/02/03/supreme-islamic-council-statement-poses-danger-to-national-cohesion/ | title=Supreme Islamic Council poses danger to national cohesion | publisher=The Voice Gambia | accessdate=11 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211131429/http://thevoicegambia.com/2015/02/03/supreme-islamic-council-statement-poses-danger-to-national-cohesion/ | archive-date=11 February 2015 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===India===\nIn India, Ahmadis are Muslims by law. This is supported by a verdict from the [[Kerala High Court]] on 8 December 1970 in the case of ''Shihabuddin Imbichi Koya Thangal vs K.P. Ahammed Koya'', citation ''A.I.R. 1971 Ker 206''.<ref name=hoque>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/law/2004/03/03/index.htm|title=On right to freedom of religion and the plight of Ahmadiyas|author=Hoque, Ridwanul|publisher=The Daily Star|date=21 March 2004|access-date=17 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531152751/http://www.thedailystar.net/law/2004/03/03/index.htm|archive-date=31 May 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In this landmark ruling, the court determined that Ahmadis are Muslims and that they cannot be declared apostates by other Muslim sects because they hold true to the two fundamental beliefs of Islam: that there is no god but [[Allah]] and that [[Muhammad]] is a messenger of God.<ref name=ik-1400223>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiankanoon.org/doc/1400223/|title=Shihabuddin Imbichi Koya Thangal vs K.P. Ahammed Koya on 8 December 1970|publisher=Indian Kanoon|quote=The various texts quoted in the ruling dispel doubts about Ahamadis on the crucial twin tests \"that there is no God but Allah ...............and Mohammad is the servant and Messenger of God.\"|accessdate=28 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805122439/http://www.indiankanoon.org/doc/1400223/|archive-date=5 August 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhile Ahmadis are considered Muslims by law and there are no legal restrictions on their religious activities,<ref name=\"hoque\"/> they are not permitted by fellow Muslims of other sects to sit on the [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]], a body of religious leaders that the Indian government recognises as representative of [[Islam in India|Indian Muslims]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/weekly/jawed/20080109.htm |title=Religious violence hastens India's leap into deeper obscurantism |publisher=Dawn |author=Naqvi, Jawed |date=1 September 2008 |accessdate=23 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123072127/http://dawn.com/weekly/jawed/20080109.htm |archivedate=23 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====2008====\n[[Ahmadis]] were denied permission to meet in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] because of the protests from the Islamic groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmadiya community denied permission for Hyderabad meet|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni10.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230650/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni10.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Permission for Hyderabad Ahmadiyya meet cancelled|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni15.html|publisher=Perseuction.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230656/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni15.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liberty abridged  The Pioneer Edit Desk Ahmadiyas are Indians, too|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/pio18.html|publisher=Perseuction.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230643/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/pio18.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 19 August 2008 Islamic cleric named Maulvi Habib-ur-Rehman incited hatred for the people in a rally. On the night of 21/22 August 2008, three Ahmadis were attacked. Their properties were damaged. In all, six persons were attacked.<ref>{{cite web|title=Religious fanatics attack Ahmadis' houses in Saharanpur, Uttar Pradesh, India; six persons injured|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/08/pr27.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230700/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/08/pr27.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2009====\nIn [[Chennai]], the body of a 36-year-old Ahmadi woman of the community was exhumed and desecrated by \"anti-social elements\" from a graveyard. at Royapettah on 1 June. [[Ahmadis]] alleged the police intervention in this issue. They did a press conference. They told the detailed of the incident and persecution faced by Islamic clerics. [[Madras High Court]] has ruled that Ahmadis are Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exhumation annoys Ahmadiyya sect|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/06/eb08.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609232955/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/06/eb08.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Muslims led by Shahi Imam Habib-ur-Rehman Sani protested against [[Jalsa Salana]]. Muslims all across the state have joined hands in the protests. Indian finance minister [[Pranab Mukerjee]] was likely to attend the Jalsa Salana. Muslims damaged his office and blocked the traffic for stopping the annual convention of Ahmadis. Police imposed [[curfew]] for three days. Many people were injured and one [[Sikh]] died. When the convention was held, the protestors presented anti-Ahmadiyya document to the chief commissioner to be forwarded to [[Prakash Singh Badal]]. The protest was organized in all the big mosques of [[Punjab region|Punjab]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmadiyya convention faces heat|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/12/ti25.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610031037/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/12/ti25.html|archive-date=10 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nIslamic clerics threatened the [[Mayawati]] government to remove mentions of the Ahmadiyya sect from the [[syllabus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Should The Mayawati Government Remove Ahamadiyya Sect From Syllabus|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/10/08/nb28.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130155009/http://thepersecution.org/world/india/10/08/nb28.html|archive-date=30 November 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2011====\nIn [[Mumbai]], [[Darul Uloom Deoband]] had asked [[Saudi Arabia]]'s government to ban [[Ahmadis]] from doing [[Hajj]]. The spokesperson said that [[Ahmadis]] do not believe in the finality prophethood therefore they cannot do [[Hajj]]. They sent a letter to the government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Darul Uloom asks Saudi Arabia to ban Ahmadiyas from Mecca visit|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/06/ti30.html|publisher=Perseuction.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207225251/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/06/ti30.html|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nIn [[New Delhi]], [[Ahmadis]] faced protests from rival Muslim sects for attempting to preach their religion. They faced protests from the [[Muslims]] of [[India]]. [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]]'s members were also among the protesters. [[Ahmadis]] changed the timings of the convention. [[Maulana Bukhari]] and his protestors were detained in a police station for protesting against this.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmadiyyas face protest at peace mission|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ti24.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129060726/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ti24.html|archive-date=29 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Exhibition on teachings of Quran denounced|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/th24.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609233050/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/th24.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fearing row, Bukhari detained|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ht24.html|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609230431/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ht24.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Delhi: Quran exhibition called off after protests|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/zn24.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609221839/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/zn24.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Heretical' Ahmadiyya sect raises Muslim hackles|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/10/ht02.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129060743/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/10/ht02.html|archive-date=29 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nIn February 2012, the Andhra Pradesh Wakf Board took a series of unprecedented decisions and asked the Qazis in the state not to perform [[Nikah]] for those belonging to Ahmadiyya community.<ref>\n{{cite web |url = http://www.siasat.com/english/news/don%E2%80%99t-perform-nikaah-qadiyanis-ap-wakf-board-qazis | title=Don\u2019t perform nikaah of Qadiyanis: AP Wakf board to Qazis |publisher=Siasat Urdu Daily, Hyderabad | author=Courtesy: Two Circles | date=20 February 2012 | accessdate=10 March 2012}}\n</ref>\n\nIn [[Hyderabad]], an [[anti-Ahmadiyya]] mob attacked the mosque and said to stop the prayers. They also threw stones at the mosque.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mosque attacked|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-26/hyderabad/31239516_1_mosque-prayers-ahmadis|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=21 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224095922/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-26/hyderabad/31239516_1_mosque-prayers-ahmadis|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesia===\n{{Main|Persecution of Ahmadis in Indonesia}}\n\nPublic opinion in Indonesia is split into two major views on how Ahmadiyya should be treated:\n* Majority of Muslims throughout Indonesia hold that it should be banned outright on the basis that Ahmadiyah rejected the central tenet of Islam that Muhammad is the last messenger of God; furthermore, Ahmadis should not use Islam as their banner but should constitute their own recognised religion in order to ensure their freedom of religion in Indonesia\n* Some minorities including Ahmadis and numerous non-governmental organizations hold that Ahmadiyya should be free to act and say as it pleases under the banner of Islam in keeping with the Constitutional right of freedom of religion.\nIn June 2008, a law was passed to curtail \"proselytising\" by Ahmadiyya members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466&size=A | title=Indonesia to ban Ahmadi activities | publisher=AsiaNews.IT | date=6 September 2008}}</ref> An Ahmadiyya mosque was burned.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YIGJhKLhpE4 | title=Anti-Ahmadiyya Mullah Burning Ahmadiyya Mosques \u2013 Indonesia | publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> Human rights groups objected to the restrictions on religious freedom. On 6 February 2011 some Ahmadiyya members were killed at [[Pandeglang]], [[Banten]] province.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html |title=Six killed in clash between villagers and Ahmadiyah followers |work=The Jakarta Post |date=6 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827070711/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html |archivedate=27 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the past few years there has been an increase in attacks on religious freedom, including incidents of physical abuse, preventing groups from performing prayers, and burning their mosques. Data from the Setara Institute for Democracy and Peace show 17, 18, and 64 incidents for the years 2008, 2009 and 2010 respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2011/feb/18/indonesia-pluralism-persecution-ahmadiyah | title=Indonesia is no longer a poster child for pluralism | author=Gillian Terzis |work=The Guardian  | date=18 February 2011}}</ref> Although the data cover persecution of all religions, the recent persecution of Ahmadis is significant and severe, followed by persecution of Christians and persecution of other Islamic sects who claim to be \"genuine/pure/fundamentalist Muslims\".\n\nAs of 2011, the sect faces widespread calls for a total \"ban\" in Indonesia.<ref>McGeown, Kate. \"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-13155924 Islamic sect Ahmadiyah faces ban in Indonesia]\" ''[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]]''. 21 April 2011. (Video)</ref> On 6 February 2011, hundreds of mainstream Muslims surrounded an Ahmadiyya household and beat three people to death. Footage of the bludgeoning of their naked bodies \u2013 while policeman looked on \u2013 was posted on the internet and subsequently broadcast on international media.<ref>Allard, Tom. [http://www.smh.com.au/world/trial-begins-after-shocking-mob-violence-ends-in-slaying-20110426-1dv37.html Trial begins after shocking mob violence ends in slaying]. ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. 27 April 2011.</ref>\n\n====2008====\nIn 2008, many Muslims in [[Indonesia]] protested against the Ahmadiyya movement. With violence and large demonstrations, these religious conservatives put pressure on the government to monitor, and harass the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community in Indonesia.<ref>[http://new.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466 Indonesia to ban Ahmadi activities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724170308/http://new.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466 |date=24 July 2009 }}, 06/09/2008</ref> Public opinion in Indonesia is split in three ways on how Ahmadiyya should be treated: (a) some hold it should be banned outright on the basis that it is a heretical and deviant sect that is not listed as an officially recognised religion in Indonesia; (b) others hold that it should not be banned because of the freedom of religion article in the Constitution, but also should not be allowed to proselytise under the banner of \"Islam\" on the basis that this is misleading; (c) still others hold that it should be free to do and say as it pleases based on the Constitutional right to freedom of religion.<ref>\"[http://markings-reflections.blogspot.com/2008/04/indonesia-shadows-over-freedom_30.html= Ahmadiyya Ban and Human Rights]\", Fazil Jamal on Jakarta Post {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In June 2008, a law was passed to curtail \"proselytizing\" by Ahmadiyya members.<ref>''[http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466&size=A Indonesia to ban Ahmadi activities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724170308/http://new.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466 |date=24 July 2009 }}'', AsiaNews.IT</ref>{{Better source|reason=see WP:RSN|date=April 2015}}  An Ahmadiyya mosque was burned.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YIGJhKLhpE4 Anti-Ahmadiyya Mullah Burning Ahmadiyya Mosques \u2013 Indonesia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725063436/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YIGJhKLhpE4 |date=25 July 2015 }}, Al Jazeera News Report</ref> Human rights groups objected to the restrictions on religious freedom.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSJAK90261 Indonesia's religious tolerance under threat-group] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624190737/http://www.reuters.com/article/latestcrisis/idusjak90261 |date=24 June 2009 }}, 10 June 2008.</ref> A government decree adopted in 2008 under pressure from Islamic conservatives bans the sect from spreading its faith.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_631949.html|title=Religious clash in Indonesia kills up to six, Straits Times, 6 Feb 2011|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209031134/http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_631949.html|archive-date=9 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\n\nIn July 2010, a mob of 200 Indonesians surrounded an Ahmadi mosque in [[Manislor]] village in [[Kuningan district]], [[West Java]]. The mob pelted the mosque with stones before being dispersed by the police.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2010/07/2010729151640257216.html Indonesia mob attacks Muslim sect] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805042105/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2010/07/2010729151640257216.html |date=5 August 2010 }}. Al Jazeera English.  29 July 2010</ref>\n\n====2011====\nOn 6 February 2011 three (originally reported as six, and later amended) Ahmadiyya members were killed at [[Pandeglang]], [[Banten]] province, in a clash between locals.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=6 February 2011|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html|title=Six killed in clash between villagers and Ahmadiyah followers|accessdate=17 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827070711/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html|archivedate=27 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While the government did instruct police to hunt the killers, it also called on Ahmadiyya to abide by the 2008 decree and stop spreading their belief.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=6 February 2011|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/govt-instructs-police-hunt-killers-calls-ahmadiyah-abide-decree.html|title=Govt instructs police to hunt killers, calls on Ahmadiyah to abide by decree|accessdate=17 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208212025/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/govt-instructs-police-hunt-killers-calls-ahmadiyah-abide-decree.html|archive-date=8 February 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011 the prosecuting sought sentences of between five and seven months for the defendants, an act that caused outcry by rights activists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/activists-cry-foul-at-lenient-prosecutors-in-ahmadiyah-trial/451544 |title=Activists Cry Foul at 'Lenient' Prosecutors in Ahmadiyah Trial |work=[[The Jakarta Globe]] |author=Elisabeth Oktofani & Chrestella Tan |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=28 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810223656/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/activists-cry-foul-at-lenient-prosecutors-in-ahmadiyah-trial/451544 |archive-date=10 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The verdict given was between three and six months, slightly lighter than sought. This has trigger criticism from human right defenders and the international community including the US and the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/29/cikeusik-verdict-%E2%80%98chilling%E2%80%99-message-minorities.html |title=Cikeusik verdict 'chilling' message to minorities |work=thejakartapost.com |accessdate=29 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012131741/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/29/cikeusik-verdict-%E2%80%98chilling%E2%80%99-message-minorities.html |archivedate=12 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In addition, a Cikeusik Ahmadi leader, Deden Darmawan Sudjana, was also sentenced to six months in prison for physical abuse and acts against the state, refusing an order from a police officer who told him to leave the house.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/08/15/cikeusik-ahmadi-leader-gets-6-months-prison.html |title=Cikeusik Ahmadi leader gets 6 months prison |date=15 August 2011 |access-date=16 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111212124034/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/08/15/cikeusik-ahmadi-leader-gets-6-months-prison.html |archive-date=12 December 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A US State Department spokeswoman said they were \"disappointed\" with the verdict, while an activist of the New York-based [[Human Rights Watch]], called it \"the [[Taliban]]ization of Indonesia\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.kompas.com/read/2011/08/16/05051048/The.Reason.Why.US.Disappointed.with.Indonesia.Court.Ruling |title=The Reason Why US 'Disappointed' with Indonesia Court Ruling |date=16 August 2011 |access-date=16 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007174944/http://english.kompas.com/read/2011/08/16/05051048/The.Reason.Why.US.Disappointed.with.Indonesia.Court.Ruling |archive-date=7 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\nIn April 2009, the Selangor Islamic Religious Council of Malaysia issued a letter that forbade members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community from offering [[Jumah|Friday prayers]] at their central mosque. Moreover, Ahmadis failure to comply with the order would result in imprisonment of up to one year and/or a fine up to 3000 Malaysian [[ringgit]]. A large notice outside the mosque states ''Qadiani Bukan Agama Islam'', which translates to ''Qadiani [Ahmadiyyat] is not Islam.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenutgraph.com/mais-forbids-ahmadiyya-worship/|title=MAIS forbids Ahmadiyya worship|publisher=thenutgraph|accessdate=26 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113150119/http://www.thenutgraph.com/mais-forbids-ahmadiyya-worship|archive-date=13 January 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/press/09/my090428.html|title=ISLAMIC COUNCIL IN MALAYSIA ISSUES NOTICE TO AHMADIYYA MUSLIM JAMAAT PREVENTING USE OF CENTRAL MOSQUE|publisher=thepersecution|accessdate=26 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023024929/http://www.thepersecution.org/press/09/my090428.html|archive-date=23 October 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Palestine===\n{{main|Ahmadiyya in Palestine}}\nAhmadis were reported to be persecuted in the Palestinian Authority-controlled areas in 2010.<ref name=it0706>{{cite web|url=http://www.israeltoday.co.il/default.aspx?tabid=178&nid=21250|title=Palestinian Muslims who reject violence are persecuted|work=israeltoday.co.il|access-date=24 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201709/http://www.israeltoday.co.il/default.aspx?tabid=178&nid=21250|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, Mohammed Sharif Odeh, head of the Ahmadi community in Israel, told Arutz Sheva radio that the Palestinian Authority is \"encouraging the cold-blooded murder of Ahmadis\" by failing to take concrete action to protect the community.<ref name=it0706/>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\n{{Main|Ahmadiyya in Saudi Arabia|Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia}}\nAhmadis are persecuted in [[Saudi Arabia]] on an ongoing basis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Persecution of Ahmadis in Saudi Arabia|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/press/08/sp080324.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> In a 2006\u20132007 nationwide campaign to track down and deport Ahmadi Muslim foreign workers, the Saudi religious police arrested 56\u201360<ref>Depending on the source there were 56\u201360 Ahmadis arrested in the years 2006\u20132007</ref> Although there are many foreign workers and Saudi citizens belonging to the Ahmadiyya sect in Saudi Arabia,<ref name=\"hrw2014\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/05/15/saudi-arabia-2-years-behind-bars-apostasy-accusation | title=Saudi Arabia: 2 Years Behind Bars on Apostasy Accusation | date=15 May 2014 | publisher=Human Rights Watch | accessdate=1 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304153400/http://www.hrw.org/news/2014/05/15/saudi-arabia-2-years-behind-bars-apostasy-accusation | archive-date=4 March 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2007/90220.htm | title=Saudi Arabia: International Religious Freedom Report 2007 | publisher=U.S. Department of State | accessdate=7 March 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/resources/AR_2007/saudi_arabia.pdf | title=Saudi Arabia | publisher=United States Commission on International Religious Freedom | accessdate=7 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720220618/http://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/resources/AR_2007/saudi_arabia.pdf | archive-date=20 July 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Persecution of Ahmadis in Saudi Arabia|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/press/08/sp080324.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=11 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223210226/http://www.thepersecution.org/press/08/sp080324.html|archive-date=23 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Ahmadis are officially banned from entering the country and from performing the [[Hajj]] and [[Umrah]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].<ref name=\"Figueira\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=heIft-h0aRcC&pg=PA47&dq=&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dCoyVZ2PLZTXapSngIAM&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Jihad in Trinidad and Tobago, July 27, 1990 | author= Daurius Figueira | page=47}}</ref><ref name=\"B\u00f6wering\">{{cite encyclopaedia | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q1I0pcrFFSUC&pg=PA25&dq&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ew00VcVfg_Zq7Z6ByAg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Princeton Encyclopedia of Islamic Political Thought | author=Gerhard B\u00f6wering, Patricia Crone | page=25-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tuVhBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&dq&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HnHzVPqLM8HOaNvugfgB&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The State as an Actor in Religion Policy: Policy Cycle and Governance | author=Maria Grazia Martino | accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2007, [[Human Rights Watch]] sent an open letter to the [[King of Saudi Arabia|Saudi king]] [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]] asking him to cease religious persecution of the Ahmadi faith in Saudi Arabia. Two letters were sent in November 2006 and February 2007 asking him to remove the travel ban on critics of the Saudi government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hrw.org/english/docs/2007/02/09/saudia15305.htm|title=Letter to King Abdullah|work=HRW|date=8 February 2007|accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Saudi authorities arrested two Saudi Sunni Muslim citizens for their conversion to Ahmadiyya Islam.<ref>U.S. Department of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor, [https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/208622.pdf International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Saudi Arabia] (20 May 2013).</ref> They were arrested three months after joining the Ahmadiyya and refusing to abandon their beliefs. As of May 2014, the two accused of apostasy had served two years in prison awaiting trial. They have not been released since then.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/May-15/256556-hrw-urges-saudi-to-free-two-ahmadis-held-for-apostasy.ashx#axzz3BwArkFYL HAW urges Saudi to free two Ahmadis held for apostasy], The Daily Star, Lebanon News (15 May 2014).</ref><ref name=\"hrw2014\"/>\n\n===Singapore===\n{{Main|Persecution of Ahmadis in Singapore}}\n\n===United Kingdom===\n\nAhmadis in the UK have endured killings, mass protests by other Muslims against Ahmadi mosque construction,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/dec/08/ahmadi-mosque-walsall-protests|title=Freedom of worship for Ahmadis|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=8 December 2010|date=8 December 2009|location=London|first=Inayat|last=Bunglawala}}</ref> and threats and intimidation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hate-leaflets-calling-killing-ahmadi-muslims-distributed-across-london-1553591|title=Hate leaflets calling for killing of Ahmadi Muslims distributed across London|first=Tom|last=Porter|date=8 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>  In March 2016, the [[First Minister of Scotland]], [[Nicola Sturgeon]], attended the wake of an Ahmadi, Asad Shah, 40, killed by a Sunni, Tanveer Ahmed, 32, in what the police characterised as \"religious prejudice\".<ref>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/asad-shah-nicola-sturgeon-joins-7631680#61qK6RXGmriEduSA.97 Asad Shah: Nicola Sturgeon joins 500 people at vigil as defiant locals declare 'This is not who we are'] dailyrecord.co.uk 25 March 2016.</ref> In April 2016, leaflets calling for death to Ahmadis were found in Stockwell Green mosque.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35928848|title='Kill Ahmadis' leaflets found in UK mosque \u2013 BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/25/muslim-council-of-britain-ahmadi-asad-shah|title=The Muslim Council of Britain is failing Ahmadis like Asad Shah|date=2016-04-25|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref> The mosque claimed that it was unaware of the leaflets being placed on its premises. The leaflets were authored in the name of an ex-head, [[Muhammad Yusuf Ludhianvi|Yusuf Ludhianvi]], of [[Khatme Nubuwwat Academy|Khatam-e-Nabuwwat (or Khatme Nabuwwat)]] \u2013 an anti-Ahmadiyya organization. The organization is fully known as Almi Majlis-e-Tahafuz Khatmi Nubuwat or the International Committee for the Protection of the Finality of Prophethood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.albalagh.net/current_affairs/yusuf_ludhianvi.shtml|title=Renowned Scholar Maulana Yusuf Ludhianvi Martyred in Karachi|website=www.albalagh.net|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\n====2009====\nIn 2009 a demonstration consisting of mainly Muslims was held in [[Walsall]] to prevent Ahmadis acquiring a mosque.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/dec/08/ahmadi-mosque-walsall-protests|title=Freedom of worship for Ahmadis|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=8 December 2010|date=8 December 2009|location=London|first=Inayat|last=Bunglawala|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908182840/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/dec/08/ahmadi-mosque-walsall-protests|archive-date=8 September 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nIn 2010, in the wake of the [[May 2010 attacks on Ahmadi mosques in Lahore|May 2010 attacks]] on two Ahmadi mosques in Lahore, Pakistan, members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community living in the UK were threatened and intimidated. Certain Muslim groups in [[South London]] distributed leaflets asking readers to kill Ahmadis and boycott their businesses, and Ahmadi mosques in Crawley and Newham were vandalised. In October 2010 [[Ofcom]] criticised the UK-based [[Ummah Channel]] for broadcasting three interactive television programmes before and after the Lahore massacre of Ahmadi Muslims in May 2010, in which religious leaders and callers alike said that Ahmadis should be killed. These programmes were repeated several times. Ofcom stated that the programme's abusive treatment of the religious views and beliefs of members of the Ahmadiyya community breached UK broadcasting regulations.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hardliners-call-for-deaths-of-surrey-muslims-2112268.html|title=Hardliners call for deaths of Surrey Muslims|publisher=The Independent|date=21 October 2010|accessdate=21 October 2010|location=London|first=Jerome|last=Taylor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606052751/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hardliners-call-for-deaths-of-surrey-muslims-2112268.html|archive-date=6 June 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ahmadiyya Debate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=6641|title=Ahmadiyya Debate|publisher=Parliament of United Kingdom|accessdate=22 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725130152/http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=6641|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNasser Butt, a [[Liberal Democrat (United Kingdom)|Liberal Democrat]] parliamentary candidate for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election]] was targeted by a campaign that asked Muslims not to vote for him because of his faith. In the election, hustings in the Tooting Islamic centre, a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate, Mark Clarke, was mistaken for Butt and had to be locked in a room for his safety.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/ahmadiyya/8451614.Election_race_infected_by_anti_Ahmadiyya_hate_campaign/ | title=Tooting election race infected by anti-Ahmadiyya hate campaign | accessdate=5 April 2011 | date=14 October 2010 | publisher=Wimbledon Guardian | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021061949/http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/ahmadiyya/8451614.Election_race_infected_by_anti_Ahmadiyya_hate_campaign/ | archive-date=21 October 2010 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nImam Suliman Gani, of the (Sunni) Tooting Islamic Centre, called for a boycott of Ahmadi shops, stating: \"Since the Qadianis are routinely deceptive about their religion, there was a potential risk of Muslims being offered meat that wasn't necessarily halal.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oakes|first1=Omar|title=Worshippers told at Tooting Islamic Centre to boycott Ahmadiyya shops|url=http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/8451539.Worshippers_told_to_boycott_Ahma%20diyya_shops/|accessdate=10 August 2016|work=Wimbledon Guardian|issue=14 October 2010|quote=Ahmadi shopkeepers face financial ruin after clerics demanded a boycott of their shops.  Imam Suliman Gani, of the TIC, admitted he personally pleaded with the owner of the Lahore Halal Meat in Tooting not to sell his business to an Ahmadi man.  He said: \"Since the Qadianis are routinely deceptive about their religion, there was a potential risk of Muslims being offered meat that wasn't necessarily halal.\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812111659/http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/8451539.Worshippers_told_to_boycott_Ahma%20diyya_shops/|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n\n=====Murder of Asad Shah=====\nIn March 2016, an Ahmadi Scottish shopkeeper [[Asad Shah]] was stabbed to death in Glasgow after wishing people a Happy Easter on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/uk/337257-scottish-muslim-shopkeeper-killed/|title=Muslim shopkeeper who wrote loving Easter posts stabbed to death in 'religiously prejudiced' attack|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510102836/https://www.rt.com/uk/337257-scottish-muslim-shopkeeper-killed/|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The [[Daily Mail]] reported:  \"police suspect the incident was 'religiously prejudiced' and have arrested a 32-year-old Muslim man belonging to the rival Sunni sect over the murder.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3512546/Police-investigating-murder-Asad-Shah-seized-Uber-taxi.html|title=Police investigating murder Asad Shah have seized an Uber car|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510155347/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3512546/Police-investigating-murder-Asad-Shah-seized-Uber-taxi.html|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 29 March 2016, the murderer's name was revealed as Tanveer Ahmed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-35918547 | title=Asad Shah death: Man in court charged with murder | publisher=BBC | date=29 March 2016 | accessdate=29 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329152741/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-35918547 | archive-date=29 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>  On 6 April 2016, Tanveer Ahmed stated \"that he killed Asad Shah,\" and claimed \"if I had not done this others would\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cramb|first1=Auslan|title=Man from Bradford admits killing Glasgow shopkeeper Asad Shah|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/06/man-from-bradford-admits-killing-glasgow-shopkeeper-asad-shah/|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=6 April 2016|quote=said it was because he \"disrespected\" Islam.   Tanveer Ahmed, 32, said in a statement that he killed Asad Shah, 40, claiming: \"if I had not done this others would\".|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408082452/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/06/man-from-bradford-admits-killing-glasgow-shopkeeper-asad-shah/|archive-date=8 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  An Ahmadi anti-extremism campaign was launched in Glasgow, with attendance of Ahmadi Muslims, Christian, Sikh, and Jewish leaders, but no Muslims belonging to other sects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/apr/18/scottish-muslim-groups-ahmadi-anti-extremism-campaign-launch-glasgow|title=Scottish Muslim groups fail to attend Ahmadi anti-extremism event|first=Libby Brooks Scotland|last=correspondent|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|via=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328100118/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/apr/18/scottish-muslim-groups-ahmadi-anti-extremism-campaign-launch-glasgow|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The murderer pleaded guilty to the \"religiously-motivated murder.\"  Part of the family of the victim is emigrating away from Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-37021385|title=Asad Shah killing: 'Disrespecting Islam' murderer jailed|date=9 August 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|via=www.bbc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314112440/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-37021385|archive-date=14 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=====Hate leaflets=====\nIn April 2016, leaflets were distributed across London's universities, mosques and shopping centres, calling for the killing of Ahmadis. The leaflets were by [[Muhammad Yusuf Ludhianvi]], with the [[Khatme Nubuwwat Academy|Khatme Nubuwwat organisation]] on the front cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hate-leaflets-calling-killing-ahmadi-muslims-distributed-across-london-1553591|title=Hate leaflets calling for killing of Ahmadi Muslims distributed across London|first=Tom|last=Porter|date=8 April 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415034819/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hate-leaflets-calling-killing-ahmadi-muslims-distributed-across-london-1553591|archive-date=15 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\n\nIn October 2017, [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[File on 4]]'' programme investigated the publication and broadcasting of anti-Ahmadiyyah material in the UK, and asked when and whether media regulators should intervene.<ref name=\"BBC File on 4 2017\">{{cite episode| title= Extremism: Hidden in Plain Sight| episodelink= | series= [[File on 4]]| credits= Presenter: [[Manveen Rana]]; Producers:  Richard Fenton-Smith & Sajid Iqbal; Editor: Gail Champion | network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b096hczb | airdate= 3 October 2017| accessdate= 3 October 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[Muslim Television Ahmadiyya International|MTA International]] has produced four documentaries regarding the persecution of [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] over the last century.\n\n* The Early Years\n* 1953\n* 1974\n* 1984 \u2013 present (2008)\n\n[[Ummah Channel]], broadcast three interactive programs against Ahmadis in the wake of [[May 2010 attacks on Ahmadi mosques in Lahore|Lahore massacre]]<ref name=\"Taylor\" /><ref name=\"Ahmadiyya Debate\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/whall/?id=2010-10-20a.284.0|title=Ahmadiyya Community, Westminster Hall Debate|publisher=TheyWorkForYou.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026214828/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/whall/?id=2010-10-20a.284.0|archive-date=26 October 2010|accessdate=28 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[Ofcom]] criticized [[Ummah Channel]] for doing this.\n\nA UK-based [[Urdu]] TV station, namely Channel 44, was fined by [[Ofcom]] on 15 April 2019 for hate speech and for being \u201canti-ahmadi\u201d. As a result, Channel 44 was fined \u00a375,000 amid growing fears of the persecution of Ahmadis.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murphy|first=Simon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/15/uk-based-tv-station-channel-44-fined-anti-ahmadi-muslim-hate-speech|title=UK-based TV station fined for anti-Ahmadi Muslim hate speech|date=15 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/816434/annual-report-18-19.pdf|title=Ofcom Annual report 2018-2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Ofcom GOV UK|page=33|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724080645/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/816434/annual-report-18-19.pdf|archive-date=24 July 2019|access-date=2 April 2020|quote=We are currently considering imposing sanctions for other serious breaches. These include: prolonged hate speech against the Ahmadiyya community which was not justified by the context (broadcast on Channel 44)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tobitt|first=Charlotte|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/ofcom-fines-channel-44-city-news-network-75000-for-hate-speech-against-ahmadiyya-community/|title=Ofcom fines UK Urdu-language news channel \u00a375,000 for 'hate speech' against Muslim group|date=15 April 2019|work=Press Gazette|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-Ahmadiyya organisations==\nPolitical groups associated with the persecution of the [[Ahmadis]] include the [[Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam]], [[Khatme Nabuwwat]] movements<ref>{{cite book | first1=Ala | last1=Al-Hammarneh | first2=Jorn | last2=Thielmann | title=Islam and Muslims in Germany | page=317 | publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |date=January 2008}}</ref> ([[Majlis-e-Tahaffuz-e-Khatme Nabuwwat]], [[Pasban Khatme Nabuwwat]], [[Tanzeem-e-Islami]] and Tehreek-e-Khatme Nabuwwat), [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]], [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan]] and [[Tehreek-i-Labbaik Pakistan]].<ref>Saeed, S. (2007), Pakistani Nationalism and the State Marginalisation of the Ahmadiyya Community in Pakistan. Studies in Ethnicity and Nationalism, 7: 132\u2013152. {{doi|10.1111/j.1754-9469.2007.tb00166.x}}</ref>\n\n==Leaders of groups associated with the persecution of Ahmadis==\n* [[Maulana Sanaullah Amratsari]], Fateh Qadyan (conqueror of Ahmdiyya)\n* [[Syed Ata Ullah Shah Bukhari]], founder of Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam\n* [[Syed Abuzar Bukhari]], former president of majlis-e-ahrar\n* [[Muhammad Yusuf Ludhianvi]], leader of Khatm-e-Nubuwwat\n* Abdul Latif Khalid Cheema, Secretary General of Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam\n* [[Agha Shorish Kashmiri]], editor of chattan\n* [[Janbaz Mirza]], editor of tabsarah\n\n==Discrimination and pejorative terms by Muslims==\n\n===Terms===\n[[Qadiani]] and [[Mirzai]] are the pejorative terms used by non-Ahmadi Muslims from the Indian subcontinent.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Islamic schools and branches]]\n*[[Sectarian violence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Religious persecution}}\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/ Website about persecution of Ahmadis]\n*[http://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/MunirInquiry-Report-Urdu.pdf Justice Munir Enquiry Report on Anti-Ahmadiyya riots of 1953 (Urdu)]\n*[http://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/Munir-Inquiry-Report-English.pdf Justice Munir Enquiry Report on Anti-Ahmadiyya riots of 1953 (English)]\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/category/pakistan/ Persecution of Ahmadis in Pakistan]\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/facts-in-figures/ Facts and Figures]\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/martyrs/ Pictures of those Martyred in 1974]\n*[http://www.alislam.org/egazette/press-release/ahmadis-murdered-for-their-faith-in-pakistan-during-2009/ Ahmadis Murdered During 2009]\n* 8 part [[Muslim Television Ahmadiyya International|MTA]] series ''1974 \u2013 From Democracy to Extremism'': [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GEzYkgThDBY 1] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z8H2J_2hFn8 2] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qiXRURLpV2U 3] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2JpfolM-NHI 4] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j_B1Vfn3xg8 5] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KC7dwF6c3Ck 6] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z4gd690TG_Y 7] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LQTnp57kOmc 8] (2013)\n*{{YouTube|CBg0pf9vxio|Solid Eveidence of political interference against Ahmadiyya Jammat in 1974}}\n\n{{Religious persecution}}\n\n{{Ahmadiyya topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Persecution Of Ahmadis}}\n[[Category:Persecution of Ahmadis| ]]\n[[Category:Islam in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Islam in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Islam in India]]\n[[Category:Islam in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Persecution by Muslims]]\n\n[[de:Ahmadiyya#Verfolgung]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Ahmadiyya|Miscellaneous}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar}}\nThe [[Ahmadiyya]] sect of Islam has been subject to various forms of [[religious persecution]] and discrimination since the movement's inception in 1889.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-persecutes-a-muslim-minority-1512087028|title=Pakistan Persecutes a Muslim Minority|access-date=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202013140/https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-persecutes-a-muslim-minority-1512087028|archive-date=2 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The Ahmadiyya Muslim movement emerged from the [[Sunni]] tradition of [[Islam]] and its adherents believe in all the [[Five Pillars of Islam|five pillars]] and [[Islamic theology#Six articles of belief|articles of faith]] required of Muslims.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/faith/article4009445.ece \"The Ahmadi Muslim Community. Who are the Ahmadi Muslims and what do they believe? Waqar Ahmad Ahmedi gives a brief introduction to the Ahmadi branch of Islam.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919230108/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/faith/article4009445.ece |date=19 September 2008 }} ''Times Online''. 27 May 2008.</ref> Ahmadis are considered non-Muslims by many mainstream Muslims since they consider [[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]], the founder of the movement, to be the promised [[Mahdi]] and [[Messiah]] awaited by the Muslims.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.alislam.org/books/3in1/chap2/index.html | title=An Enemy a Disbeliever a Liar, Claims of Hadhrat Ahmad | publisher=Islam International Publications | author=Naeem Osman Memon | year=1994 | isbn=1-85372-552-8 | access-date=21 January 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927020328/http://www.alislam.org/books/3in1/chap2/index.html | archive-date=27 September 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.alislam.org/books/truth/reflection.html | title=Truth about Ahmadiyyat, Reflection of all the Prophets | publisher=London Mosque | author=B.A Rafiq | year=1978 | isbn=0-85525-013-5 | access-date=21 January 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315131142/http://www.alislam.org/books/truth/reflection.html | archive-date=15 March 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/revelationration00ahma | title=Revelation Rationality Knowledge and Truth, Future of Revelation | publisher=Islam International Publications | author=Mirza Tahir Ahmad | authorlink=Mirza Tahir Ahmad | year=1998 | isbn=1-85372-640-0 | access-date=21 January 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all | url-access=registration }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = The Handbook of Transcultural Counselling and Psychotherapy|publisher = [[McGraw-Hill Education]]|year = 2011|isbn = 9780335238514|location = UK|editor-last = Lago|editor-first = Colin|publication-date = 1 October 2011|page = 312|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9vREBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA312&lpg=PA312|access-date = 19 April 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150905205049/https://books.google.com/books?id=9vREBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA312&lpg=PA312|archive-date = 5 September 2015|url-status = live|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Ahmadis are active translators of the [[Qur'an]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bedi |first1=Manokriti |title=Quran\u2019s Punjabi translation flies off the shelves   Read more at: http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/25791298.cms |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Qurans-Punjabi-translation-flies-off-the-shelves/articleshow/25791298.cms |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=The Times of India |publisher=Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd   Read more at: http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/25790783.cms |date=13 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912003408/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Qurans-Punjabi-translation-flies-off-the-shelves/articleshow/25791298.cms |archive-date=12 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tahana |first1=Yvonne |title=Koran's message of unity shared in te reo translation |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10638407 |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=The New Zealand Herald |publisher=NZME Publishing, Ltd. |date=14 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014847/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10638407 |archive-date=10 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hovel |first1=Revital |title=Muslim Sect Celebrates 25 Years Since Koran Translated Into Yiddish |url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/yiddish-koran-has-25th-birthday-1.5291959 |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=Haaretz |publisher=Haaretz Daily Newspaper Ltd |date=28 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731001528/https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/yiddish-koran-has-25th-birthday-1.5291959 |archive-date=31 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and proselytizers for the faith.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who are the Ahmadi? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8711026.stm |accessdate=9 September 2018 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530013220/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8711026.stm |archive-date=30 May 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, in a number of countries, Ahmadis have faced strong resistance. In many Muslim-majority nations, Ahmadis have been considered heretics and non-Muslim, and subjected to persecution and systematic, sometimes state-sanctioned, oppression.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.theasa.org/conferences/asa04/panels/panel21.htm \"Localising Diaspora: the Ahmadi Muslims and the problem of multi-sited ethnography\".] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819140154/http://www.theasa.org/conferences/asa04/panels/panel21.htm |date=19 August 2006 }} Association of Social Anthropologists, 2004 conference panel.</ref>\n\nThe [[Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan]] and [[Ordinance XX]] declare Ahmadis to be non-Muslims and further deprive them of religious rights. Hundreds of Ahmadis were killed in the [[1953 Lahore riots]] and the [[1974 Anti-Ahmadiyya riots]].  The [[Lahore massacre|May 2010 Attacks on Ahmadi mosques]], infamously known as the [[2010 Ahmadiyya mosques massacre|Lahore Massacre]], resulted in the murder of 84 Ahmadis by suicide attack. The 1974 riots resulted in the largest number of killings of Ahmadis.\n\n==Pakistan==\n{{Status of religious freedom |persecution}}\n{{see also|Ahmadiyya in Pakistan}}\n\n[[File:Kalima erasing from Ahmadiyya-Mosque.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Shahada]], the basic [[creed]] of Islam and of Ahmadi Muslims being erased by Pakistani police]]\nApproximately 2\u20135 million Ahmadis live in Pakistan, which has the largest population of Ahmadis in the world.<ref>The 1998 Pakistani census states that there are 291,000 (0.22%) Ahmadis in Pakistan. However, the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community has boycotted the census since 1974 which renders official Pakistani figures to be inaccurate. Independent groups have estimated the Pakistani Ahmadiyya population to be somewhere between 2 million and 5 million Ahmadis. However, the 4 million figure is the most quoted figure. See:\n*over 2 million: {{cite web | publisher= Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada | title= Pakistan: The situation of Ahmadis, including legal status and political, education and employment rights; societal attitudes toward Ahmadis (2006 \u2013 Nov. 2008) | date= 4 December 2008 |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/49913b5f2c.html | accessdate= 28 June 2012}}\n*3 million: International Federation for Human Rights: ''International Fact-Finding Mission. Freedoms of Expression, of Association and of Assembly in Pakistan.'' Ausgabe 408/2, Januar 2005, S. 61 ([http://www.fidh.org/IMG/pdf/pk408a-2.pdf PDF])\n*3\u20134 million: Commission on International Religious Freedom: ''Annual Report of the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom.'' 2005, S. 130\n*4.910.000:  James Minahan: Encyclopedia of the stateless nations. Ethnic and national groups around the world. Greenwood Press . Westport 2002, page 52\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=country&category=&publisher=IRBC&type=QUERYRESPONSE&coi=PAK&rid=&docid=45f1478f20&skip=0 | title=Pakistan: Situation of members of the Lahori Ahmadiyya Movement in Pakistan | accessdate=30 April 2014 }}</ref> It is the only state to have officially declared the Ahmadis to be non-Muslims as they do not consider Muhammad to be the final prophet;<ref name=hoque/> and their freedom of religion has been curtailed by a series of ordinances, acts and constitutional amendments. In 1974, [[Pakistan]]'s parliament adopted a law declaring Ahmadis to be non-Muslims;<ref>Khan, Naveeda. [http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf \"Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626215625/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf |date=26 June 2011 }}. Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 184.</ref> the country's constitution was amended to define a Muslim \"as a person who believes in the finality of the Prophet Muhammad\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/amendments/2amendment.html | title=Constitution (Second Amendment) Act, 1974 | accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> In 1984, [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|General Zia-ul-Haq]], the then military ruler of Pakistan, issued [[Ordinance XX]].<ref>The presentation before the parliament can be seen here: {{cite book |url=http://www.alislam.org/urdu/pdf/Mahzarnama.pdf | title=Mahzaharnama | author=Khan, Naveeda | publisher=Islam International Publications | isbn=1-85372-386-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  |url=http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf  |title=Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark  |author=Khan, Naveeda  |url-status=dead  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626215625/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/bin/i/d/Trespasses.pdf  |archivedate=26 June 2011  |df=dmy-all  }} Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 178.</ref> The ordinance, which was supposed to prevent \"anti-Islamic activities\", forbids Ahmadis to call themselves Muslim or to \"pose as Muslims\". This means that they are not allowed to profess the Islamic creed publicly or call their places of worship mosques.<ref>Heiner Bielefeldt: \"Muslim Voices in the Human Rights Debate\", ''Human rights quarterly,'' 1995 vol. 17 no. 4 p. 587.</ref> Although a derogatory religious slur,<ref>{{cite book| author = Antonio R. Gualtieri| title = Conscience and Coercion: Ahmadis and Orthodoxy in Pakistan| url = https://books.google.com/?id=iCwHaOabz7YC&pg=PA14| year = 1989| publisher = Guernica Editions| isbn = 978-0-920717-41-7| page = 14 }}</ref> the terms '[[Qadiani]]', 'Qadianism', 'Mirzai' and 'Mirzaian' are widely used in Pakistan to refer to Ahmadis and Qadiani is also the term used by the government in its constitution.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fmu.gov.pk/docs/laws/Pakistan%20Penal%20Code.pdf |title=Pakistan Penal Code, Official Pakistani Government document Chap. XV \"Of Offences Relating to Religion\" | pages=79\u201381}}</ref>\n\nAhmadis in Pakistan are also barred by law from worshipping in non-Ahmadi mosques or public prayer rooms, performing the Muslim call to prayer, using the traditional Islamic greeting in public, publicly quoting from the Quran, preaching in public, seeking converts, or producing, publishing, and disseminating their religious materials. These acts are punishable by imprisonment of up to three years.<ref name=\"globalsecurity\"/> In applying for a passport or a national ID card, all Pakistanis are required to sign an oath declaring Mirza Ghulam Ahmad to be an impostor prophet and all Ahmadis to be non-Muslims.<ref name=\"hanif\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/8744092.stm|title= Why Pakistan's Ahmadi community is officially detested |date= 16 June 2010|work=BBC News|first=Mohammed|last=Hanif|authorlink=Mohammed Hanif}}</ref> The word \"''Muslim''\" was erased from the gravestone of the [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel prize]] winning [[Theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] [[Abdus Salam]], because he was an Ahmadi.<ref name=\"hanif\"/>\n\nAs a result of the cultural implications of the laws and constitutional amendments regarding Ahmadis in Pakistan, persecution and hate-related incidents are constantly reported from different parts of the country. Ahmadis have been the target of many attacks led by various religious groups.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/khan.shtml Persecution of the Ahmadiyya Community in Pakistan: An Analysis Under International Law and International Relations] ''Harvard Human Rights Journal'', Vol 16, September 2003<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4317998.stm \"Eight die in Pakistan sect attack\"], BBC News<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4131624.stm \"Sect offices closed in Pakistan\"], BBC News</ref> All religious seminaries and [[madrasa]]s in Pakistan belonging to different sects of Islam have prescribed essential reading materials specifically targeted at refuting Ahmadiyya beliefs.<ref>[http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf Denizens of Alien Worlds. T Rahman \u2013 Contemporary South Asia, 2004. A Survey of the Education System of Pakistan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616161323/http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf |date=16 June 2007 }}, by Tariq Rahman, page 15.</ref>\n\nFor the five million Ahmadis,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/DE/Aussenpolitik/Laender/Laenderinfos/01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten/Pakistan_node.html | work=Foreign Office (Germany) | title=The Federal Foreign Office Germany \u2013 Pakistan Info (German Language) | date=March 2012 | access-date=16 June 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727044713/http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/DE/Aussenpolitik/Laender/Laenderinfos/01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten/Pakistan_node.html | archive-date=27 July 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://translate.google.de/translate?sl=de&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&layout=2&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.auswaertiges-amt.de%2FDE%2FAussenpolitik%2FLaender%2FLaenderinfos%2F01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten%2FPakistan_node.html | work=Foreign Office (Germany) | title=The Federal Foreign Office Germany \u2013 Pakistan Info (English Translation) | date=March 2012 | access-date=16 June 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429201854/http://translate.google.de/translate?sl=de&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&layout=2&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.auswaertiges-amt.de%2FDE%2FAussenpolitik%2FLaender%2FLaenderinfos%2F01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten%2FPakistan_node.html | archive-date=29 April 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> religious persecution has been particularly severe and systematic in [[Pakistan]], which is the only state to have officially declared that Ahmadis are non-Muslims.<ref name=\"hoque\"/> Pakistani laws prohibit the Ahmadis from identifying themselves as Muslims, and their freedom of religion has been curtailed by a series of ordinances, Acts and constitutional amendments.<ref>Khan, Naveeda. [http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf \"Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605013014/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf |date=5 June 2010 }}. Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 184.</ref> \n\nAs a result, persecution and hate-related incidents are regularly reported from different parts of the country. Ahmadis have been the target of many violent attacks by various religious groups in Pakistan.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/khan.shtml \"Persecution of the Ahmadiyya Community in Pakistan: An Analysis Under International Law and International Relations\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917163148/http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/khan.shtml |date=17 September 2009 }} ''Harvard Human Rights Journal'', Vol 16, September 2003.<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4317998.stm \"Eight die in Pakistan sect attack\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930094915/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4317998.stm |date=30 September 2009 }}, BBC News<br>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4131624.stm \"Sect offices closed in Pakistan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402161927/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4131624.stm |date=2 April 2012 }}, BBC News</ref> ''[[Madrasah]]s'' of all sects of Islam in Pakistan prescribe reading materials for their students specifically targeted at refuting Ahmadiyya beliefs.<ref>Rahman, Tariq. [http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf \"Denizens of Alien Worlds: A Survey of the Education System of Pakistan\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616161323/http://uoit.ca/sas/Articles/DAW.pdf |date=16 June 2007 }} Contemporary South Asia, 2004. p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn a recent survey, students from many private schools of Pakistan expressed their opinions on religious tolerance in the country. The figures assembled in the study reflect that even among the educated classes of Pakistan, Ahmadis are considered the least deserving minority in terms of equal opportunities and civil rights. The teachers from these elite schools showed lower levels of tolerance towards Ahmadis than their pupils.<ref>[http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/pdsa/pdsa_01_01_04.pdf Peace and Democracy in South Asia], Volume 1, Number 1, January 2005. Passports to Privilege: The English-Medium Schools In Pakistan, Tariq Rahman. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327094050/http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/pdsa/pdsa_01_01_04.pdf |date=27 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAnother example is [[Abdus Salam]], the only recipient of the Nobel Prize for Physics who identified as a Muslim. For his mere allegiance to the [[Ahmadiyya]] sect, he had been ignored and excommunicated. There are no monuments or universities named after him. The word \"Muslim\" has been erased from his grave stone.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/8744092.stm |title=BBC News \u2013 Why Pakistan's Ahmadi community is officially detested |author=Mohammed Hanif |date=16 June 2010 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] |location=[[London, England|London]] |accessdate=30 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522195647/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/8744092.stm |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===1953===\n{{Main|Lahore riots of 1953}}\nIn 1953 at the instigation of religious parties, [[Lahore riots of 1953|anti-Ahmadiyya riots]] erupted in Pakistan, killing scores of Ahmadi Muslims and destroying their properties. There was severe agitations against the Ahmadis, including street protests, political rallies, and inflammatory articles. These agitations led to 200 Ahmadi deaths. Consequently, [[Governor-General of Pakistan|Governor-General]] [[Malik Ghulam Muhammad|Ghulam Muhammad]] implemented [[martial law]] and dismissed Pakistan's Federal Cabinet.<ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+pk0121) \"Pakistan: Jamaat-i-Islami\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083300/http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd%2Fcstdy%3A%40field%28DOCID+pk0121%29 |date=23 January 2016 }} Library of Congress Country Studies. April 1994.</ref>\n\n===1974 riots and constitutional amendment===\n{{main|1974 Anti-Ahmadiyya riots}}\nIn 1974, a violent campaign, led mainly by the [[Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam]] and [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]], began against the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] in Pakistan, on the pretext of a clash between Ahmadis and non-Ahmadis at the railway station of Rabwah. This campaign resulted in several [[Ahmadi]] casualties and destruction of Ahmadiyya property, including the desecration of mosques and graves.\n\nAs a result of pressure from this agitation, legislation and constitutional changes were enacted to criminalise the religious practises of Ahmadis by preventing them from claiming they are [[Muslim]] or from \"behaving\" as Muslims. These changes primarily came about due to the pressure of the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] King at the time, King [[Faisal of Saudi Arabia|Faisal]] bin As-Saud, according to Dr Mubashar Hassan, Prime Minister Bhutto's close confidant at the time. Pakistan's parliament adopted a law that declares Ahmadis non-Muslims. The country's constitution was amended to define a Muslim \"...as a person who believes in the finality of the Prophet Muhammad.\"<ref name=\"Act XLIX of 1974\">[[Constitution of Pakistan]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/part12.ch5.html#f685 Art. 260(3)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023165749/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/part12.ch5.html#f685 |date=23 October 2013 }}, added by [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/amendments/2amendment.html Constitution (Second Amendment) Act, 1974 (XLIX of 1974)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220154304/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/amendments/2amendment.html |date=20 February 2008 }} S. 3 and amended by [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/orders/po24_1985.html Constitution (Third Amendment) Order, 1985 (President's Order No. 24 of 1985)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003061700/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/constitution/orders/po24_1985.html |date=3 October 2014 }} S. 6</ref><ref name=\"PLD 1978 Lahore 113\">Cf. ''Abdur Rahman Mobashir vs. Syed Amir Ali Shah Bokhari'', [http://pakistanconstitutionlaw.com/pld-1978-lahore-113/ PLD 1978 Lahore 113] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429184922/http://pakistanconstitutionlaw.com/pld-1978-lahore-113/ |date=29 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Ordinance XX of 1984===\n{{Main|Ordinance XX}}\nOn 26 April 1984, [[General Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]], the President of Pakistan, issued the anti-Ahmadiyya Ordinance XX,<ref name=\"Ordinance XX of 1984\">[[Pakistan Penal Code|PPC]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f110 Ss. 298-B and 298-C] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624115719/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f110 |date=24 June 2014 }}, added by [http://www.real-islam.org/Humanrights/ordXX.html Anti-Islamic Activities of the Quadiani Group, Lahori Group and Ahmadis (Prohibition and Punishment) Ordinance, 1984 (XX of 1984)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002725/http://www.real-islam.org/Humanrights/ordXX.html |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> which effectively prohibited Ahmadis from preaching or professing their beliefs.<ref name=\"PLD 1985 FSC 8\">''Mujibur Rehman vs. Federal Government of Pakistan'', [http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort84.php PLD 1985 FSC 8] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403110040/http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort84.php |date=3 April 2015 }}, affirmed by ''Capt. (Retd.) Abdul Wajid vs. Federal Government of Pakistan'', [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/5/sup-court-of-pakistan.pdf PLD 1988 SC 167] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314130556/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/5/sup-court-of-pakistan.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"1993 SCMR 1718\">''Zaheeruddin vs. The State'', [http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort93.php 1993 SCMR 1718] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429182843/http://irshad.org/exposed/legal/pkcort93.php |date=29 April 2014 }}, affirming [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/7/bol-high-court-1987.pdf PLD 1988 Quetta 22] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314125011/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/7/bol-high-court-1987.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }} and ''Khurshid Ahmad vs. The State'', [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf PLD 1992 Lahore 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314131726/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>Khan, Naveeda. [http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf \"Trespasses of the State: Ministering to Theological Dilemmas through the Copyright/Trademark\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605013014/http://anthropology.jhu.edu/Naveeda_Khan/Trespasses.pdf |date=5 June 2010 }}. Sarai Reader 2005: Bare Acts. p. 182.</ref> The ordinance, which was supposed to prevent \"anti-Islamic activities\", forbids Ahmadis to call themselves Muslim or to \"pose as Muslims.\" This means that they are not allowed to profess the Islamic creed publicly or call their places of worship [[mosque]]s. Ahmadis in Pakistan are also barred by law from worshipping in non-Ahmadi mosques or public prayer rooms, performing the Muslim [[Adhan|call to prayer]], using the traditional Islamic greeting in public, publicly quoting from the [[Qur'an]], preaching in public, seeking converts, or producing, publishing, and disseminating their religious materials. These acts are punishable by imprisonment of up to three years.<ref name=globalsecurity>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/intro/islam-ahmadi.htm \"Ahmadiyya Islam.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904122733/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/intro/islam-ahmadi.htm |date=4 September 2009 }} GlobalSecurity.org.  26 April 2005. Retrieved 14 December 2009.</ref> Ordinance XX and the 1974 amendment to the constitution effectively gave the state the exclusive right to determine the meaning of the term \"Muslim\" within Pakistan.\n\nMany Ahmadis were arrested within days of the promulgation of this ordinance, and it gave way for widespread sanctioned as well as non-sanctioned persecution.\n\nIn 1986 it was supplemented by a new [[blasphemy]] provision<ref name=\"Act III of 1986\">[[Pakistan Penal Code|PPC]] [http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f108 S. 295-C] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624115719/http://www.pakistani.org/pakistan/legislation/1860/actXLVof1860.html#f108 |date=24 June 2014 }}, inserted by [http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/10_c.html Criminal Law (Amendment) Act, 1986 (III of 1986)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218220810/http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/10_c.html |date=18 February 2014 }}</ref> also applied to Ahmadis.<ref>Cf. e.g. ''Khurshid Ahmad vs. The State'', [http://www.khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf PLD 1992 Lahore 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314131726/http://khatm-e-nubuwwat.org/lawyers/data/english/11/lahore-high-court-1992.pdf |date=14 March 2013 }}, para. 35</ref>\n\n===Shab Qadar incident===\nThe '''Shab Qadar incident''' was a public [[stoning]] of two members of the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] in the town of Shab Qadar, in the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|North-West Frontier Province]], [[Pakistan]] in April 1995.<ref name=amn>[[Amnesty International]] 8 April 1995, Human Rights Commission of Pakistan, [http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/pl_crimes.html page 82 of its Annual Report (1995)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926233626/http://www.thepersecution.org/archive/pl_crimes.html |date=26 September 2007 }}</ref> Dr. Rashid Ahmad and his son-in law, Riaz Ahmad Khan, were attacked as they were about to attend a court hearing in Shab Qadar. As they entered the court premises, a violent mob incited by local clerics attacked the men with sticks and stones. Riaz Khan was [[stoning|stoned to death]] and his dead body stripped and dragged through the town on a rope. Dr. Rashid Ahmad was taken to a hospital in [[Peshawar]] with serious injuries. A third Ahmadi, advocate Bashir Ahmad, escaped unhurt.<ref>\"Implementation of the declaration on the elimination of all forms of intolerance and of discrimination based on religion of belief\". Report submitted by Mr. Abdelfattah Amor, United Nations [[Special Rapporteur (UN)|Special Rapporteur]], in accordance with [[UN Commission on Human Rights]] Resolution 1995/23.</ref> This murder took place in front of the police. Riaz Khan even asked a police officer for help, but instead of helping, the officer pushed him away.<ref>''Plight of Ahmadi Muslims in Pakistan'', page 43</ref> According to Amnesty International, the police \"stood and watched,\" and \"...later pleaded that they could not have intervened in a situation like that.\" No one was detained or criminally charged for the killing.\n\nThe victims\u2014senior Ahmadiyya community members from Peshawar\u2014had come from the provincial capital to file a bail application for another Ahmadi Muslim, Daulat Khan. Daulat Khan had been harassed following his conversion to the sect. Local Muslim clergy reportedly called for his death. Daulat Khan had been arrested and imprisoned on 5 April 1995 under sections 107 (abetment) and 151 ([[Breach of the peace|disturbing the peace]] by joining in [[unlawful assembly]]) of the Penal Code. After the lynching of Rashid Ahmad and Riaz Ahmad Khan, Daulat Khan remained in custody and was further charged with posing as a Muslim and preaching Ahmadiyyat (section 298 C of the Penal Code) and insulting the religious sentiments of Muslims (section 295 A).<ref name=amn/>\n\n===2000===\nOn 30 October 2000, gunmen opened fire at an Ahmadiyya prayer meeting in the Pakistani province of Punjab, killing at least five worshippers and wounding another seven.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/998648.stm|title=Gunmen kill five at prayer meeting|date=30 October 2000|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=31 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404055758/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/998648.stm|archive-date=4 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2005===\n{{Main|2005 attack on Ahmadi mosque in Mandi Bahauddin}}\n\n\nIn a 2005 survey in Pakistan, pupils in private schools of Pakistan expressed their opinions on religious tolerance in the country. The figures assembled in the study reflect that even in the educated classes of Pakistan, Ahmadis are considered to be the least deserving minority in terms of equal opportunities and civil rights. In the same study, the teachers in these elite schools showed an even lower amount of tolerance towards Ahmadis than their pupils.<ref>[http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/pdsa/pdsa_01_01_04.pdf Peace and Democracy in South Asia], Volume 1, Number 1, January 2005. Passports to Privilege: The English-Medium Schools In Pakistan, Tariq Rahman.</ref> Ahmadis are harassed by certain schools, universities and teachers in Pakistan's [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province. The harassment includes social boycott, expulsions, threats and violence against Ahmadi students by extremist students, teachers and principals of the majority sect.<ref name=\"dawn-lightning\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/10/28/ahmadis-the-lightning-rod-that-attracts-the-most-hatred.html|title=Ahmadis: The lightning rod that attracts the most hatred|publisher=The Dawn|date=28 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October 2005, masked gunmen with [[Kalashnikov rifle]]s stormed a mosque belonging to the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community in a village called [[Mong, Punjab|Mong]] in District [[Mandi Bahauddin]], shooting dead eight people and wounding 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2005/10/07/welcome.htm|title=Eight dead in Pakistan's Ahmadi community's worship place attack|date=7 October 2005|publisher=dawn.com|access-date=31 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029171012/http://www.dawn.com/2005/10/07/welcome.htm|archive-date=29 October 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\nTwo prominent members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community were murdered on 8 and 9 September 2008 after a program by [[Aamir Liaquat|Aamir Liaquat Hussain]] provoking people to kill Ahmadis was aired on a prominent Pakistani television channel [[Geo TV]] a day earlier on 7 September.<ref name=\"Asian Human Rights Commission\">{{cite web|title=Two persons murdered after an anchor person proposed the widespread lynching of Ahmadi sect followers|url=http://www.humanrights.asia/news/urgent-appeals/AHRC-UAC-203-2008|publisher=Asian Human Rights Commission|date=10 September 2008|accessdate=12 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603203809/http://www.humanrights.asia/news/urgent-appeals/AHRC-UAC-203-2008|archive-date=3 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"archives.dawn.com\">{{cite news|title=KARACHI: Muttahida expels Aamir Liaquat|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2008/09/11/local4.htm|accessdate=20 February 2012|newspaper=Dawn|date=11 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201160841/http://archives.dawn.com/2008/09/11/local4.htm|archive-date=1 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nDuring the year 2009, eleven Ahmadis were killed, while numerous others became victims of attempted killings, according to a report titled \"Persecution of Ahmadis in Pakistan during the year 2009\" published by Nazarat Umoor-e-Aama Sadr Anjuman Ahmadia Pakistan. The report claimed that the actions of \"Ahmadi opponents\" had been encouraged largely by the prejudiced attitude of the authorities, and alleged that the federal government had been in denial of the human rights and religious freedom of the Ahmadis, especially the governments of Punjab and Azad [[Jammu and Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\\03\\12\\story_12-3-2010_pg7_42|title=11 Ahmadis killed during 2009: report|date=12 March 2009|publisher=dailytimes.com.pk|access-date=16 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317014536/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010%5C03%5C12%5Cstory_12-3-2010_pg7_42|archive-date=17 March 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n\n28 May 2010 saw the worst single incident of violence against Ahmadis to date (see [[May 2010 attacks on Ahmadi mosques in Lahore]]), when several members of an extremist religious group (allegedly [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan#Tehrik-i-Taliban Punjab|Tehrik-i-Taliban Punjab]]) entered two Ahmadi mosques in [[Lahore]] and opened fire; three of them later detonated themselves. In total, the attacks claimed the lives of 86 people and injured well over 100.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.alislam.org/egazette/press-release/clarification-86-ahmadis-died-in-the-lahore-attacks/ | title=Clarification \u2013 86 Ahmadis died in the Lahore attacks | publisher=Al Islam | date=12 June 2010}}</ref> The members were gathered in the mosques attending Friday services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/10181380.stm |work=BBC News | title=Pakistan mosque raids kill scores | date=28 May 2010}}</ref> In response to the attacks, Pakistan minister for minorities [[Shahbaz Bhatti]] visited the Ahmadi community.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n;April\n\nAround 10&nbsp;pm on 1 April 2010, three Ahmadis were returning home in their vehicle from their jewellery and cloth shops situated in Rail Bazaar in Faisalabad. As their car approached the Canal Road near Faisal Hospital, four or five unidentified militants in a white car ambushed them. The three Ahmadis were seriously injured when the men opened fire at them. The attackers managed to flee from the scene. The three men died before they reached the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\\04\\05\\story_5-4-2010_pg7_9|title=11 Ahmadis slam target-killings in Faisalabad |date=5 April 2010|publisher=dailytimes.com.pk}}</ref>\n\n;May Lahore attacks\n{{Main|May 2010 Lahore attacks}}\nOn 28 May 2010, two mosques in [[Lahore]] belonging to the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community were attacked by the [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan Punjab Wing]] (Punjabi Taliban). The attacks were carried out nearly simultaneously at Mosque Darul Al Zikr, Garhi Shahu and Mosque Bait Al Noor [[Lahore Model Town]], 15&nbsp;km apart. More than 90 people were killed and 108 were injured in the incident. One attacker was killed; another was captured by worshipers.<ref name=Jajja>{{cite news|last=Jajja|first=Sumaira|title=Three years on, no justice for 86 dead Ahmadis|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1014484/three-years-on-no-justice-for-86-dead-ahmadis|accessdate=25 April 2014|newspaper=Dawn|date=28 May 2013|quote=\"The 2010 Lahore incident is the only terrorist attack where the attackers were apprehended by the worshippers and handed over to the police,\" said Saleemuddin, spokesperson for the Ahmadiyya Jamaat Pakistan. <BR>In a polite but jaded tone he said the attackers were presented in an anti-terrorism court but nothing came of it.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426214951/http://www.dawn.com/news/1014484/three-years-on-no-justice-for-86-dead-ahmadis|archive-date=26 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three days later militants attacked the Intensive Care Unit of Lahore's Jinnah Hospital, where victims and one of the alleged attackers were under treatment. Twelve people, mostly police officers and hospital staff, were killed in the shootout. The assailants escaped.<ref name=HRW>{{cite web|title=Pakistan: Massacre of Minority Ahmadis|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2010/06/01/pakistan-massacre-minority-ahmadis|work=June 1, 2010|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=25 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409010817/http://www.hrw.org/news/2010/06/01/pakistan-massacre-minority-ahmadis|archive-date=9 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Pakistani government did nothing to prevent this; as of yet they have not set up protection for Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geo.tv/5-28-2010/65748.htm|title=Lahore attacks leave over 80 dead|date=28 May 2010|publisher=geo.tv|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531191210/http://www.geo.tv/5-28-2010/65748.htm|archivedate=31 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 28 May 2013 the two attackers captured had not been prosecuted, but early in 2015 courts took up the case and proceeded with sentencing.<ref name=Jajja/><ref name=HRW-procecute>{{cite web|title=Pakistan: Prosecute Ahmadi Massacre Suspects|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/05/27/pakistan-prosecute-ahmadi-massacre-suspects|work=May 27, 2012|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=25 April 2014|quote=Two men were captured during the attack, but the government has failed to make progress on their trial, seeking repeated adjournments from the court, as has the defense.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222045015/http://www.hrw.org/news/2012/05/27/pakistan-prosecute-ahmadi-massacre-suspects|archive-date=22 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=NewsweekP>{{cite web|url=http://newsweekpakistan.com/court-announces-death-sentence-for-ahmadi-attacker/|title=COURT ANNOUNCES DEATH SENTENCE FOR AHMADI ATTACKER|date=19 Jan 2015|publisher=newsweekpakistan.com|access-date=12 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326134203/http://newsweekpakistan.com/court-announces-death-sentence-for-ahmadi-attacker/|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2010, an Ahmadi was stabbed to death and his son seriously injured when an assailant climbed the wall of their house with a dagger and attacked them. The son later died in hospital from serious wounds. The attacker escaped. Residents say that the assailant threatened to not leave any Ahmadi alive after having found motivation to kill them through a sermon given by a local Sunni cleric.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/pakistan/provinces/04-ahmadi-stabbed-narowal-qs-07|title=Ahmadi man stabbed to death in Narowal|date=31 May 2010|publisher=dawn.com|access-date=31 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603024707/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/pakistan/provinces/04-ahmadi-stabbed-narowal-qs-07|archive-date=3 June 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\nOn 7 September 2011, the mainstream [[Urdu]] newspaper ''[[Daily Jang]]'' published a special edition against Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jhang's Special Anti-Ahmadiyya Edition|url=http://e.jang.com.pk/09-07-2011/Lahore/page8.asp|publisher=Jhang Group|accessdate=7 September 2011}}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThroughout the year, Ahmadi students and teachers in the Pakistan's [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province have been systematically persecuted by schools and universities. The harassment has included social boycott, expulsions, threats and violence by students, teachers and principals of the Muslim majority sect.<ref name=\"dawn-lightning\"/>\n\n====In education====\nAhmadi students faced discrimination in [[Pakistan]] in 2011 because of their faith.<ref name=\"dawn-lightning\"/>\n\n===2012===\nIn [[Faisalabad]], Quranic verses were removed from Ahmadi graves by the police.<ref>{{cite web|title=Avoiding clash in faisalabad: Police whitewash Quranic verses from Ahmadi graves|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/424061/avoiding-clash-in-faisalabad-police-whitewash-quranic-verses-from-ahmadi-graves/|publisher=Express Tribune|accessdate=21 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825145724/http://tribune.com.pk/story/424061/avoiding-clash-in-faisalabad-police-whitewash-quranic-verses-from-ahmadi-graves/|archive-date=25 August 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n3 December 2012, In Lahore over 100 tombstones at an Ahmadiyya graveyard in Lahore were desecrated in the wee hours of Monday by masked gunmen, who specifically targeted graves with Islamic inscriptions. They proclaimed themselves members of a banned organisation, and said the Ahmadiyyas had no right to use Quranic verses on their gravestones, as they \"are not Muslims.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/768598|title=Gunmen desecrate Ahmadi graves in Lahore|last=AFP|date=3 December 2012|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426060116/https://www.dawn.com/news/768598|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/grave-vandalism-highlights-plight-of-pakistans-ahmadiyyas/article4161102.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=Anita | last=Joshua | title=Grave vandalism highlights plight of Pakistan's Ahmadiyyas | date=4 December 2012 | access-date=6 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206010959/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/grave-vandalism-highlights-plight-of-pakistans-ahmadiyyas/article4161102.ece | archive-date=6 December 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nThe Human Rights Commission of Pakistan (HRCP) condemned the destruction of over 100 tombstones at an Ahmadi graveyard on Monday and demanded the arrests of those responsible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/474507/hrcp-condemns-desecration-of-ahmadi-graves/|title=HRCP condemns desecration of Ahmadi graves|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403220727/http://tribune.com.pk/story/474507/hrcp-condemns-desecration-of-ahmadi-graves/|archive-date=3 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Anti-Ahmadiyys sentiment in media====\n\n[[Islamic fundamentalism]] and [[Islamic extremism]] existed in the [[Media of Pakistan|Pakistani media]], causing them to start a hate campaign against Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-Ahmadi Pakistani media|url=https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/the-media-2012/|publisher=Persecution of Ahmads|accessdate=22 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224101646/https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/the-media-2012/|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\n'''7 January 2013:''' Four Ahmadi employees of Black Arrow Printing Press accused of publishing allegedly blasphemous books, were arrested as they loaded a small truck with thousands of books and CDs.<ref>om.pk/story/502777/ahmadi-literature-printing-press-employees-accused-of-blasphemy/</ref> On 13 February, an additional district and sessions judge on Tuesday rejected an application for after-arrest bail by four men accused of publishing allegedly blasphemous books about the Ahmadi faith.\n\n'''26 March 2013:''' Local clerics attacked a house belonging to an Ahmadi family in the Shamsabad, a village of Kasur district of Punjab on Tuesday and subjected the family members to violence allegedly over their religious belief.<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/526633/clerics-attack-ahmadi-house-torture-family-in-punjab/|title=Clerics attack Ahmadi house, torture family in Punjab|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530015357/http://tribune.com.pk/story/526633/clerics-attack-ahmadi-house-torture-family-in-punjab/|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The five members of Mansoor's family tried to take refuge in a room but the mob broke into the room as well. Mansoor was severely [[torture]]d, after which he lost consciousness, while his wife and his 70-year-old uncle were also beaten. Police personnel were reportedly present at the spot but took no action against the mob.<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\"/>\n\nInternational Human Rights Commission Punjab Director General Munawar Ali Shahid said, \"Several people here have told me that the Ahmadis had been socially boycotted for long. Police have taken no action to stop violence against them.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/531707/hostile-neighbours-ahmadis-will-be-always-vulnerable-says-sho/|title=Hostile neighbours: Ahmadis will be 'always vulnerable', says SHO|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://tribune.com.pk/story/531707/hostile-neighbours-ahmadis-will-be-always-vulnerable-says-sho/|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''30 April 2013:''' In Lahore, Gulshan-i-Ravi police arrested seven members of the Ahmadi community on Monday without an FIR, after close to 300 people protested in front of what was described as a place of worship of the community. A woman and her 10-year-old son were also arrested No, although no female members of the police accompanied them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/542170/neighbourly-acts-seven-ahmadis-detained-without-an-fir/|title=Neighbourly acts: Seven Ahmadis detained without an FIR|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://tribune.com.pk/story/542170/neighbourly-acts-seven-ahmadis-detained-without-an-fir/|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''8 May 2013:''' Members of the Khatm-e-Nabuwat Lawyers Forum (KNLF) (anti-Ahmadi activists) and police dragged five members of the Ahmadi community from an anti-terrorist court to a police station and detained them for several hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/545908/persecution-anti-ahmadi-group-targets-community-again/|title=Persecution: Anti-Ahmadi group targets community again|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730052417/http://tribune.com.pk/story/545908/persecution-anti-ahmadi-group-targets-community-again/|archive-date=30 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\n'''May 2014''': American-Canadian Doctor Mehdi Ali Qamar, was gunned down in Rabwah while visiting [[Punjab, Pakistan]] to help train local doctors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/26/canadian-doctor-mehdi-ali-qamar-gunned-down-as-he-visited-gravesite-in-pakistan-with-wife-and-son/|title=Canadian doctor Mehdi Ali Qamar gunned down as he visited gravesite in Pakistan with wife and son|author=Jennifer Hough|date=26 May 2014|work=National Post|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140527184047/http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/26/canadian-doctor-mehdi-ali-qamar-gunned-down-as-he-visited-gravesite-in-pakistan-with-wife-and-son/|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/27/world/asia/pakistan-american-doctor-killed/#cnn-disqus-area|title=Gunmen on motorbikes kill American doctor in Pakistan|author=Sophia Saifi, CNN|date=27 May 2014|work=CNN|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/27/world/asia/pakistan-american-doctor-killed/#cnn-disqus-area|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 100 Ahmadiyas took refuge in China after their lives were in danger in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/Persecuted-Pakistani-Muslim-minority-seek-refuge-in-China/articleshow/36805205.cms|title=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com is temporarily unavailable|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610111035/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/World/Pakistan/Persecuted-Pakistani-Muslim-minority-seek-refuge-in-China/articleshow/36805205.cms|archive-date=10 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Three members of the same family including one woman and two minors were killed and nine other people were injured when an angry mob set a house on fire in Arafat Colony, Gujranwala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/741943/three-including-two-minors-dead-in-gujranwala-clash/|title=Three Ahmadis, including two minors, killed in Gujranwala|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=8 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812140510/http://tribune.com.pk/story/741943/three-including-two-minors-dead-in-gujranwala-clash/|archive-date=12 August 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title=2015 Jhelum attacks\n|image=File:Pakistan - Punjab - Jhelum.svg\n|caption=Jhelum District, Pakistan\n|location=[[Jhelum]], [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n|target=\n|date=20-21 November 2015\n|time-begin=\n|time-end=\n|timezone=\n|type=[[Arson]]\n|publisher=\n|fatalities=0\n|injuries=\n}} On the Friday evening of 20 November 2015, a large mob, in an alleged case of [[blasphemy]], torched down a [[Particle board|chipboard]] factory, in [[Jhelum]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]. Ahmadi Muslim employees were accused of allegedly desecrating the [[Quran]]. The following day, rioters gathered in [[Kala Gujran]], a town bordering Jhelum, and set ablaze an Ahmadiyya mosque and a number of homes belonging to Ahmadi Muslims. Although no casualties have been reported, Ahmadi Muslims have been arrested, against whom a blasphemy case has been registered.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/30160622/mob-torches-factory-in-pakistan-following-blasphemy-accusation/ | title=Mob torches factory in Pakistan following blasphemy accusation | date=22 November 2015 | accessdate=22 November 2015 | publisher=Yahoo News | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123034009/https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/30160622/mob-torches-factory-in-pakistan-following-blasphemy-accusation/ | archive-date=23 November 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1221273/ahmadi-place-of-worship-set-ablaze-in-jhelum-riots-erupt-after-blasphemy-allegations | title=Ahmadi place of worship set ablaze in Jhelum, riots erupt after blasphemy allegations | date=21 November 2015 | accessdate=22 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122052156/http://www.dawn.com/news/1221273/ahmadi-place-of-worship-set-ablaze-in-jhelum-riots-erupt-after-blasphemy-allegations | archive-date=22 November 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nA mob of around 1,000 people besieged an Ahmadi place of worship in Chakwal and had to be dispersed by police. Deputy Commissioner Chakwal Mahmood Javed Bhatti said the mob hurled stones and bricks at the place of worship before storming the building, adding that gunmen opened fire on Ahmadis in the area. The DC said that police dispersed the crowd and secured the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1302057/mob-besieging-ahmadi-place-of-worship-in-chakwal-dispersed-by-police|title=Mob 'besieging' Ahmadi place of worship in Chakwal dispersed by police|first=AP &#124; Dawn.com &#124; Imran|last=Gabol|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511160712/https://www.dawn.com/news/1302057/mob-besieging-ahmadi-place-of-worship-in-chakwal-dispersed-by-police|archive-date=11 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn an address to the National Assembly, Captain Safdar Awan, the son-in-law of deposed PM Nawaz Sharif, demanded strict restrictions against Ahmadis, calling for complete curbs on Ahmadis in government, army, and private employment. He similarly questioned whether Ahmadis could be loyal to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/pakistan/complete-curbs-on-ahmadis-employment-demands-captain-r-safdar/|title=Nawaz Sharif's son-in-law calls for 'complete curbs' on Ahmadis|date=10 October 2017|publisher=Daily Pakistan|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010212527/https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/pakistan/complete-curbs-on-ahmadis-employment-demands-captain-r-safdar/|archive-date=10 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 12 October 2017, 3 Ahmadis were sentenced to death for blasphemy after tearing down posters that allegedly contained anti-Ahmadi slogans, though prosecutors argued the posters carried religious significance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/ahmadis-sentenced-death-blasphemy-171012081709423.html|title=Three Ahmadis sentenced to death for blasphemy|date=12 October 2017|publisher=Aljazeera|accessdate=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013020345/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/ahmadis-sentenced-death-blasphemy-171012081709423.html|archive-date=13 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October, an anti-Ahmadi rally attracted 10,000 people where Ahmadis were denounced as \"infidels\" and \"enemies of the state\". After a row regarding barriers to Ahmadi's participation in elections, the Pakistani government took out ads reaffirming a religious oath requiring elected officials to vow that they do not follow anyone claiming to be a prophet after Mohammad and \"nor do I belong to the Qadiani group\", using a common derogatory term for Ahmadis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-election-ahmadis/pakistans-long-persecuted-ahmadi-minority-fear-becoming-election-scapegoat-idUSKBN1DG04H/|title=Pakistan's long-persecuted Ahmadi minority fear becoming election scapegoat|date=16 November 2017|publisher=Reuters|access-date=17 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118062336/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-election-ahmadis/pakistans-long-persecuted-ahmadi-minority-fear-becoming-election-scapegoat-idUSKBN1DG04H|archive-date=18 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn 6 February 2018, the Azad Jammu and Kashmir Legislative Assembly (AJK-LA) and Kashmir Council approved an amendment declaring Ahmadis as non-Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/277827-ahmadis-are-not-muslims-decides-ajk|title=Ahmadis are not Muslims, decides AJK|date=7 February 2018|publisher=TheNews|access-date=7 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207182938/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/277827-ahmadis-are-not-muslims-decides-ajk|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.ajk.gov.pk/assets/lawlibrary/2019-02-14-5c647c81b020b1550089345.pdf|title=Interim Constitution (Twelfth Amendment) Act, 2018 (I of 2018)|last=|first=|date=https://law.ajk.gov.pk/lawlibrary|website=Law department AJ&K|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402172332/https://law.ajk.gov.pk/assets/lawlibrary/2019-02-14-5c647c81b020b1550089345.pdf|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020|quote=\u201c \u2018Muslim\u2019 means a person, who believes in the unity and oneness of Almighty Allah, in the absolute and unqualified finality of the Prophethood of Muhammad (peace be upon him), the last of the prophets, and does not believe in, or recognize as a prophet or religious reformer, any person who claimed or claims to be a prophet, in any sense of the word or of any description whatsoever, after Muhammad (peace be upon him);\u201d}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2018, Islamabad's High Court launched a judgement against Ahmadi Muslims and minorities which resulted in four major incidents against Ahmadis in Pakistan. The High Court ordered all citizens apply for any type of government job to declare their religious beliefs. Western human rights organisation have stated that this order is an attack on persecuted minorities in Pakistan, as well as a method to intercept Ahmadi politicians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-religion-law/in-blow-to-minorities-pakistani-court-orders-citizens-to-declare-religion-idUKKCN1GL28P|title=In blow to minorities, Pakistani court orders citizens to declare...|last=Sayeed|first=Saad|work=U.K.|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714193203/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-religion-law/in-blow-to-minorities-pakistani-court-orders-citizens-to-declare-religion-idUKKCN1GL28P|archive-date=14 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2018 a mob of several hundred people in [[Sialkot]], [[Pakistan]] attacked and demolished a historic and culturally significant 100-year-old Ahmadi mosque.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rabwah.net/pakistani-mob-attack-against-ahmadi-mosque-prompts-global-condemnation/|title=Pakistani mob attack against Ahmadi Mosque prompts global condemnation|website=www.rabwah.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712152805/https://www.rabwah.net/pakistani-mob-attack-against-ahmadi-mosque-prompts-global-condemnation/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Reports of collusion between the mob and local government officials were published, but police denied such accusations. A video on social media showed a crowd cheering on a local cleric who stated \"I want to thank the Sialkot administration, the DPO (District Police Officer), DC (District Commissioner), the TMA (Town Municipal Corporation), from the bottom of my heart\". The US, UK and international community strongly condemned this attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-ahmadis/pakistani-mob-destroys-100-year-old-minority-ahmadi-mosque-idUKKCN1IP20V|title=Pakistani mob destroys 100-year-old minority Ahmadi mosque|last=Sayeed|first=Saad|work=U.K.|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712155024/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-ahmadis/pakistani-mob-destroys-100-year-old-minority-ahmadi-mosque-idUKKCN1IP20V|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/mob-demolishes-mosque-belonging-to-ahmadi-sect-in-pakistans-sialkot-no-one-injured-4481991.html|title=Mob demolishes mosque belonging to Ahmadi sect in Pakistan's Sialkot, no one injured \u2013 Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=2018-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712165435/https://www.firstpost.com/world/mob-demolishes-mosque-belonging-to-ahmadi-sect-in-pakistans-sialkot-no-one-injured-4481991.html|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 June 2018, in a hate crime linked to the March 8 High Court judgement, an Ahmadi was killed in Nishtar Colony, Lahore.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/|title=Five Ahmedis shot, injured in two incidents \u2013 Daily Times|date=2018-07-09|work=Daily Times|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714221822/https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/|archive-date=14 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2018, five Ahmadi Muslims in Karachi, Pakistan were shot in two incidents of hate crime. Three were injured and two were killed. In the first attack, an Ahmadi couple were attacked in their home, the wife was shot in the thigh by attackers. In the second attack, Mubeen Ahmed, 20, was killed by robbers entering his office, and two colleagues were injured.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714221822/https://dailytimes.com.pk/264711/hate-crime-five-ahmedis-shot-injured-in-two-incidents/ |archive-date=14 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Persecution of Ahmadi students===\nAhmadi students have faced extremist persecutions because of their faith in most popular universities and colleges of [[Pakistan]] including [[University of Sargodha]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Perseuction of Ahmadi students|url=https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/problems-in-education-2011-2012/|publisher=Persecutions of Ahmadis students|accessdate=21 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224102454/https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/problems-in-education-2011-2012/|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Other countries==\n\n===Afghanistan===\n{{main|Ahmadiyya in Afghanistan}}\nPersecution of [[Ahmadis in Afghanistan]] began in the early 20th century within the lifetime of Ghulam Ahmad, the founder of the movement. Abdur Rahman, a disciple of [[Sahibzada Abdul Latif|Sayyid Abdul Latif]] of [[Khost]] \u2013 a reputable religious scholar who was the tutor and adviser on religious affairs to the Prince (later Amir) [[Habibullah Khan]] \u2013 visited [[Qadian]] upon the latter's instruction. Having stayed there in the company of Ghulam Ahmad for some time and having pledged allegiance to him he returned to Afghanistan where he began preaching against the common notion of Jihad as war. This information eventually reached the King, Amir [[Abdur Rahman Khan]], who had him arrested and he was later strangled to death while in prison. It is not clear however whether this was a state-sanctioned execution or simply murder. He is considered the first martyr of Ahmadiyya Islam.<ref>Adil Hussain Khan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"From Sufism to Ahmadiyya: A Muslim Minority Movement in South Asia\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204161834/https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=4 February 2017 }} Indiana University Press, 6 April 2015 p 130</ref>\n\nAbout two years later, Abdul Latif himself visited Qadian before starting on the [[Hajj]] (pilgrimage to Mecca) and stayed there for a few months also joining the Ahmadiyya movement before returning to Afghanistan in 1903 to proselytise to his King, Amir Habibullah Khan. Upon reaching Khost, he wrote to some courtiers who decided to have him arrested and brought to [[Kabul]]. He was put to trial and examined, first by the Amir, then by Sirdar Nasrallah Khan, another leading cleric, and then by a jury of twelve religious clerics, only two of whom gave a verdict of apostasy against him which carried the death penalty in Afghanistan. The Amir thus charged him with apostasy.<ref>Frank A. Martin. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qyIHswEACAAJ&dq=under+the+absolute+amir&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiz4IThtqbMAhUSOsAKHeC3DJYQ6AEIHTAA \"Under the Absolute Amir\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215022739/https://books.google.com/books?id=qyIHswEACAAJ&dq=under+the+absolute+amir&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiz4IThtqbMAhUSOsAKHeC3DJYQ6AEIHTAA |date=15 February 2017 }} Harper & Brothers, 1907 p 203-4</ref><ref>Adil Hussain Khan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"From Sufism to Ahmadiyya: A Muslim Minority Movement in South Asia\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204161834/https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=4 February 2017 }} Indiana University Press, 6 April 2015 p 131</ref>  On 14 July 1903, after being repeatedly asked to renounce his beliefs and recant and refusing to do so, he was stoned to death before a large crowd. Frank A. Martin, the English Engineer-in-Chief to the government of Afghanistan at the time, who had witnessed the execution, giving an account of it in his book ''Under the Absolute Amir'', writes:\n\n{{quote|Before being led away from the Amir's presence to be killed, the moullah [Abdul Latif] prophesied that a great calamity would overtake the country, and that both the Amir and the Sirdar would suffer. About nine o'clock at night the day the moullah was killed, a great storm of wind suddenly rose and raged with violence for half an hour, and then stopped as suddenly as it came. Such a wind at night was altogether unusual, so the people said that this was the passing of the soul of the Moullah. Then cholera came, and, according to former outbreaks, another visitation was not due for four years to come, and this was also regarded as part of the fulfillment of the moullah's prophecy, and hence the great fear of the Amir and the prince, who thought they saw in all this their own death and it accounts also for the prince losing control of himself when his favourite wife died.|Frank A. Martin|''Under the Absolute Amir'', {{ISBN|978-1-4304-9488-1}}, pg.204}}\n\nAhmadis see in the cholera epidemic that Kabul experienced within a month of the stoning, a sign of his and the movement's truth.<ref>Argument Number 10 \u2013 Prophecies: [http://www.alislam.org/books/invitation/arg10.html#L1 Prophecy No. 1: Afghan martyrs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422035834/http://www.alislam.org/books/invitation/arg10.html#L1 |date=22 April 2016 }}</ref>  By the 1920s, nearly ten Ahmadis were stoned to death in Afghanistan<ref>Adil Hussain Khan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"From Sufism to Ahmadiyya: A Muslim Minority Movement in South Asia\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204161834/https://books.google.com/books?id=C2DxBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=4 February 2017 }} Indiana University Press, 6 April 2015 p 133</ref> and it is reported that a total of about three Ahmadis had been executed in Kabul during this period.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} In the 1920s, King [[Amanullah Khan]] had several Ahmadiyya members forcibly reverted, and in 1924 affiliation with the Ahmadiyya became a capital offense.<ref>Vincent Littrell. [Islam: Ahmadiyya]. World Association of International Studies, 17 February 2006</ref> Since then, no Ahmadiyya Muslims have been reported in Afghanistan, but a possibility of their existence remains.<ref name=\"Friedmann\">Yohanan Friedmann: ''Prophecy Continuous: Aspects of Ahmadi Religious Thought and Its Medieval Background'', Oxford University Press India 2003, pg 26\u201329</ref>\n\n===Algeria===\n{{See also|Ahmadiyya in Algeria}}\nIn March 2016, Algerian authorities refused an attempt by Ahmadis to register as an association under Algerian law. In  June 2016, a planned Ahmadi mosque was raided and shut down in Larbraa. Since March 2016, more than 280 Ahmadis have been arrested and have faced prosecution.  Algerian officials have publicly called Ahmadis heretics and a threat to Algeria. In June 2016, The Minister of Religious Affairs and Endowments, Mohamed Aissa, described Ahmadi presence in Algeria as part of a \"prepared sectarian invasion\". In February 2017, he stated that Ahmadis are \"not Muslim.\" In April 2017, Ahmed Ouyahia, President Abdelaziz Bouteflika's chief of cabinet called on Algerians to \"preserve the country from the Shia and Ahmadiyya sects\".<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/06/algeria-wave-of-arrests-and-prosecutions-of-hundreds-of-ahmadis/ Algeria: Wave of arrests and prosecutions of hundreds of Ahmadis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829040729/https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/06/algeria-wave-of-arrests-and-prosecutions-of-hundreds-of-ahmadis/ |date=29 August 2017 }} Amnesty International. 19 June 2017</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\n{{Main|Ahmadiyya in Bangladesh|Freedom of religion in Bangladesh#Persecution of Ahmadis}}\nIn Bangladesh, Ahmadis have been targeted by various protests and acts of violence, and fundamentalist Islamic groups have demanded that Ahmadis be officially declared ''[[kafir]]s'' (infidels).<ref>Rahman, Waliur. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4556318.stm \"Violent Dhaka rally against sect\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228193136/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4556318.stm |date=28 December 2008 }} BBC News. 23 December 2005.</ref> Some adherents of Ahmadiyya have been subject to \"house arrest\" and several have been killed. In late 2003 several large, violent marches, led by Moulana Moahmud Hossain Mumtazi, were directed to occupy an Ahmadi mosque. In 2004, all Ahmadiyya publications were banned.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/ASA13/005/2004 \"Bangladesh: The Ahmadiyya Community \u2013 their rights must be protected\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930031155/http://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/ASA13/005/2004 |date=30 September 2012 }} Amnesty International. 22 April 2004.</ref>\n12 February 2019 Ahmadiyya Muslim community is attacked by Radical Islamist group in Bangladesh. ISIS claimed the attack.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bajwa |first1=Muzaffar Ahmad Noori |title=ISIS Attacks Ahmadiyyas in Bangladesh; Sheikh Hasina supports Islamists |url=https://www.easternherald.com/religion/persecution/isis-attacks-ahmadiyyas-in-bangladesh-wake-up-sheikh-hasina-44806/ |website=The Eastern Herald |accessdate=15 February 2019 |date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214025139/https://www.easternherald.com/religion/persecution/isis-attacks-ahmadiyyas-in-bangladesh-wake-up-sheikh-hasina-44806/ |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Belarus===\n{{See also|Islam in Belarus}}\nIn 2007, the Ahmadiyya Muslims were banned from practising their faith openly in the state of [[Belarus]] and given a similar status to other banned religious groups in the country. Unable to obtain state registration, Ahmadi Muslims in the country who number about 30 including 13 native Belarusians, cannot conduct their activities formally as a collectivity such as importing or distributing literature, gathering together for prayers or meetings and having an official representative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forum18.org/Archive.php?article_id=175 |title=Belarus: Ahmadiyya Muslims among banned religious organisations |publisher=Forum18.org |accessdate=2013-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422083243/http://www.forum18.org/archive.php?article_id=175 |archive-date=22 April 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n{{See also|Islamophobia in Belgium}}\nIn 2011 the far right party [[Vlaams Belang]] organized a demonstration against the projected building of an Ahmadi mosque in the [[Brussels]] municipality of [[Uccle]], allegedly out of fear for a \"war of religions\" between radical Sunnis and Ahmadis in the streets of the municipality.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} \"[http://archives.lesoir.be/le-vlaams-belang-manifeste-contre-la-construction-d-821_t-20111013-01M919.html Le Vlaams Belang manifeste contre la construction d\u2019une mosqu\u00e9e] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123083259/http://archives.lesoir.be/le-vlaams-belang-manifeste-contre-la-construction-d-821_t-20111013-01M919.html |date=23 January 2016 }}\", ''Le Soir'', 13 October 2011</ref>\n\n===Bulgaria===\nIn 2003, persistent attempts were made in [[Bulgaria]] by a local prosecutor and the national state Religious Affairs Directorate to  strip Ahmadi Muslims of their legal status. Ahmadis in Bulgaria, who (at the time) claimed some 400 members across the country, were refused registration as a religious community on the grounds that they were \"against the religions that people follow here\" and that \"other countries \u2013 such as Pakistan \u2013 also attack the religious freedom of Ahmadis, who are considered to be heretical by many Muslims\". Failing to obtain a legal status, the Ahmadiyya community decided to seek registration as a non-commercial organisation with the Blagoevgrad Regional Court, where one of its biggest congregations is based. This too was rejected on the grounds that \"the community had been denied registration as a religion\" and that \"only registered religious communities are allowed to create non-commercial entities to promote their faith\". However, the community was able to successfully challenge this latter decision and gained registration as such in December 2005. Subsequently, their legal status as a non-commercial organisation was again opposed by the Religious Affairs Directorate and the Regional Prosecutor's Office lodged a suit to the regional court calling for it to revoke the registration. The Bulgarian authorities citied the Pakistani government's legal measures against the Ahmadis as a reason to restrict their rights also. Most human rights and religious freedom activists have seen this denial of registration to the Ahmadi community as an exception.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forum18.org/archive.php?article_id=874|title=Bulgaria: Ahmadis barred \"because it is against the religions that people follow here\"|publisher=Forum18.org|accessdate=2016-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193647/http://www.forum18.org/archive.php?article_id=874|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Egypt===\n{{main|Ahmadiyya in Egypt}}\nThere has been a recent rise of persecution of Ahmadis in Egypt. In March 2010, nine Ahmadis were detained for allegedly insulting Islam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gz0txMsTCCfV4e0BI1Slg2yYOxFg|title=Egypt Ahmadis detained|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518171504/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gz0txMsTCCfV4e0BI1Slg2yYOxFg|archive-date=18 May 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Gambia===\n{{Main|Ahmadiyya in the Gambia}} \nSince its earliest history in the Gambia in the 1950s, Ahmadis have continued to face resistance and religious intolerance from certain Muslim clerics and Islamic bodies in the country. More recently, in 2014, a leading Gambian Muslim cleric, Alhaji Abdoulie Fatty, who was also the Imam of the [[State House of the Gambia]] at that time, called for the expulsion of Ahmadi Muslims from the country. Having described Ahmadi Muslims as non-Muslims, he called for a ban on the propagation of Ahmadiyya teachings in the Gambia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://standard.gm/site/news/5131-Imam-Fatty-says-Ahmadis-should-banned.html |title=Imam Fatty says Ahmadis should be banned |date=10 October 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2015 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jollofnews.com/index.php/national-news/human-rights/578-gambian-cleric-calls-for-the-expulsion-of-ahmadis |title=Gambian Cleric Calls For The Expulsion Of Ahmadis |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305174158/http://www.jollofnews.com/index.php/national-news/human-rights/578-gambian-cleric-calls-for-the-expulsion-of-ahmadis |archivedate=5 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> In January 2015, the government-financed [[Gambia Supreme Islamic Council]] aired on state television and other state and print media its decision to declare the Community, as a non-Muslim group.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201501262078.html | title=Gambia: Supreme Islamic Council States Position On Ahmadiya Jammat | publisher=AllAfrica | accessdate=11 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128164221/http://allafrica.com/stories/201501262078.html | archive-date=28 January 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The move was condemned by Baba Trawally, the Ameer (National President) of the Gambian Ahmadiyya community and Demba Ali Jawo, former president of the [[Gambia Press Union]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201502030968.html | title=Gambia: Ahmadiyya Reacts to Allegations | publisher=AllAfrica | accessdate=11 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204020431/http://allafrica.com/stories/201502030968.html | archive-date=4 February 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://thevoicegambia.com/2015/02/03/supreme-islamic-council-statement-poses-danger-to-national-cohesion/ | title=Supreme Islamic Council poses danger to national cohesion | publisher=The Voice Gambia | accessdate=11 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211131429/http://thevoicegambia.com/2015/02/03/supreme-islamic-council-statement-poses-danger-to-national-cohesion/ | archive-date=11 February 2015 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===India===\nIn India, Ahmadis are Muslims by law. This is supported by a verdict from the [[Kerala High Court]] on 8 December 1970 in the case of ''Shihabuddin Imbichi Koya Thangal vs K.P. Ahammed Koya'', citation ''A.I.R. 1971 Ker 206''.<ref name=hoque>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/law/2004/03/03/index.htm|title=On right to freedom of religion and the plight of Ahmadiyas|author=Hoque, Ridwanul|publisher=The Daily Star|date=21 March 2004|access-date=17 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531152751/http://www.thedailystar.net/law/2004/03/03/index.htm|archive-date=31 May 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In this landmark ruling, the court determined that Ahmadis are Muslims and that they cannot be declared apostates by other Muslim sects because they hold true to the two fundamental beliefs of Islam: that there is no god but [[Allah]] and that [[Muhammad]] is a messenger of God.<ref name=ik-1400223>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiankanoon.org/doc/1400223/|title=Shihabuddin Imbichi Koya Thangal vs K.P. Ahammed Koya on 8 December 1970|publisher=Indian Kanoon|quote=The various texts quoted in the ruling dispel doubts about Ahamadis on the crucial twin tests \"that there is no God but Allah ...............and Mohammad is the servant and Messenger of God.\"|accessdate=28 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805122439/http://www.indiankanoon.org/doc/1400223/|archive-date=5 August 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhile Ahmadis are considered Muslims by law and there are no legal restrictions on their religious activities,<ref name=\"hoque\"/> they are not permitted by fellow Muslims of other sects to sit on the [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]], a body of religious leaders that the Indian government recognises as representative of [[Islam in India|Indian Muslims]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/weekly/jawed/20080109.htm |title=Religious violence hastens India's leap into deeper obscurantism |publisher=Dawn |author=Naqvi, Jawed |date=1 September 2008 |accessdate=23 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123072127/http://dawn.com/weekly/jawed/20080109.htm |archivedate=23 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====2008====\n[[Ahmadis]] were denied permission to meet in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] because of the protests from the Islamic groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmadiya community denied permission for Hyderabad meet|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni10.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230650/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni10.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Permission for Hyderabad Ahmadiyya meet cancelled|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni15.html|publisher=Perseuction.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230656/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/yni15.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liberty abridged  The Pioneer Edit Desk Ahmadiyas are Indians, too|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/pio18.html|publisher=Perseuction.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230643/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/06/pio18.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 19 August 2008 Islamic cleric named Maulvi Habib-ur-Rehman incited hatred for the people in a rally. On the night of 21/22 August 2008, three Ahmadis were attacked. Their properties were damaged. In all, six persons were attacked.<ref>{{cite web|title=Religious fanatics attack Ahmadis' houses in Saharanpur, Uttar Pradesh, India; six persons injured|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/08/pr27.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201230700/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/08/08/pr27.html|archive-date=1 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2009====\nIn [[Chennai]], the body of a 36-year-old Ahmadi woman of the community was exhumed and desecrated by \"anti-social elements\" from a graveyard. at Royapettah on 1 June. [[Ahmadis]] alleged the police intervention in this issue. They did a press conference. They told the detailed of the incident and persecution faced by Islamic clerics. [[Madras High Court]] has ruled that Ahmadis are Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exhumation annoys Ahmadiyya sect|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/06/eb08.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609232955/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/06/eb08.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Muslims led by Shahi Imam Habib-ur-Rehman Sani protested against [[Jalsa Salana]]. Muslims all across the state have joined hands in the protests. Indian finance minister [[Pranab Mukerjee]] was likely to attend the Jalsa Salana. Muslims damaged his office and blocked the traffic for stopping the annual convention of Ahmadis. Police imposed [[curfew]] for three days. Many people were injured and one [[Sikh]] died. When the convention was held, the protestors presented anti-Ahmadiyya document to the chief commissioner to be forwarded to [[Prakash Singh Badal]]. The protest was organized in all the big mosques of [[Punjab region|Punjab]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmadiyya convention faces heat|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/12/ti25.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610031037/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/09/12/ti25.html|archive-date=10 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nIslamic clerics threatened the [[Mayawati]] government to remove mentions of the Ahmadiyya sect from the [[syllabus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Should The Mayawati Government Remove Ahamadiyya Sect From Syllabus|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/10/08/nb28.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130155009/http://thepersecution.org/world/india/10/08/nb28.html|archive-date=30 November 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2011====\nIn [[Mumbai]], [[Darul Uloom Deoband]] had asked [[Saudi Arabia]]'s government to ban [[Ahmadis]] from doing [[Hajj]]. The spokesperson said that [[Ahmadis]] do not believe in the finality prophethood therefore they cannot do [[Hajj]]. They sent a letter to the government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Darul Uloom asks Saudi Arabia to ban Ahmadiyas from Mecca visit|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/06/ti30.html|publisher=Perseuction.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207225251/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/06/ti30.html|archive-date=7 February 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nIn [[New Delhi]], [[Ahmadis]] faced protests from rival Muslim sects for attempting to preach their religion. They faced protests from the [[Muslims]] of [[India]]. [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]]'s members were also among the protesters. [[Ahmadis]] changed the timings of the convention. [[Maulana Bukhari]] and his protestors were detained in a police station for protesting against this.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmadiyyas face protest at peace mission|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ti24.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129060726/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ti24.html|archive-date=29 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Exhibition on teachings of Quran denounced|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/th24.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609233050/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/th24.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fearing row, Bukhari detained|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ht24.html|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609230431/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/ht24.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Delhi: Quran exhibition called off after protests|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/zn24.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609221839/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/09/zn24.html|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Heretical' Ahmadiyya sect raises Muslim hackles|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/10/ht02.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129060743/http://www.thepersecution.org/world/india/11/10/ht02.html|archive-date=29 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nIn February 2012, the Andhra Pradesh Wakf Board took a series of unprecedented decisions and asked the Qazis in the state not to perform [[Nikah]] for those belonging to Ahmadiyya community.<ref>\n{{cite web |url = http://www.siasat.com/english/news/don%E2%80%99t-perform-nikaah-qadiyanis-ap-wakf-board-qazis | title=Don\u2019t perform nikaah of Qadiyanis: AP Wakf board to Qazis |publisher=Siasat Urdu Daily, Hyderabad | author=Courtesy: Two Circles | date=20 February 2012 | accessdate=10 March 2012}}\n</ref>\n\nIn [[Hyderabad]], an [[anti-Ahmadiyya]] mob attacked the mosque and said to stop the prayers. They also threw stones at the mosque.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mosque attacked|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-26/hyderabad/31239516_1_mosque-prayers-ahmadis|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=21 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224095922/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-26/hyderabad/31239516_1_mosque-prayers-ahmadis|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesia===\n{{Main|Persecution of Ahmadis in Indonesia}}\n\nPublic opinion in Indonesia is split into two major views on how Ahmadiyya should be treated:\n* Majority of Muslims throughout Indonesia hold that it should be banned outright on the basis that Ahmadiyah rejected the central tenet of Islam that Muhammad is the last messenger of God; furthermore, Ahmadis should not use Islam as their banner but should constitute their own recognised religion in order to ensure their freedom of religion in Indonesia\n* Some minorities including Ahmadis and numerous non-governmental organizations hold that Ahmadiyya should be free to act and say as it pleases under the banner of Islam in keeping with the Constitutional right of freedom of religion.\nIn June 2008, a law was passed to curtail \"proselytising\" by Ahmadiyya members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466&size=A | title=Indonesia to ban Ahmadi activities | publisher=AsiaNews.IT | date=6 September 2008}}</ref> An Ahmadiyya mosque was burned.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YIGJhKLhpE4 | title=Anti-Ahmadiyya Mullah Burning Ahmadiyya Mosques \u2013 Indonesia | publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> Human rights groups objected to the restrictions on religious freedom. On 6 February 2011 some Ahmadiyya members were killed at [[Pandeglang]], [[Banten]] province.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html |title=Six killed in clash between villagers and Ahmadiyah followers |work=The Jakarta Post |date=6 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827070711/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html |archivedate=27 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the past few years there has been an increase in attacks on religious freedom, including incidents of physical abuse, preventing groups from performing prayers, and burning their mosques. Data from the Setara Institute for Democracy and Peace show 17, 18, and 64 incidents for the years 2008, 2009 and 2010 respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2011/feb/18/indonesia-pluralism-persecution-ahmadiyah | title=Indonesia is no longer a poster child for pluralism | author=Gillian Terzis |work=The Guardian  | date=18 February 2011}}</ref> Although the data cover persecution of all religions, the recent persecution of Ahmadis is significant and severe, followed by persecution of Christians and persecution of other Islamic sects who claim to be \"genuine/pure/fundamentalist Muslims\".\n\nAs of 2011, the sect faces widespread calls for a total \"ban\" in Indonesia.<ref>McGeown, Kate. \"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-13155924 Islamic sect Ahmadiyah faces ban in Indonesia]\" ''[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]]''. 21 April 2011. (Video)</ref> On 6 February 2011, hundreds of mainstream Muslims surrounded an Ahmadiyya household and beat three people to death. Footage of the bludgeoning of their naked bodies \u2013 while policeman looked on \u2013 was posted on the internet and subsequently broadcast on international media.<ref>Allard, Tom. [http://www.smh.com.au/world/trial-begins-after-shocking-mob-violence-ends-in-slaying-20110426-1dv37.html Trial begins after shocking mob violence ends in slaying]. ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. 27 April 2011.</ref>\n\n====2008====\nIn 2008, many Muslims in [[Indonesia]] protested against the Ahmadiyya movement. With violence and large demonstrations, these religious conservatives put pressure on the government to monitor, and harass the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community in Indonesia.<ref>[http://new.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466 Indonesia to ban Ahmadi activities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724170308/http://new.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466 |date=24 July 2009 }}, 06/09/2008</ref> Public opinion in Indonesia is split in three ways on how Ahmadiyya should be treated: (a) some hold it should be banned outright on the basis that it is a heretical and deviant sect that is not listed as an officially recognised religion in Indonesia; (b) others hold that it should not be banned because of the freedom of religion article in the Constitution, but also should not be allowed to proselytise under the banner of \"Islam\" on the basis that this is misleading; (c) still others hold that it should be free to do and say as it pleases based on the Constitutional right to freedom of religion.<ref>\"[http://markings-reflections.blogspot.com/2008/04/indonesia-shadows-over-freedom_30.html= Ahmadiyya Ban and Human Rights]\", Fazil Jamal on Jakarta Post {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In June 2008, a law was passed to curtail \"proselytizing\" by Ahmadiyya members.<ref>''[http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466&size=A Indonesia to ban Ahmadi activities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724170308/http://new.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=12466 |date=24 July 2009 }}'', AsiaNews.IT</ref>{{Better source|reason=see WP:RSN|date=April 2015}}  An Ahmadiyya mosque was burned.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YIGJhKLhpE4 Anti-Ahmadiyya Mullah Burning Ahmadiyya Mosques \u2013 Indonesia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725063436/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YIGJhKLhpE4 |date=25 July 2015 }}, Al Jazeera News Report</ref> Human rights groups objected to the restrictions on religious freedom.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSJAK90261 Indonesia's religious tolerance under threat-group] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624190737/http://www.reuters.com/article/latestcrisis/idusjak90261 |date=24 June 2009 }}, 10 June 2008.</ref> A government decree adopted in 2008 under pressure from Islamic conservatives bans the sect from spreading its faith.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_631949.html|title=Religious clash in Indonesia kills up to six, Straits Times, 6 Feb 2011|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209031134/http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_631949.html|archive-date=9 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\n\nIn July 2010, a mob of 200 Indonesians surrounded an Ahmadi mosque in [[Manislor]] village in [[Kuningan district]], [[West Java]]. The mob pelted the mosque with stones before being dispersed by the police.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2010/07/2010729151640257216.html Indonesia mob attacks Muslim sect] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805042105/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2010/07/2010729151640257216.html |date=5 August 2010 }}. Al Jazeera English.  29 July 2010</ref>\n\n====2011====\nOn 6 February 2011 three (originally reported as six, and later amended) Ahmadiyya members were killed at [[Pandeglang]], [[Banten]] province, in a clash between locals.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=6 February 2011|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html|title=Six killed in clash between villagers and Ahmadiyah followers|accessdate=17 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827070711/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/six-killed-clash-between-villagers-and-ahmadiyah-followers.html|archivedate=27 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While the government did instruct police to hunt the killers, it also called on Ahmadiyya to abide by the 2008 decree and stop spreading their belief.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=6 February 2011|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/govt-instructs-police-hunt-killers-calls-ahmadiyah-abide-decree.html|title=Govt instructs police to hunt killers, calls on Ahmadiyah to abide by decree|accessdate=17 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208212025/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/02/06/govt-instructs-police-hunt-killers-calls-ahmadiyah-abide-decree.html|archive-date=8 February 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011 the prosecuting sought sentences of between five and seven months for the defendants, an act that caused outcry by rights activists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/activists-cry-foul-at-lenient-prosecutors-in-ahmadiyah-trial/451544 |title=Activists Cry Foul at 'Lenient' Prosecutors in Ahmadiyah Trial |work=[[The Jakarta Globe]] |author=Elisabeth Oktofani & Chrestella Tan |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=28 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810223656/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/activists-cry-foul-at-lenient-prosecutors-in-ahmadiyah-trial/451544 |archive-date=10 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The verdict given was between three and six months, slightly lighter than sought. This has trigger criticism from human right defenders and the international community including the US and the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/29/cikeusik-verdict-%E2%80%98chilling%E2%80%99-message-minorities.html |title=Cikeusik verdict 'chilling' message to minorities |work=thejakartapost.com |accessdate=29 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012131741/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/29/cikeusik-verdict-%E2%80%98chilling%E2%80%99-message-minorities.html |archivedate=12 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In addition, a Cikeusik Ahmadi leader, Deden Darmawan Sudjana, was also sentenced to six months in prison for physical abuse and acts against the state, refusing an order from a police officer who told him to leave the house.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/08/15/cikeusik-ahmadi-leader-gets-6-months-prison.html |title=Cikeusik Ahmadi leader gets 6 months prison |date=15 August 2011 |access-date=16 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111212124034/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/08/15/cikeusik-ahmadi-leader-gets-6-months-prison.html |archive-date=12 December 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A US State Department spokeswoman said they were \"disappointed\" with the verdict, while an activist of the New York-based [[Human Rights Watch]], called it \"the [[Taliban]]ization of Indonesia\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.kompas.com/read/2011/08/16/05051048/The.Reason.Why.US.Disappointed.with.Indonesia.Court.Ruling |title=The Reason Why US 'Disappointed' with Indonesia Court Ruling |date=16 August 2011 |access-date=16 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007174944/http://english.kompas.com/read/2011/08/16/05051048/The.Reason.Why.US.Disappointed.with.Indonesia.Court.Ruling |archive-date=7 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\nIn April 2009, the Selangor Islamic Religious Council of Malaysia issued a letter that forbade members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community from offering [[Jumah|Friday prayers]] at their central mosque. Moreover, Ahmadis failure to comply with the order would result in imprisonment of up to one year and/or a fine up to 3000 Malaysian [[ringgit]]. A large notice outside the mosque states ''Qadiani Bukan Agama Islam'', which translates to ''Qadiani [Ahmadiyyat] is not Islam.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenutgraph.com/mais-forbids-ahmadiyya-worship/|title=MAIS forbids Ahmadiyya worship|publisher=thenutgraph|accessdate=26 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113150119/http://www.thenutgraph.com/mais-forbids-ahmadiyya-worship|archive-date=13 January 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/press/09/my090428.html|title=ISLAMIC COUNCIL IN MALAYSIA ISSUES NOTICE TO AHMADIYYA MUSLIM JAMAAT PREVENTING USE OF CENTRAL MOSQUE|publisher=thepersecution|accessdate=26 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023024929/http://www.thepersecution.org/press/09/my090428.html|archive-date=23 October 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Palestine===\n{{main|Ahmadiyya in Palestine}}\nAhmadis were reported to be persecuted in the Palestinian Authority-controlled areas in 2010.<ref name=it0706>{{cite web|url=http://www.israeltoday.co.il/default.aspx?tabid=178&nid=21250|title=Palestinian Muslims who reject violence are persecuted|work=israeltoday.co.il|access-date=24 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201709/http://www.israeltoday.co.il/default.aspx?tabid=178&nid=21250|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, Mohammed Sharif Odeh, head of the Ahmadi community in Israel, told Arutz Sheva radio that the Palestinian Authority is \"encouraging the cold-blooded murder of Ahmadis\" by failing to take concrete action to protect the community.<ref name=it0706/>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\n{{Main|Ahmadiyya in Saudi Arabia|Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia}}\nAhmadis are persecuted in [[Saudi Arabia]] on an ongoing basis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Persecution of Ahmadis in Saudi Arabia|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/press/08/sp080324.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> In a 2006\u20132007 nationwide campaign to track down and deport Ahmadi Muslim foreign workers, the Saudi religious police arrested 56\u201360<ref>Depending on the source there were 56\u201360 Ahmadis arrested in the years 2006\u20132007</ref> Although there are many foreign workers and Saudi citizens belonging to the Ahmadiyya sect in Saudi Arabia,<ref name=\"hrw2014\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/05/15/saudi-arabia-2-years-behind-bars-apostasy-accusation | title=Saudi Arabia: 2 Years Behind Bars on Apostasy Accusation | date=15 May 2014 | publisher=Human Rights Watch | accessdate=1 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304153400/http://www.hrw.org/news/2014/05/15/saudi-arabia-2-years-behind-bars-apostasy-accusation | archive-date=4 March 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2007/90220.htm | title=Saudi Arabia: International Religious Freedom Report 2007 | publisher=U.S. Department of State | accessdate=7 March 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/resources/AR_2007/saudi_arabia.pdf | title=Saudi Arabia | publisher=United States Commission on International Religious Freedom | accessdate=7 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720220618/http://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/resources/AR_2007/saudi_arabia.pdf | archive-date=20 July 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Persecution of Ahmadis in Saudi Arabia|url=http://www.thepersecution.org/press/08/sp080324.html|publisher=Persecution.org|accessdate=11 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223210226/http://www.thepersecution.org/press/08/sp080324.html|archive-date=23 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Ahmadis are officially banned from entering the country and from performing the [[Hajj]] and [[Umrah]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].<ref name=\"Figueira\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=heIft-h0aRcC&pg=PA47&dq=&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dCoyVZ2PLZTXapSngIAM&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Jihad in Trinidad and Tobago, July 27, 1990 | author= Daurius Figueira | page=47}}</ref><ref name=\"B\u00f6wering\">{{cite encyclopaedia | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q1I0pcrFFSUC&pg=PA25&dq&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ew00VcVfg_Zq7Z6ByAg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Princeton Encyclopedia of Islamic Political Thought | author=Gerhard B\u00f6wering, Patricia Crone | page=25-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tuVhBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&dq&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HnHzVPqLM8HOaNvugfgB&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The State as an Actor in Religion Policy: Policy Cycle and Governance | author=Maria Grazia Martino | accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2007, [[Human Rights Watch]] sent an open letter to the [[King of Saudi Arabia|Saudi king]] [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]] asking him to cease religious persecution of the Ahmadi faith in Saudi Arabia. Two letters were sent in November 2006 and February 2007 asking him to remove the travel ban on critics of the Saudi government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hrw.org/english/docs/2007/02/09/saudia15305.htm|title=Letter to King Abdullah|work=HRW|date=8 February 2007|accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Saudi authorities arrested two Saudi Sunni Muslim citizens for their conversion to Ahmadiyya Islam.<ref>U.S. Department of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor, [https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/208622.pdf International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Saudi Arabia] (20 May 2013).</ref> They were arrested three months after joining the Ahmadiyya and refusing to abandon their beliefs. As of May 2014, the two accused of apostasy had served two years in prison awaiting trial. They have not been released since then.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/May-15/256556-hrw-urges-saudi-to-free-two-ahmadis-held-for-apostasy.ashx#axzz3BwArkFYL HAW urges Saudi to free two Ahmadis held for apostasy], The Daily Star, Lebanon News (15 May 2014).</ref><ref name=\"hrw2014\"/>\n\n===Singapore===\n{{Main|Persecution of Ahmadis in Singapore}}\n\n===United Kingdom===\n\nAhmadis in the UK have endured killings, mass protests by other Muslims against Ahmadi mosque construction,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/dec/08/ahmadi-mosque-walsall-protests|title=Freedom of worship for Ahmadis|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=8 December 2010|date=8 December 2009|location=London|first=Inayat|last=Bunglawala}}</ref> and threats and intimidation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hate-leaflets-calling-killing-ahmadi-muslims-distributed-across-london-1553591|title=Hate leaflets calling for killing of Ahmadi Muslims distributed across London|first=Tom|last=Porter|date=8 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>  In March 2016, the [[First Minister of Scotland]], [[Nicola Sturgeon]], attended the wake of an Ahmadi, Asad Shah, 40, killed by a Sunni, Tanveer Ahmed, 32, in what the police characterised as \"religious prejudice\".<ref>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/asad-shah-nicola-sturgeon-joins-7631680#61qK6RXGmriEduSA.97 Asad Shah: Nicola Sturgeon joins 500 people at vigil as defiant locals declare 'This is not who we are'] dailyrecord.co.uk 25 March 2016.</ref> In April 2016, leaflets calling for death to Ahmadis were found in Stockwell Green mosque.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35928848|title='Kill Ahmadis' leaflets found in UK mosque \u2013 BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/25/muslim-council-of-britain-ahmadi-asad-shah|title=The Muslim Council of Britain is failing Ahmadis like Asad Shah|date=2016-04-25|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref> The mosque claimed that it was unaware of the leaflets being placed on its premises. The leaflets were authored in the name of an ex-head, [[Muhammad Yusuf Ludhianvi|Yusuf Ludhianvi]], of [[Khatme Nubuwwat Academy|Khatam-e-Nabuwwat (or Khatme Nabuwwat)]] \u2013 an anti-Ahmadiyya organization. The organization is fully known as Almi Majlis-e-Tahafuz Khatmi Nubuwat or the International Committee for the Protection of the Finality of Prophethood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.albalagh.net/current_affairs/yusuf_ludhianvi.shtml|title=Renowned Scholar Maulana Yusuf Ludhianvi Martyred in Karachi|website=www.albalagh.net|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\n====2009====\nIn 2009 a demonstration consisting of mainly Muslims was held in [[Walsall]] to prevent Ahmadis acquiring a mosque.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/dec/08/ahmadi-mosque-walsall-protests|title=Freedom of worship for Ahmadis|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=8 December 2010|date=8 December 2009|location=London|first=Inayat|last=Bunglawala|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908182840/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/dec/08/ahmadi-mosque-walsall-protests|archive-date=8 September 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nIn 2010, in the wake of the [[May 2010 attacks on Ahmadi mosques in Lahore|May 2010 attacks]] on two Ahmadi mosques in Lahore, Pakistan, members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community living in the UK were threatened and intimidated. Certain Muslim groups in [[South London]] distributed leaflets asking readers to kill Ahmadis and boycott their businesses, and Ahmadi mosques in Crawley and Newham were vandalised. In October 2010 [[Ofcom]] criticised the UK-based [[Ummah Channel]] for broadcasting three interactive television programmes before and after the Lahore massacre of Ahmadi Muslims in May 2010, in which religious leaders and callers alike said that Ahmadis should be killed. These programmes were repeated several times. Ofcom stated that the programme's abusive treatment of the religious views and beliefs of members of the Ahmadiyya community breached UK broadcasting regulations.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hardliners-call-for-deaths-of-surrey-muslims-2112268.html|title=Hardliners call for deaths of Surrey Muslims|publisher=The Independent|date=21 October 2010|accessdate=21 October 2010|location=London|first=Jerome|last=Taylor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606052751/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hardliners-call-for-deaths-of-surrey-muslims-2112268.html|archive-date=6 June 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ahmadiyya Debate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=6641|title=Ahmadiyya Debate|publisher=Parliament of United Kingdom|accessdate=22 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725130152/http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=6641|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNasser Butt, a [[Liberal Democrat (United Kingdom)|Liberal Democrat]] parliamentary candidate for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election]] was targeted by a campaign that asked Muslims not to vote for him because of his faith. In the election, hustings in the Tooting Islamic centre, a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate, Mark Clarke, was mistaken for Butt and had to be locked in a room for his safety.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/ahmadiyya/8451614.Election_race_infected_by_anti_Ahmadiyya_hate_campaign/ | title=Tooting election race infected by anti-Ahmadiyya hate campaign | accessdate=5 April 2011 | date=14 October 2010 | publisher=Wimbledon Guardian | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021061949/http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/ahmadiyya/8451614.Election_race_infected_by_anti_Ahmadiyya_hate_campaign/ | archive-date=21 October 2010 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nImam Suliman Gani, of the (Sunni) Tooting Islamic Centre, called for a boycott of Ahmadi shops, stating: \"Since the Qadianis are routinely deceptive about their religion, there was a potential risk of Muslims being offered meat that wasn't necessarily halal.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oakes|first1=Omar|title=Worshippers told at Tooting Islamic Centre to boycott Ahmadiyya shops|url=http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/8451539.Worshippers_told_to_boycott_Ahma%20diyya_shops/|accessdate=10 August 2016|work=Wimbledon Guardian|issue=14 October 2010|quote=Ahmadi shopkeepers face financial ruin after clerics demanded a boycott of their shops.  Imam Suliman Gani, of the TIC, admitted he personally pleaded with the owner of the Lahore Halal Meat in Tooting not to sell his business to an Ahmadi man.  He said: \"Since the Qadianis are routinely deceptive about their religion, there was a potential risk of Muslims being offered meat that wasn't necessarily halal.\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812111659/http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/8451539.Worshippers_told_to_boycott_Ahma%20diyya_shops/|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n\n=====Murder of Asad Shah=====\nIn March 2016, an Ahmadi Scottish shopkeeper [[Asad Shah]] was stabbed to death in Glasgow after wishing people a Happy Easter on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/uk/337257-scottish-muslim-shopkeeper-killed/|title=Muslim shopkeeper who wrote loving Easter posts stabbed to death in 'religiously prejudiced' attack|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510102836/https://www.rt.com/uk/337257-scottish-muslim-shopkeeper-killed/|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The [[Daily Mail]] reported:  \"police suspect the incident was 'religiously prejudiced' and have arrested a 32-year-old Muslim man belonging to the rival Sunni sect over the murder.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3512546/Police-investigating-murder-Asad-Shah-seized-Uber-taxi.html|title=Police investigating murder Asad Shah have seized an Uber car|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510155347/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3512546/Police-investigating-murder-Asad-Shah-seized-Uber-taxi.html|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 29 March 2016, the murderer's name was revealed as Tanveer Ahmed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-35918547 | title=Asad Shah death: Man in court charged with murder | publisher=BBC | date=29 March 2016 | accessdate=29 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329152741/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-35918547 | archive-date=29 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>  On 6 April 2016, Tanveer Ahmed stated \"that he killed Asad Shah,\" and claimed \"if I had not done this others would\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cramb|first1=Auslan|title=Man from Bradford admits killing Glasgow shopkeeper Asad Shah|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/06/man-from-bradford-admits-killing-glasgow-shopkeeper-asad-shah/|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=6 April 2016|quote=said it was because he \"disrespected\" Islam.   Tanveer Ahmed, 32, said in a statement that he killed Asad Shah, 40, claiming: \"if I had not done this others would\".|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408082452/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/06/man-from-bradford-admits-killing-glasgow-shopkeeper-asad-shah/|archive-date=8 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  An Ahmadi anti-extremism campaign was launched in Glasgow, with attendance of Ahmadi Muslims, Christian, Sikh, and Jewish leaders, but no Muslims belonging to other sects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/apr/18/scottish-muslim-groups-ahmadi-anti-extremism-campaign-launch-glasgow|title=Scottish Muslim groups fail to attend Ahmadi anti-extremism event|first=Libby Brooks Scotland|last=correspondent|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|via=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328100118/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/apr/18/scottish-muslim-groups-ahmadi-anti-extremism-campaign-launch-glasgow|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The murderer pleaded guilty to the \"religiously-motivated murder.\"  Part of the family of the victim is emigrating away from Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-37021385|title=Asad Shah killing: 'Disrespecting Islam' murderer jailed|date=9 August 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|via=www.bbc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314112440/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-37021385|archive-date=14 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=====Hate leaflets=====\nIn April 2016, leaflets were distributed across London's universities, mosques and shopping centres, calling for the killing of Ahmadis. The leaflets were by [[Muhammad Yusuf Ludhianvi]], with the [[Khatme Nubuwwat Academy|Khatme Nubuwwat organisation]] on the front cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hate-leaflets-calling-killing-ahmadi-muslims-distributed-across-london-1553591|title=Hate leaflets calling for killing of Ahmadi Muslims distributed across London|first=Tom|last=Porter|date=8 April 2016|accessdate=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415034819/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hate-leaflets-calling-killing-ahmadi-muslims-distributed-across-london-1553591|archive-date=15 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\n\nIn October 2017, [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[File on 4]]'' programme investigated the publication and broadcasting of anti-Ahmadiyyah material in the UK, and asked when and whether media regulators should intervene.<ref name=\"BBC File on 4 2017\">{{cite episode| title= Extremism: Hidden in Plain Sight| episodelink= | series= [[File on 4]]| credits= Presenter: [[Manveen Rana]]; Producers:  Richard Fenton-Smith & Sajid Iqbal; Editor: Gail Champion | network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b096hczb | airdate= 3 October 2017| accessdate= 3 October 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\n\n[[Muslim Television Ahmadiyya International|MTA International]] has produced four documentaries regarding the persecution of [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] over the last century.\n* The Early Years\n* 1953\n* 1974\n* 1984 \u2013 present (2008)\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[Ummah Channel]], broadcast three interactive programs against Ahmadis in the wake of [[May 2010 attacks on Ahmadi mosques in Lahore|Lahore massacre]]<ref name=\"Taylor\" /><ref name=\"Ahmadiyya Debate\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/whall/?id=2010-10-20a.284.0|title=Ahmadiyya Community, Westminster Hall Debate|publisher=TheyWorkForYou.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026214828/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/whall/?id=2010-10-20a.284.0|archive-date=26 October 2010|accessdate=28 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[Ofcom]] criticized [[Ummah Channel]] for doing this.\n\nA UK-based [[Urdu]] TV station, namely Channel 44, was fined by [[Ofcom]] on 15 April 2019 for hate speech and for being \u201canti-ahmadi\u201d. As a result, Channel 44 was fined \u00a375,000 amid growing fears of the persecution of Ahmadis.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murphy|first=Simon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/15/uk-based-tv-station-channel-44-fined-anti-ahmadi-muslim-hate-speech|title=UK-based TV station fined for anti-Ahmadi Muslim hate speech|date=15 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/816434/annual-report-18-19.pdf|title=Ofcom Annual report 2018-2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Ofcom GOV UK|page=33|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724080645/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/816434/annual-report-18-19.pdf|archive-date=24 July 2019|access-date=2 April 2020|quote=We are currently considering imposing sanctions for other serious breaches. These include: prolonged hate speech against the Ahmadiyya community which was not justified by the context (broadcast on Channel 44)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tobitt|first=Charlotte|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/ofcom-fines-channel-44-city-news-network-75000-for-hate-speech-against-ahmadiyya-community/|title=Ofcom fines UK Urdu-language news channel \u00a375,000 for 'hate speech' against Muslim group|date=15 April 2019|work=Press Gazette|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-Ahmadiyya organisations==\nPolitical groups associated with the persecution of the [[Ahmadis]] include the [[Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam]], [[Khatme Nabuwwat]] movements<ref>{{cite book | first1=Ala | last1=Al-Hammarneh | first2=Jorn | last2=Thielmann | title=Islam and Muslims in Germany | page=317 | publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |date=January 2008}}</ref> ([[Majlis-e-Tahaffuz-e-Khatme Nabuwwat]], [[Pasban Khatme Nabuwwat]], [[Tanzeem-e-Islami]] and Tehreek-e-Khatme Nabuwwat), [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]], [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan]] and [[Tehreek-i-Labbaik Pakistan]].<ref>Saeed, S. (2007), Pakistani Nationalism and the State Marginalisation of the Ahmadiyya Community in Pakistan. Studies in Ethnicity and Nationalism, 7: 132\u2013152. {{doi|10.1111/j.1754-9469.2007.tb00166.x}}</ref>\n\n==Leaders of groups associated with the persecution of Ahmadis==\n* [[Maulana Sanaullah Amratsari]], Fateh Qadyan (conqueror of Ahmdiyya)\n* [[Syed Ata Ullah Shah Bukhari]], founder of Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam\n* [[Syed Abuzar Bukhari]], former president of majlis-e-ahrar\n* [[Muhammad Yusuf Ludhianvi]], leader of Khatm-e-Nubuwwat\n* Abdul Latif Khalid Cheema, Secretary General of Majlis-e-Ahrar-e-Islam\n* [[Agha Shorish Kashmiri]], editor of chattan\n* [[Janbaz Mirza]], editor of tabsarah\n\n==Discrimination and pejorative terms by Muslims==\n\n===Terms===\n[[Qadiani]] and [[Mirzai]] are the pejorative terms used by non-Ahmadi Muslims from the Indian subcontinent.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Islamic schools and branches]]\n*[[Sectarian violence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Religious persecution}}\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/ Website about persecution of Ahmadis]\n*[http://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/MunirInquiry-Report-Urdu.pdf Justice Munir Enquiry Report on Anti-Ahmadiyya riots of 1953 (Urdu)]\n*[http://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/Munir-Inquiry-Report-English.pdf Justice Munir Enquiry Report on Anti-Ahmadiyya riots of 1953 (English)]\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/category/pakistan/ Persecution of Ahmadis in Pakistan]\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/facts-in-figures/ Facts and Figures]\n*[https://www.persecutionofahmadis.org/martyrs/ Pictures of those Martyred in 1974]\n*[http://www.alislam.org/egazette/press-release/ahmadis-murdered-for-their-faith-in-pakistan-during-2009/ Ahmadis Murdered During 2009]\n* 8 part [[Muslim Television Ahmadiyya International|MTA]] series ''1974 \u2013 From Democracy to Extremism'': [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GEzYkgThDBY 1] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z8H2J_2hFn8 2] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qiXRURLpV2U 3] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2JpfolM-NHI 4] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j_B1Vfn3xg8 5] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KC7dwF6c3Ck 6] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z4gd690TG_Y 7] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LQTnp57kOmc 8] (2013)\n*{{YouTube|CBg0pf9vxio|Solid Eveidence of political interference against Ahmadiyya Jammat in 1974}}\n\n{{Religious persecution}}\n\n{{Ahmadiyya topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Persecution Of Ahmadis}}\n[[Category:Persecution of Ahmadis| ]]\n[[Category:Islam in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Islam in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Islam in India]]\n[[Category:Islam in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Persecution by Muslims]]\n\n[[de:Ahmadiyya#Verfolgung]]\n", "name_user": "Taimoorahmed11", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persecution_of_Ahmadis"}
